1. --
{ Welcome to the course!   Here you will find a practical and ambitious repertoire against all the major 1.d4 systems ranging from the dubious and obscure Hübsch Gambit to serious mainline alternatives such as the London system, where White can try and play for an advantage.    The latter, in particular, has had a big surge in popularity even at the very top level. This is not that surprising given that, in this day and age of computer preparation, a lot of the mainlines have been worked out to forced draws.    While some of these systems are unambitious or outright bad, I urge you not to underestimate the more serious ones. White can try and use clever move orders to steer the game into relatively unexplored positions where he is often more familiar with the typical plans and ideas. Fear not, I have paid close attention to move order tricks and found a lot of new ideas for Black, so you will most likely be the one surprising your opponents with my recommendations. There are well over 100 theoretical novelties in the course!  Notwithstanding, I’ve done my very best to punish incorrect play by the first player and outright refute dubious gambits. I’m particularly proud of my recommendation against the Blackmar-Diemer Gambit, which should put it out of business once and for all.   My aim in this course was to recommend lines that not only neutralize White's ambitious lines but also allow you to fight for the full point. I've taken the liberty of assuming you want to play for a win with Black wherever possible, particularly when White plays unambitiously or essays dubious gambits. This doesn't mean you'll have to learn 1000 variations to get a complete repertoire. On the contrary, I have also made every effort to make this repertoire practical and easy to learn.   To this point, I have used the Important lines feature, which you can enable in the course options tab. I also added three Quickstarters with a selection of the absolutely most important lines.  The course is compatible with all of Black’s main defenses to 1.d4, including antidotes to all the major 1.d4 systems for   -1…d5 players @@StartBracket@@i.e. QGD, QGA, Slav, and Ragozin players@@EndBracket@@   -1…Nf6 2…e6 players @@StartBracket@@that’s you, Nimzo/QID/Bogo-Indian players@@EndBracket@@   -1…Nf6 2…g6 players @@StartBracket@@hello KID and Grunfeld fans@@EndBracket@@   This structure is similar to the one Avrukh used in his excellent book GM Repertoire: Beating 1.d4 sidelines, which is now almost a decade old and thus completely out of date.  The next three informational lines contain a roadmap listing the relevant chapters for1…d5, 1…Nf6 2…e6, and 1…Nf6 2…g6 players.  The total number of variations for each is around 150  (around 60 of which are marked as important)  .  It is virtually impossible to make a course compatible with all of Black’s defenses to 1.d4 2.c4. For example, Chigorin players will not find complete antidotes to all the d4 systems White can throw at them. In those  @@StartBracket@@few cases@@EndBracket@@, you will have to do your own research @@StartBracket@@or alternatively learn a better defense against 1.d4 2.c4!@@EndBracket@@.   I was frustrated by the lack of proper coverage of d4 systems in Chessable courses and in the larger chess literature. These systems often receive a few pages at the end of a book or are an afterthought in most Chessable courses, where the authors spend most of their time on the mainlines. I found the existing coverage to be very incomplete and to contain many dubious recommendations where Black not only does not equalize but is actually considerably worse after the opening.  I spent countless hours meticulously analyzing these systems with the latest versions of the revolutionary neural network engines, Stockfish and Leela Zero, running on very fast cloud servers. You will find a whole array of improvements over the current theory and more than 100 novelties.  Apart from checking the latest version of the Mega Database, I also made extensive use of correspondence games and made sure to check the most popular lines at the club level using the Lichess database. I’ve made every effort to cover lines you are likely to encounter and avoided dedicating a lot of lines to options you’ll rarely if ever see on the board.   Finally, throughout the course, you will find coverage of new lines and plans that White has yet to employ in practice but I believe are likely to be played in the future based on suggestions by the NNUE engines. Nowadays, I strongly believe it is paramount to not only cover what are currently the main theoretical battlegrounds but also try and predict where theory is likely to head. This should help you stay ahead of the curve and confidently face even the most well-prepared opponents.   As in all my courses, you can count on a high level of support. I will promptly answer any questions you have and regularly update the course with new theoretical developments. }
*

