{ The following lists the relevant chapters for 1...Nf6 2...e6 players. If you play the Nimzo/QID/Bogo-Indian against 1. d4, this is for you!  The repertoire clashes are detailedhere.  The 50 most important lines can be found in theQuickstarter. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3
{ 2.Bf4  e6  3.Nf3  d5  leads to the London system, which is covered via the 1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. Nf3 e6 move order inchapter 7.   2.Bg5  The Trompowsky is covered inchapter 11. I recommend meeting it with  2...d5  Although infrequent, it is possible for White to play  3.Nf3  This transposes to the Torre which is covered via the 1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bg5 move order inchapter 4.   2.Nc3  d5  3.Bf4  The Jobava Attack is covered inchapter 6 via the 1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 move order.   3.Bg5  The Veresov is covered inchapter 5 via the 1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 move order.   Against  3.e4  you can either play  3...Nxe4  which is the easiest way to punish this gambit. It is covered inchapter 10 on the Hübsch Gambit.   OR instead play  3...dxe4  which transposes to the Blackmar-Diemer gambit, covered in chapter 9 via the 1. d4 d5 2. e4 move order. The latter is less practical/requires learning more theory.   2.e3  e6  3.Bd3  d5  4.f4  The Stonewall system is covered inchapter 12.   I recommend meeting  2.g3  with  2...d5  when  3.Nf3  c5!  transposes tochapter 8.   Rare options such as  2.d5  ,  2.g4  ,  2.f4  ,  2.b4  ,  2.Nd2  ,  2.c3  and  2.f3  are covered inchapter 24. }
2... e6 3. Bg5
{ The Torre is covered inchapter 14.   3.Nc3  d5  is covered inchapter 16.   3.Nbd2  is also covered inchapter 16.   3.c3  c5  4.Bg5   4.Nbd2  transposes to the Colle system, which is covered inchapter 13.  4...d5  transposes to the Torre, covered inchapter 14.   3.Bf4  is another way to reach the London system, which is covered via the 1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. Nf3 e6 move order inchapter 7.   3.e3  The Colle system is covered inchapter 13.   3.g3  The g3 system is covered inchapter 15. }
