{ The following lists the relevant chapters for 1...Nf6 2...g6 players, i.e. players whose main defenses against 1. d4 are the King's Indian or the Grunfeld.  The repertoire clashes are detailedhere.  The 70 most important lines can be found in theQuickstarter. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3
{ 2.Bg5  The Trompowsky is covered inchapter 11. I recommend meeting it with  2...d5  Although infrequent, it is possible for White to play  3.Nf3  This transposes to the Torre which is covered via the 1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bg5 move order inchapter 4.   2.Nc3  d5  3.Bf4  The Jobava Attack can simply be met with  3...g6  which transpose to the London system. Refer tochapter 20 for the details.   3.Bg5  The Veresov is covered inchapter 5 via the 1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 move order.   Against  3.e4  you can either play  3...Nxe4  which is the easiest way to punish this gambit. It is covered inchapter 10 on the Hübsch Gambit.   OR instead play  3...dxe4  which transposes to the Blackmar-Diemer Gambit that is covered inchapter 9 via the 1. d4 d5 2. e4 move order. The latter is less practical/requires learning more theory.   2.g3  is not theoretically dangerous but can be used to move order you out of your repertoire. The easiest is to meet it with  2...d5  when  3.Nf3  c5!  transposes tochapter 8. White has zero chances for an advantage here and you only need to learn 10 trainable variations.   Rare options such as  2.d5  ,  2.g4  ,  2.f4  ,  2.b4  ,  2.Nd2  ,  2.c3  and  2.f3  are covered inchapter 24. }
2... g6 3. Bf4
{ The London system is covered inchapters 20 and21.   3.Bg5  The Torre is covered inchapter 18.   3.c3  Bg7  4.Bg5  transposes to the Torre, which is covered inchapter 18.   4.Nbd2  is also covered inchapter 18.   3.Nc3  d5  4.Bg5  The Barry attack is covered inchapter 19.   4.Bf4  transposes to the London system, which is covered inchapter 20.   3.e3  The Colle is covered inchapter 17.   3.g3  The g3 system is covered inchapter 22. }
