1. d4 d5 2. Bf4
{ 2.Nc3  Nf6  3.Bf4  was recommended by GM Simon Williams in the Chessable course 'The Jobava London System'. The specific clash occurs after  3...e6  4.e3  Bb4  5.Bd3  c5  6.dxc5  Nbd7  7.Nge2  a6  8.Bg3  Here I recommend  8...Bxc5!  which GM Simon Williams did not consider. This is also stronger than 8...Nh5, which was recommended by GM Sam Shankland in the Lifetime Repertoire: Semi-Slav. Black can count on a significant advantagehere.   2.Bg5  The Pseudo-Trompowsky was recommended by FM Marko Makaj in the Chessable course 'Calm & Collected: 1.d4'.  2...f6  After this move, deep analysis indicates White @@StartBracket@@no typo!@@EndBracket@@ is already struggling to maintain the balance.  3.Bd2  is Marko's recommendation. He missed an important deviation on move 7, after which White is under pressure. I found the title of his course very appropriate as White needs to indeed remain calm. Any further inaccuracy will result in a clear disadvantage for the first player. The details can be foundhere.   2.e4  dxe4  3.Nc3  Nf6  4.f3  The Blackmar-Diemer gambit, which I tackle with  4...exf3  5.Nxf3  g6  The neural network engines' top choice, which puts the gambit out of business. A powerful innovation on move 12 that was not considered in the 'The Blackmar-Diemer Gambit' book by Christoph Scheerer nor in IndrekR's Chessable course 'Blackmar-Diemer for Blitz'  gives Black a clear advantage. Check out the detailshere.   2.e3  Nf6  3.Bd3  c5  4.c3  Nc6  5.f4  The Stonewall system was recommended by IM Yaacov Norowitz and NM Elijah Logozar in the Chessable course 'The Yaac Attack'. They stopped their analysis after 2 more moves, stating that White is 'significantly worse' @@StartBracket@@yes that's a direct quote!@@EndBracket@@. I prove this statement is accuratehere.   2.Nf3  Nf6  3.g3  The 3. g3 system was recommended in the Chessable course 'Keep it Simple: 1. d4' by IM Christof Sielecki. I tackle it with  3...c5  which gives Black a great game with minimal knowledge required. The specific clash occurshere.   2.Nf3  Nf6  3.e3  The Colle system was recommended by GM Milos Pavlovic in the book 'The Modernized Colle-Zukertort Attack ' and by GM Aaron Summerscale and Sverre Johnsen in the book 'A Killer Chess Opening Repertoire'. I propose tackling this system with  3...c5  The specific clash with Pavlovic's and Summerscale's analysis occurshere. }
2... Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Nd2
{ 4.c3  Bd6  5.Bxd6  Qxd6  6.f4  was recommended by GM Simon Williams in the Chessbase FritzTrainer 'The London System with 2.Bf4'. The specific clash occurshere.   4.Nf3  Bd6  5.Nbd2  was recommended in the Chessable course 'The London System: Essential Theory' by IM John Bartholomew and FM Daniel Barrish. However, they failed to consider the natural  5...O-O  The details can be foundhere.  6.c3  c5  7.Ne5  was recommended in the Chessable course 'The London Attack' by IndrekR. The specific clash occurshere where Black enjoys a good game. }
4... Bd6 5. Bg3 O-O 6. Bd3 c5 7. c3 Qc7
{ is my recommended setup vs the London system, which was  not covered in the book 'Winning with the Modern London System' by GM Nikola Sedlak nor in 'The Agile London System' by GM Alfonso Romero Holmes and FM Oscar de Prado Rodriguez. The details can be foundhere. }
