1. --
{ Almost all the lines in the course are the result of original analysis with the latest versions of Stockfish and Leela running on very fast cloud servers.   I made extensive use of correspondence and high-level OTB games. I also paid close attention to the most popular replies at the club level by checking the Lichess online database.  I addressed the recommendations in all the recent books, DVDs, and Chessable courses recommending various d4 systems  (refer to the repertoire clashes files for more details)  .   The course has a similar structure to the book 'GM Repertoire: Beating 1. d4 Sidelines' by GM Boris Avrukh. However, almost all the recommendations are different and far stronger, which is not surprising when you consider that this book is from 2013.   Engines: latest versions of Stockfish and Leela Chess  Databases: MegaDatabase, CorrBase, Lichess database  Books/DVDs/Courses:  -Aaron Summerscale and Sverre Johnsen, A Killer Chess Opening Repertoire, Gambit, 2010  -Alfonso Romero Holmes and Oscar de Prado, The Agile London System, Chessable course  -Boris Avrukh, GM Repertoire: Beating 1. d4 Sidelines, Quality Chess, 2013  -Christoph Scheerer, The Blackmar-Diemer Gambit, Everyman Chess, 2011  -Cristof Sielecki, Keep it Simple: 1. d4, Chessable course  -Dmitry Kryakvin, Play the Trompowsky Attack, Chess Stars, 2018  -Graham Burgess, A Cunning Chess Opening Repertoire for White, Gambit, 2013  -IndrekR, Blackmar-Diemer for Blitz, Chessable course  -John Bartholomew and Daniel Barrish, The London system: Essential theory, Chessable course  -Kamil Plichta, Break the rules: Play the Trompowsky, Chessable course  -Levy Rozman, D4 Dynamite, Online course  -Marko Makaj, Calm & Collected: 1.d4, Chessable course  -Milos Pavlovic, The Modernized Colle-Zukertort Attack, Chessable course  -Nikola Sedlak, Winning with the Modern London system Vols. 1 and 2, Chess Evolution, 2016  -Simon Williams, The Jobava London system, Chessable course  -Simon Williams, The London System with 2.Bf4, Chessbase FritzTrainer, 2019  -Richard Pert, Playing the Trompowsky, Quality Chess, 2013  -Yaacov Norowitz and Elijah Logozar, 'The Yaac Attack', Chessable course }
