{ Welcome to the Quickstarter! Here you'll find the 50 most important lines covering all the major d4 systems for 1...d5 players. }
1. d4 d5 2. e3
{ is typically an indication White is aiming for the Stonewall. He can also transpose into the Colle by playing Nf3 later on. }
2... Nf6 3. Bd3 { My recommendation is } 3... c5
{ immediately pressuring the center. } 4. c3 Nc6 5. f4
{ The Stonewall system. White takes firm control over the e5 square with f2-f4. White wants to plant a knight on e5 and then start a kingside attack with Qe1-h4. However, I'm sure the bishop on c1 isn't too happy with the way White arranged his pawns.  White doesn't score very well with the Stonewall at either master or club level, especially after }
5... Bg4
{ Developing the bishop outside the pawn chain before playing ...e6 is very logical. The bishop is very active here and after White plays Nf3, the knight will be pinned. This will make it harder for White to jump into e5. }
6. Nf3
{ This was recommended in the Chessable course 'The Yaac Attack' by IM Yaacov Norowitz and NM Elijah Logozar. They stopped their analysis here, saying and I quote: 'It must be said that White is objectively significantly worse in this position.' This assessment is 100% accurate.  I must commend the authors for first finding and, secondly, daring to recommend a system for White where they are significantly worse after 6 moves. That's quite a rare feat in chess literature! Sarcasm aside, we will continue for a few more moves to see exactly why White is already considerably worse. }
6... e6 7. O-O { 7.Nbd2  Bd6  transposes to the text after 7. O-O Bd6 8. Nbd2 }
7... Bd6 8. Nbd2
{ is inaccurate as it allows   Alternatively  8.h3  Bf5  9.Bxf5  exf5∓  leaves White with a backward pawn on e3. }
8... cxd4
{ when White's desirable recapture with exd4 is not available since the f4 pawn would then drop. }
9. cxd4 { The desirable recapture  9.exd4?  drops the f4 pawn to  9...Bxf4∓ }
9... O-O
{ with 8...cxd4 we managed to open the c-file in our favor, which we're ready to exploit with ...Nb4 and ...Rc8 next. A sample continuation is }
10. Qe1 Nb4 11. Bb1 Rc8
{ Black followed up with ...Nc2 and had a big advantage, which he easily converted into a full point in 0-1 @@StartBracket@@47@@EndBracket@@ Norowitz,Y @@StartBracket@@2420@@EndBracket@@ - Boyer,M @@StartBracket@@2302@@EndBracket@@ Chess. com INT 2020. This game is analyzed in themodel games chapter. }
