1. d4 d5 2. e3
{ is typically an indication White is aiming for the Stonewall. He can of course transpose into the Colle by playing Nf3 later on. }
2... Nf6 3. Bd3 c5 { immediately pressuring the center. } 4. c3 Nc6 5. f4
{ The Stonewall system. White takes firm control over the e5 square with f2-f4. White wants to plant a knight on e5 and then start a kingside attack with Qe1-h4. However, I'm sure the bishop on c1 isn't too happy with the way White arranged his pawns.  White doesn't score very well with the Stonewall at either master or club level, especially after }
5... Bg4
{ Developing the bishop outside the pawn chain before playing ...e6 is very logical. The bishop is very active here and after White plays Nf3, the knight will be pinned. This will make it harder for White to jump into e5. }
6. Nf3
{ This was recommended in the Chessable course 'The Yaac Attack' by IM Yaacov Norowitz and NM Elijah Logozar. They stopped their analysis here, saying and I quote: 'It must be said that White is objectively significantly worse in this position.' This assessment is 100% accurate.  I must commend the authors for finding and recommending a system for White where they are significantly worse after 6 moves. That's quite a rare feat in chess literature! Sarcasm aside, we will continue for a few more moves to see exactly why White is already considerably worse. }
6... e6 7. O-O { 7.Nbd2  Bd6  transposes to the text after 7. O-O Bd6 8. Nbd2 }
7... Bd6 8. Qe1 { An excellent counter is } 8... Bf5
{ which is Black's second most popular continuation OTB and Stockfish's top choice. In online games, it's only 4th most common and 7 times less seen than the dubious 8...Bxf3?!, which is the most frequent move according to the Lichess database.  The idea behind 8...Bf5 is to swap off White's light-squared bishop, leaving him with a bunch of weaknesses along this color complex. }
9. Bxf5
{ Keeping the tension with  9.Qe2  is examined in detail in the main theoretical section of the course. You can check it outhere. }
9... exf5
{ After the exchange of light-squared bishops, we have complete control over the e4 square and White's light squares are critically weak. }
10. Nbd2 O-O 11. Ne5 Qc7
{ is very favorable for Black. We can jump into e4 at any point and then expel White's knight on e5 with ...f6.   A sample continuation is  12.Qe2  Rac8  13.Ndf3  Ne4  14.Bd2  Rfe8∓  Next up is ...f6 with a clear advantage for Black. }
