1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3
{ The Colle system, also known as the Colle-Koltanowski system, is named after the Belgian masters Edgard Colle and George Koltanowski.    Characterized by the moves 2. Nf3 and 3. e3, White usually develops his light-squared bishop to d3, the queenside knight to d2, and tries to engineer the pawn break e3-e4. White typically reinforces the d4 pawn with c2-c3 in response to …c5, setting up a triangle or pyramidal pawn structure with pawns on f2, e3, d4, c3, and b2.    Nowadays, this variation is considered innocuous as it does not put any pressure on the center and restricts White’s dark-squared bishop. It is a popular system at the club level mainly because it can be learned very quickly and is of very low maintenance.   White's setup is definitely solid but also very unambitious. }
3... c5
{ is both principled and very practical, immediately fighting for the center. I always felt there was no need to go for 3...e6, which has a lot more theory and leads to stale positions where it is difficult to play for a win. }
4. Nbd2 { A flexible move, keeping options open. } 4... cxd4
{ is the simplest, defining the pawn structure right away and thus avoiding any move order trickery. }
5. exd4 Nc6 6. Bb5
{ has been played a few times. White's idea is to play c4 and try to undermine our knight on c6 with Qa4 and Ne5. }
6... Qb6
{ is the most incisive reply. It was not considered by Milos Pavlovic in 'The Modernized Colle-Zukertort Attack', first published as a book in 2019 and later converted into a Chessable course. }
7. c4 g6
{ Black need not react to what White is doing and can simply continue development. }
8. Qa4 { 8.Ne5  is met with  8...Nd7= } 8... Bd7 9. Ne5
{ White got in all the moves he wanted but achieved very little. } 9... Nxe5
{ starts a series of exchanges } 10. dxe5 Bxb5 11. Qxb5+
{ Worse is  11.cxb5?!  Nd7  12.Nf3  Nc5∓  when the b5 pawn drops. } 11... Qxb5
12. cxb5 Nd7
{ is a very pleasant endgame for Black. White's pawns on e5 and b5 are nothing but targets. }
