1. d4 d5 2. Bg5
{ This early bishop development is known as the Pseudo-Trompowsky. This variation has also been called the Levitsky Attack, named after the Russian GM and 1911 Russian Champion Stepan Levitsky. It has also been dubbed the Hodgson Attack as it was played extensively by English GM Julian Hodgson. Other names for this variation are the Queen's Bishop Attack or simply the Bishop attack.    White’s main idea behind  2.Bg5  is to meet  2...Nf6  with  3.Bxf6  damaging Black’s kingside pawn structure.   This theme is analogous to one of the mainlines of the Trompowsky variation @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.Bg5  d5  3.Bxf6  exf6  However, unlike the Trompowsky, our knight is not yet on f6. This is a crucial difference, enabling us to instead immediately knock back White’s bishop with }
2... f6
{ After this move, White @@StartBracket@@no typo!@@EndBracket@@ is already struggling to maintain the balance. }
3. Bf4 { The engines are already claiming White is worse after this retreat. }
3... Nc6 4. e3 { does nothing to prevent us from pushing ahead with } 4... e5
5. Bg3 exd4 { opens the e-file in Black's favor. } 6. exd4 Qe7+
{ immediately exploiting the open e-file. } 7. Qe2 { drops the d4 pawn. After }
7... Nxd4 8. Qxe7+ Nxe7
{ White has no time for Bxc7 since the c2 pawn is hanging. Black is thus a clean pawn up. }
