[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bg5
{ This early bishop development is known as the Pseudo-Trompowsky. This variation has also been called the Levitsky Attack, named after the Russian GM and 1911 Russian Champion Stepan Levitsky. This variation has also been dubbed the Hodgson Attack as it was played extensively by English GM Julian Hodgson. Other names for this variation are the Queen's Bishop Attack or simply the Bishop attack.  White’s main idea behind 2. Bg5 is to meet 2...Nf6 with 3. Bxf6, damaging Black’s kingside pawn structure.   This theme is analogous to one of the mainlines of the Trompowsky variation @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.Bg5  d5  3.Bxf6  exf6  However, unlike the Trompowsky, our knight is not yet on f6. This is a crucial difference, enabling us to instead immediately knock back White’s bishop with }
2... f6
{ After this move, White @@StartBracket@@no typo!@@EndBracket@@ is already struggling to maintain the balance. }
3. Bd2
{ I recall reading somewhere that after Bd2 White was successful in provoking the 'weakening move' ...f6 and the bishop is slightly better placed on d2 than on c1. The neural network engines strongly disagree with this statement as the evaluation bar is already dipping below zero. Here's why: 1@@EndBracket@@ ...f6 is a useful move preparing the ...e5 central break 2@@EndBracket@@ White's bishop actually stands worse on d2 than on c1 as it's in the way of other pieces, for example blocking the White queen from protecting the d4 pawn. }
3... Nc6
{ Hitting the d4 pawn and preparing the ... e5 pawn break. It's clear the bishop on d2 is completely misplaced. }
4. c4
{ is White's only way of maintaining the balance @@StartBracket@@you read that right, White is the one that needs to be accurate here@@EndBracket@@. }
4... Nxd4 { No reason not to take a free pawn. } 5. Bc3 e5 6. Bxd4 exd4 7. Qxd4
Bb4+
{ This natural move is Black's strongest option, which was not considered by FM Marko Makaj in his Chessable course Calm and Collected 1. d4. White needs to indeed remain calm, as any further inaccuracy will result in a clear disadvantage for the first player. }
8. Nc3 Ne7 9. cxd5
{ 9.O-O-O?!  lands White in trouble after  9...c5!  10.Qd3  d4∓ } 9... Bxc3+
10. Qxc3 Nxd5
{ Ten moves in and the engine evaluation bar is already dipping below zero. Black is ahead in development, having already developed a minor piece and is one move away from castling. Conversely, White's kingside has yet to move.  In the theory section, we consider White's various retreating moves with his queen. You can check the detailshere. }
