1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. g3
{ The g3 system, which was amongst others recommended by IM Cristof Sielecki in the book and Chessable course Keep it Simple: 1.d4.  White delays  (and sometimes entirely foregoes)  c2-c4, preferring to first develop the kingside and keep options open. Several Catalan players have tried this approach, hoping to avoid certain variations and hoping to later transpose into more favorable versions of the Catalan.  However, we can immediately put an end to this possibility with }
3... c5
{ which is not only strong but also very practical. It is only Black's 5th most popular continuation at both the master and club level, but once more Black players catch on to it, I expect the g3 system to take a big dip in popularity.  The idea behind 3...c5 is to exchange White's d-pawn for our c-pawn, reducing his control over the center.   The main problem with White’s early g3 approach is that Black can quickly strike in the center when White will be hoping he had played c4 from the get-go.   3...b5  was recommended by Boris Avrukh in the book 'GM Repertoire: Beating 1. d4 sidelines'. This is another reliable option but 3... c5 is more incisive. }
4. Bg2 { is almost exclusively played. } 4... cxd4 5. O-O h6
{ I quite like this move, stopping Bg5. This ensures White will not be able to pressure our d5 pawn. }
6. b3
{ is interesting, as the dark-squared bishop is arguably better placed on b2 than on f4. The downside is that it wastes valuable time. }
6... e6 7. Bb2 Bc5 { The bishop is most active here. } 8. Nxd4 O-O
{ We're now threatening to expand with ...e5 so White does best to challenge our center right away with }
9. c4 dxc4 { Simple and strong. } 10. bxc4
{ In the Chessable course 'Keep it Simple: 1. d4', IM Sielecki stops here and says 'We have excellently placed bishops and open lines, giving plenty of compensation for the structural deficit'. I agree that White has sufficient compensation for the isolated pawn on c4, but that's about it. That is, White has no advantage as the following continuation illustrates }
10... Qb6 { Hits the bishop and clears the way for ...Rd8. } 11. Nb3 Be7 12.
Qc2 Bd7 13. e4 Bc6
{ followed by ...Nbd7-c5 is very comfortable. White is the one that needs to be accurate since the static factors, namely the better pawn structure, favor Black. }
