[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. e4 dxe4 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. f3
{ is the true Blackmar-Diemer gambit @@StartBracket@@BDG for short@@EndBracket@@, one of the few gambits at White's disposal after 1. d4.   In exchange for a pawn, White gains a tempo and a half-open f-file. Rapid development and active positioning of the minor pieces with Bc4 and Nf3-e5 is typically the name of the game in this gambit, hoping to start an attack against Black's king.  It might have enjoyed some success in the romantic era, but today's engines believe it is very suspect. I'll be recommending a fianchetto setup with ...g6, which completely neutralizes White's attacking chances and is the top choice of the neural network engines. }
4... exf3 5. Nxf3 g6
{ is both Leela and Stockfish 12's top choice. It also makes perfect sense. White is a pawn down and his only chance is to try and mount an attack against our king. By fianchettoing the dark-squared bishop, White's chances of mounting a successful attack are very slim. }
6. Bc4
{ The Studier attack, named after Georg Studier who played the BGD extensively. }
6... Bg7 7. O-O
{ 7.Ne5  O-O  8.Bg5  c5∓  gave Black a clear advantage in 0-1 @@StartBracket@@22@@EndBracket@@ Wilshusen,H @@StartBracket@@1505@@EndBracket@@ -Gierden,H @@StartBracket@@2132@@EndBracket@@ GER email 2017. }
7... O-O
{ Black has completed development and is essentially a clean pawn up. It'll be very hard for White to mount a successful attack on our king. Actually, let me rephrase that, it won't be possible at all. }
8. Qe1
{ intending to transfer the queen to h4. White wants to get Qh4, Bh6 and Ng5 in. This is however nothing but a pipe dream. }
8... Nc6
{ immediately exploiting the drawback of 8. Qe1, which left the d4 pawn vulnerable to attack. }
9. Qh4 Bg4
{ Not only attacks the main defender of the d4 pawn, but also blocks White's queen from covering this pawn. }
10. Ne2
{ covers the d4 pawn but going backwards is definitely not what White wanted. }
10... Bf5
{ Attacking the c2 pawn.   Also possible is  10...Bxf3!?  11.Rxf3  Na5  12.Bd3  c5  13.dxc5  Nc6∓  followed by ...Ne5. }
11. c3 { 11.Bb3  runs into  11...Na5⩱ } 11... Na5
{ chasing down White's bishop, which is short on squares. } 12. Bb5 c6 13. Ba4
Nd5
{ Next up is ...e6. White has no attack and his pieces are completely uncoordinated. }
