[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter (1...d5)"]
[Black "Blackmar-Diemer Gambit #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. e4 dxe4 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. f3
{ is the true Blackmar-Diemer gambit @@StartBracket@@BDG for short@@EndBracket@@, one of the few gambits at White's disposal after 1. d4.   In exchange for a pawn, White gains a tempo and a half-open f-file. Rapid development and active positioning of the minor pieces with Bc4 and Nf3-e5 is typically the name of the game in this gambit, hoping to start an attack against Black's king.  It might have enjoyed some success in the romantic era, but today's engines believe it is very suspect. I'll be recommending a fianchetto setup with ...g6, which completely neutralizes White's attacking chances and is the top choice of the neural network engines. }
4... exf3 5. Nxf3 g6
{ is both Leela and Stockfish 12's top choice. It also makes perfect sense. White is a pawn down and his only chance is to try and mount an attack against our king. By fianchettoing the dark-squared bishop, White's chances of mounting a successful attack are very slim. }
6. Bf4
{ The Bogoljubov variation, which Scheerer in his book on the BDG called the Longo Bogo. He believes it is a promising continuation for White. Today's neural network engines @@StartBracket@@which to be fair were not available when he wrote his book@@EndBracket@@ do not agree. }
6... Bg7 7. Qd2
{ 7.Bc4  can be met with  7...O-O  After  8.Qd2  Nc6  9.O-O-O   9.d5  runs into  9...Na5!  9...Bg4  10.Rhe1  Nb4  11.a3  Nbd5  heading to d5.  12.Nxd5  Nxd5  13.Bh6  Bxf3  14.gxf3  e6  Black is a clean pawn up. }
7... O-O
{ Our king is very safe on the kingside. The fianchetto setup is notoriously difficult to crack. }
8. O-O-O c6 9. Bh6 { is more to the point than 9. h4. } 9... Bg4
{ We bring out our light-squared bishop first before developing the knight. We can chop off White's knight at an opportune moment and reduce his attacking potential. }
10. Be2 Nbd7 11. h3 Bxf3 12. Bxf3 Nb6
{ Exclam! We're threatening ...Nc4, attacking White's queen which is the sole defender of the bishop on h6. This forces White to either retreat his dark-squared bishop or capture on g7. This powerful move was not considered in the 'The Blackmar-Diemer Gambit' book by Christoph Scheerer nor in IndrekR's Chessable course BDG for Blitz. }
13. Bxg7
{ Alternatives such as  13.Bf4  and  13.h4  are considered in the main theoretical section of the course. Clickhere andhere for the details on each one. }
13... Kxg7 14. g4 { What else? } 14... Nfd5
{ intending ...Nc4 with a clear advantage. None of White's pieces have crossed the 4th rank and half of them are on the queenside, meaning White has no attack. We've also already exchanged off two pairs of minor pieces, meaning he also won't be able to mount one in the future.   A sample continuation is  15.Qd3  Nf4  16.Qe3  Qd6  17.Ne4  Nfd5!  A strong in-between move!  18.Qd2  Qf4  forces the queens off the board when Black is still a pawn up. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter (1...d5)"]
[Black "Richter attack"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. f3
{ The so-called Richter Attack. White prepares to expand in the center with e2-e4. In doing so, he however deprives the knight on g1 of its best square.   While the engines rate this attack as dubious, White scores quite well in fast time controls. As such, good knowledge of the variations is required to punish White's dubious play. }
3... c5 { is a typical reaction when White is threatening e4. } 4. e4
{ The only logical follow up to White's previous move.   4.e3  is incongruent. The pawn on f3 now makes no sense.  4...Nc6  5.Bb5  e6  6.Nge2  Bd6  7.O-O  O-O  followed by ...Bd7 and ...a6 gave Black a clear advantage, which he easily converted in 0-1 @@StartBracket@@15@@EndBracket@@ Bucher,R @@StartBracket@@2055@@EndBracket@@ -Klovans,J @@StartBracket@@2394@@EndBracket@@ Triesen 2002. White's knight on e2 is completely misplaced and the bishop on c1 is restricted. }
4... cxd4 5. Qxd4 Nc6 { Developing with tempo. } 6. Bb5
{ is almost invariably played. White wants to keep the queen on d4, where it pressures the d5 pawn and supports e4-e5 in some variations. }
6... Bd7 { Breaks the pin, practically forcing } 7. Bxc6 bxc6
{ is the strongest recapture. It is Stockfish's top choice and much rarer than 7...Bxc6, thus packing good surprise value. The idea behind ...bxc6 is to play ...e6 and then kick back White's queen with ... c5, taking over the center.   7...Bxc6  was recommended by GM Boris Avrukh in 'GM Repertoire: Beating 1.d4 Sidelines'. The text is however stronger. }
8. e5 { Pushing ahead is White's most popular continuation. } 8... Ng8
{ Yes, we have to undevelop the knight but White cannot exploit this. We're ready for ...e6 and potentially ...c5, taking over the center. }
9. f4
{ Reinforces the e5 pawn and vacates the f3 square for the knight.   White can also develop the knight with  9.Nge2  e6  threatens ...c5. If White tries to stop it with  10.Na4  then   10.Be3??  loses on the spot to  10...c5  11.Qd3  d4−+  10...Ne7  11.Bd2  Qc7∓  followed by ...Nf5, when Black will get ...c5 in with a clear advantage. }
9... e6 10. Nf3 Qb6
{ is simple and effective, aiming for a clearly better endgame for Black. } 11.
Qxb6 axb6
{ Next up are ...c5, ...Bc6 and even ...d4 later on. Also on the agenda are ...Be7 and ...Nh6-f5 with a clear advantage. }
*

