[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter (1...d5)"]
[Black "London 5. Bg3 mainline - Our setup explained"]
[Result "*"]

{ In this info line, I'd like to discuss the setup we're aiming for in the mainline of the London system with 5. Bg3. Here's the formula you should remember:  1. Develop the kingside with ...Nf6, ...e6, ...Bd6 and ...O-O  2. Break with ...c5  3. Place the queen on c7  4. Develop the b8 knight to d7  Our main goal is to break in the center with ...e5. }
1. d4 d5 2. Bf4
{ 1. Develop the kingside with ...Nf6, ...e6, ...Bd6 and ...O-O } 2... Nf6 3.
e3 e6 4. Nf3 Bd6
{ immediately fighting for the e5 square and clearing the way for ...O-O. } 5.
Bg3 { is White's mainline. } 5... O-O
{ Notice how we first develop the kingside before touching anything on the queenside. }
6. Nbd2 { 2. Break with ...c5 } 6... c5
{ putting pressure on White's center and vacating the c7 square for our queen. }
7. c3 { 3. Place the queen on c7 } 7... Qc7
{ The queen is better placed on c7 than on e7. This is because in the former it fights for the e5 square.  Notice that we also develop the queen first and only then b8 knight. This is so we can meet dxc5 with ...Qxc5. }
8. Bd3 { 4. Develop the b8 knight to d7 } 8... Nbd7
{ The knight should be placed on d7 rather than on c6.   The reason is that  8...Nc6  runs into  9.dxc5  taking advantage of the pin and the fact that the knight on c6 is blocking our queen from covering the c5 pawn.  From d7, the knight takes control over the e5 square without blocking our queen from protecting the c5 pawn.   This piece arrangement - bishop on d6, queen on c7, and knight on d7  a@@EndBracket@@ takes firm control over the e5 square, meaning White can't install a knight here  b@@EndBracket@@ prepares the e6-e5 break. Once we achieve this break, we have comfortably equalized. }
9. Qc2 { 5. Break with e6-e5 } 9... e5
{ The final step in our plan, which gives us an excellent game. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter (1...d5)"]
[Black "London 5. Bg3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4
{ The London system, which I believe is White's strongest d4 system. In the main theoretical section of the course, I expand on the merits of this move and my approach against it. Check it outhere. }
2... Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Nf3 Bd6
{ immediately fighting for the e5 square and clearing the way for ...O-O. } 5.
Bg3
{ is at least 3x as popular as the alternatives. White invites Black to capture on g3, which would open the h-file for the rook on h1.  A rule of thumb  (although there are some exceptions)  is that we should only capture the bishop on g3 when White has castled short  (as the rook is no longer on h1)  . }
5... O-O
{ finishing kingside development. It's important to note that we develop the kingside first with ...Nf6, ...e6, ...Bd6, and ...O-O before touching anything else on the queenside.   The immediate pawn break  5...c5  gives White the extra option of playing  6.Bb5+ }
6. c4
{ White can once again try this approach. We're perfectly positioned to fight for the center with }
6... c5 7. cxd5
{ Alternatives such as  7.dxc5  and  7.Nc3  are examined in detail in the theory section of the course. You can check out the detailshere andhere respectively. }
7... exd5 8. Nc3 { 8.Bd3  can be met with  8...c4  9.Bc2  b5↑ } 8... c4
{ is rare but very interesting. It deprives White's bishop of the d3 square. The plan is to complete development with ... Be6 and ...Nbd7 and then expand on the queenside with ...a6 + ...b5. }
9. Bh4
{ White is threatening to win the d5 pawn @@StartBracket@@or spoil our pawn structure@@EndBracket@@ with Bxf6 followed by Nxd5. }
9... Be6 10. Be2 Nbd7 11. O-O a6
{ Black is doing very well and can continue with ...Qc7 and ...b5. } *

