1. d4 d5 2. Bf4
{ The London system, which I believe is White's strongest d4 system. In the main theoretical section of the course, I expand on the merits of this move and my approach against it. Check it outhere. }
2... Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Nf3 Bd6
{ immediately fighting for the e5 square and clearing the way for ...O-O. } 5.
Bg3 { is at least 3x as popular as the alternatives. } 5... O-O 6. Nbd2
{ White can also start with   6.Bd3  which will transpose to the mainline after  6...c5 }
6... c5
{ It's now time to discuss the setup we're aiming for. We're going to place our queen on c7 and b8 knight on d7, taking complete control over the e5 square. This will completely neutralize White's typical plan of entrenching a knight on e5 and starting a kingside attack. }
7. c3 Qc7 { Next up is ...Nbd7, taking full control over e5. } 8. Bd3 Nbd7
{ We've achieved our objective, that is White is unable to anchor a knight on e5. Not only that, we're ready to break with ...e5 next. }
9. Bxd6 Qxd6 10. O-O e5
{ equalizes on the spot. If White isn't careful, Black can even start to take over due to his space advantage. We could already stop here but as this position has been seen in 800+ games at the club level, I think it's worthwhile continuing for a couple of more moves. }
11. dxe5
{ The alternative capture  11.dxc5?!  is dubious as it hands Black the center.  11...Nxc5  12.Nc4  is creative but nothing to worry about. After  12...Qc7  13.Ncxe5  Re8  White's knight is trapped. The only way to continue is  14.b4  Nce4  15.c4  Rxe5  16.Nxe5  Qxe5  wins an exchange. Black has a decisive advantage, a sample continuation being  17.cxd5  Bf5  18.Bxe4  Ng4!  A nice intermezzo, threatening mate!  19.g3  Qxe4−+  Black has two pieces for the rook and is thus winning. }
11... Nxe5 12. Nxe5 Qxe5 13. Nf3 Qe7
{ drops the queen back to safety. Next up are ...Rd8 and ...b6 + ...Bb7 with an excellent position. White has less space and thus needs to be accurate to maintain the balance. }
