1. d4 d5 2. Bf4
{ The London system, which I believe is White's strongest d4 system. In the main theoretical section of the course, I expand on the merits of this move and my approach against it. Check it outhere. }
2... Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Nf3 { Another 5th move option is } 4... Bd6
{ immediately fighting for the e5 square and clearing the way for ...O-O. } 5.
Bxd6
{ This looks very unambitious but has been played several times by GM Tamir Nabaty with reasonable success. }
5... Qxd6 6. c4
{ This is White's only chance to fight for an advantage.   Alternatives like  6.Nbd2  give Black very easy play. For example  6...O-O  7.Bd3  Nbd7  8.O-O  e5=  is very pleasant.   Similarly  6.c3  O-O  7.Bd3  Nbd7  8.Nbd2  c5  9.O-O  e5=  is great. }
6... O-O 7. Nc3 { 7.c5  is discussed in themain section of the course. } 7...
dxc4
{ The simplest and most direct route towards equality. We're ready to break in the center next with ...c7-c5.   Note that the immediate break  7...c5  leaves us with an isolated pawn after  8.cxd5  exd5  9.dxc5  which I'd rather avoid. This is the reason we first take on c4. }
8. Bxc4 c5 { Immediately challenging White's center. } 9. O-O cxd4 10. Qxd4
Qxd4 11. Nxd4 Bd7 { followed by ...Nc6 with an equal position. } *

