[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter (1...Nf6 2...e6)"]
[Black "Jobava Attack #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3
{ Threatens to expand in the center with e2-e4, which we immediately stop with }
2... d5 3. Bf4
{ The Jobava Attack, named after the strong Georgian GM Baadur Jobava. This variation has also been called the Jobava-Prie Attack in honor of GM Éric Prié, who used to annotate the d4 systems column for Chesspublishing. Lichess calls it the Rapport-Jobava Attack since super-GM Richard Rapport has also played it extensively. Chess. com and 365chess.com refer to it as the Chigorin Variation. Finally, GM Simon Williams in his Chessable course called it the Jobava London System. Jobava racked up quite a score a few years ago but has largely given it up. The reason for this is there are multiple systems where Black is very comfortable, such as 3...c5, 3...g6, and 3...a6. }
3... e6 { I was surprised to see } 4. e3
{ recommended by GM Simon Williams in his Chessable course as after } 4... Bb4
{ the neural network engines are already giving Black the advantage. This is on a high speed cloud server so it might take a while for your local engine to come to the same conclusion.  The point is ...c5 followed by ...Qa5 and ...Ne4 are coming next, exploiting White's pinned piece. }
5. Bd3 c5
{ places White in an awkward predicament as he has no good way of completing development. }
6. dxc5
{ is basically forced.   6.Nge2  blunders the bishop.  6...c4   6.Nf3  also lands White in trouble after  6...c4  7.Be2  Ne4  followed by ...Nxc3 nets Black a pawn.   6.a3?  is a mistake and allows Black to execute his idea, namely  6...Bxc3+  7.bxc3  Qa5  when White cannot cover the c3 pawn as  8.Qd2  runs into  8...c4  9.Be2  Ne4−+ }
6... Nbd7 7. Ne2 { covering the knight on c3. } 7... a6
{ is very precise. We want to capture the c5 pawn with the bishop and so it makes sense to prevent White from ever playing Nb5. Now you might be wondering, why aren't we going for ...Nxc5? After all, it hits the d3 bishop. The point is that our knight is much better placed on d7, enabling us to push ahead with ... e6-e5 completely taking over the center.   The immediate  7...Bxc5  also gives Black an advantage. }
8. O-O Bxc5
{ Simple and effective.   8...e5  wins a piece after  9.Bg5  e4  10.Nxd5  but White has good compensation. It is analyzed as analternative recommendation. }
9. e4 { However, Black has the following strong reply } 9... d4
{ first kicking White's knight back... } 10. Nb1
{ ...and now it's time to hit the bishop with } 10... e5 11. Bg3
{ Going back with   11.Bc1  is obviously bad. After  11...O-O  Black is in excellent shape. }
11... Nh5
{ followed by ...O-O with a dominant position.   A sample continuation is  12.Nd2  Nxg3  13.Nxg3  O-O  14.Rc1  preparing to break with c4  14...b5  15.Nb3  Bb6  16.c4  dxc3  17.Rxc3  Nf6∓  Next up are ...Be6 and ...Rc8. Black's two bishops are very strong in this position. }
