[White "Quickstarter (1...Nf6 2...e6)"]
[Black "Jobava Attack #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3
{ Threatens to expand in the center with e2-e4, which we immediately stop with }
2... d5 3. Bf4
{ The Jobava Attack, named after the strong Georgian GM Baadur Jobava. This variation has also been called the Jobava-Prie Attack in honor of GM Éric Prié, who used to annotate the d4 systems column for Chesspublishing. Lichess calls it the Rapport-Jobava Attack since super-GM Richard Rapport has also played it extensively. Chess. com and 365chess.com refer to it as the Chigorin Variation. Finally, GM Simon Williams in his Chessable course called it the Jobava London System. Jobava racked up quite a score a few years ago but has largely given it up. The reason for this is there are multiple systems where Black is very comfortable, such as 3...c5, 3...g6, and 3...a6. }
3... e6
{ is my recommendation and one of the most challenging responses. The idea is to quickly play ...Bb4  (or ...Bd6)  , pinning White’s knight on c3 and thereby increasing control over the e4 square. White’s knight can often be further undermined with …Ne4, which White must be constantly on the lookout for. }
4. Nb5 { The only serious move in my opinion. } 4... Na6
{ may look awkward but is perfectly fine. We parry White's threat of Nxc7 and are ready to kick back his knight with ... c6 after we develop our kingside. }
5. e3 Be7 6. Nf3 O-O 7. Ne5
{ is a popular move at the club level. The knight looks pretty on e5 but it's actually not doing much. In fact, it is blocking the bishop on f4, meaning the knight on b5 is no longer doing anything @@StartBracket@@i.e. White is no longer threatening Nc7@@EndBracket@@ . }
7... c5
{ Now that the bishop on f4 is blocked, White's knight on b5 is not doing anything. In fact, it can even become a target. As such, there's no reason to first kick it back with 8...c6. }
8. Bd3 { This move is a mistake as it runs into the immediate } 8... c4 9. Be2
Qa5+ { forcing White's knight back. } 10. Nc3
{ And now Black has the fantastic shot } 10... Ba3
{ undermining the b2 pawn, which is the sole defender of the knight on c3. This thematic tactical shot occurs in multiple openings. For example, it is very prevalent in the Von Hennig-Schara Gambit. }
11. Qc1 Ne4
{ White has no way of preventing material losses as the knight on c3 is about to drop.   A sample continuation is  11...Ne4  12.bxa3  Qxc3+  13.Kf1  f6  14.Nf3  Bd7−+  with a decisive advantage. }
