[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter (1...Nf6 2...e6)"]
[Black "Colle #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. e3
{ The Colle system, also known as the Colle-Koltanowski system, is named after the Belgian masters Edgard Colle and George Koltanowski.    Characterized by the moves 2. Nf3 and 3. e3, White usually develops his light-squared bishop to d3, the queenside knight to d2, and tries to engineer the pawn break e3-e4. White typically reinforces the d4 pawn with c2-c3 in response to …c5, setting up a triangle or pyramidal pawn structure with pawns on f2, e3, d4, c3, and b2.    Another possible setup is to fianchetto the dark-squared bishop with b3 and Bb2. This is known as the Colle–Zukertort system, named after the Polish-German-British master Johannes Hermann Zukertort. World-renowned German GM and trainer Artur Yusupov played it extensively at the grandmaster level in the 90s. The idea behind White’s construction is to take control firm control over e5 and anchor a knight on this square with Nf3-e5, which can be further reinforced by f2-f4. Yusupov won countless games by then starting a kingside attack with Qe1-h4 and lifting a rook along the third rank with Rf1-f3.   Ever since Black has found several effective ways of countering these plans and the Colle system is nowadays considered innocuous. }
3... b6
{ Having played the Nimzo and QID extensively myself, I always liked meeting the Colle system with the fianchetto. From b7, the light-squared bishop takes control over the key e4 square. }
4. Bd3
{ 4.c3  ,  4.b3  , and  4.Nbd2  have little independent value and will transpose to lines covered throughout the chapter.   4.c4  transposes into a pretty harmless variation of the QID. While it falls outside the scope of this course, Black can develop in the same way and easily equalize. }
4... Bb7 5. O-O d5
{ Taking a stake in the center. It's time to discuss the setup we're aiming for. We'll place our bishop on d6, b8 knight on d7, and castle kingside.  If allowed, we'll play ...Ne4, then entrench our knight with ...f7-f5 and can even start a kingside attack with ...Rf6-h6 and/or ...Qe8-h5. }
6. c3
{ The Triangle setup is completely harmless.   Moving the pawn one square forward with  6.c4  can be met with  6...dxc4  7.Bxc4  c5=  followed by ...Nbd7 and ...Be7 with a good game. }
6... Bd6 7. Nbd2 Nbd7 { Takes firm control over the e5 square. } 8. Re1 Ne4
{ stopping White from playing e4. Black can follow up with ...O-O and ...f5 and is already slightly better. White's bishop on c1 is terrible.   A sample continuation is  9.c4  f5  10.b3  O-O  11.Bb2  Rf6  starting active play on the kingside with  ...Rh6  up next. }
*

