1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. e3
{ The Colle system, also known as the Colle-Koltanowski system, is named after the Belgian masters Edgard Colle and George Koltanowski.    Characterized by the moves 2. Nf3 and 3. e3, White usually develops his light-squared bishop to d3, the queenside knight to d2, and tries to engineer the pawn break e3-e4. White typically reinforces the d4 pawn with c2-c3 in response to …c5, setting up a triangle or pyramidal pawn structure with pawns on f2, e3, d4, c3, and b2.    Another possible setup is to fianchetto the dark-squared bishop with b3 and Bb2. This is known as the Colle–Zukertort system, named after the Polish-German-British master Johannes Hermann Zukertort. World-renowned German GM and trainer Artur Yusupov played it extensively at the grandmaster level in the 90s. The idea behind White’s construction is to take control firm control over e5 and anchor a knight on this square with Nf3-e5, which can be further reinforced by f2-f4. Yusupov won countless games by then starting a kingside attack with Qe1-h4 and lifting a rook along the third rank with Rf1-f3.   Ever since Black has found several effective ways of countering these plans and the Colle system is nowadays considered innocuous. }
3... b6
{ Having played the Nimzo and QID extensively myself, I always liked meeting the Colle system with the fianchetto. }
4. Bd3 Bb7 5. O-O d5
{ taking a stake in the center. It's time to discuss the setup we're aiming for. We'll place our bishop on d6, b8 knight on d7 and castle kingside. If allowed, we'll then entrench our knight on e4 with ...f7-f5 and can even start a kingside attack with ... Rf6-h6 and/or ...Qe8-h5. }
6. b3
{ aiming for a Zukertort-style setup.   6.c4  Bd6  7.Nc3  O-O  transposes to the mainline. }
6... Bd6 7. Bb2 O-O 8. Ne5
{ White is once again aiming for a Stonewall setup with f4, and so we should immediately challenge the d4 pawn with }
8... c5 9. Nd2 Nc6 10. a3 Rc8
{ A useful move, improving the position of the rook and waiting for White to commit to f2-f4. }
11. f4 { White goes for his typical attacking plan. } 11... Ne7
{ uncovers the light-squared bishop, enabling ...Ne4 next. } 12. Qf3
{ White wants to get the queen over to the kingside and also stops the immediate ...Ne4.   Worse is  12.Qe2  as it does nothing to prevent  12...Ne4⩱  Black is better as he can purge White's knight from e5 with ...f6, while White has no way of getting rid of Black's knight on e4. }
12... b5
{ is once again very strong, threatening to push ahead with ...c5-c4. Black is in great shape.   A sample continuation is  12...b5  13.dxc5   13.Bxb5  cxd4  14.Bxd4  Rxc2  is the point behind 12...b5.  Bxc5  14.b4  Bb6  15.Nb3  Ne4  when Black was was already better in 0-1 @@StartBracket@@32@@EndBracket@@ Halkias,A @@StartBracket@@2094@@EndBracket@@-Balogh,C @@StartBracket@@2638@@EndBracket@@ Achaia 2017. }
