[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter (1...Nf6 2...e6)"]
[Black "Torre #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bg5
{ The Torre attack is White's third most popular option on move 3 with 25000+ games. White typically places his light-squared bishop on d3, the queenside knight on d2, and reinforces the d4 pawn with c2-c3. The first player then hopes to push forward with e2-e4 and start a kingside attack, taking advantage of the fact that the bishop on g5 can chop off knight on f6 – the main defender of Black’s king – at an opportune moment.   We’re not going to give White such easy play and will be challenging White’s bishop with ...h6 early on. Another recurring theme is to play ...Qb6, targeting the b2 pawn which White has left undefended. }
3... c5
{ My preferred system vs the Torre, immediately fighting for the center. } 4.
e3 { is White's most popular move. } 4... h6
{ Simple and effective. This move was not considered in the Chessable course Calm & Collected: 1.d4 by FM Marko Makaj. }
5. Bxf6
{ 5.Bh4  d5  6.c3  Nbd7  is covered via the 3. c3 move order in themain theoretical section of the course.   5.Bf4  d5  is a completely harmless London where Black got in ...h6 move for free. If White wanted to play like this, he should have gone Bf4 on move 3. }
5... Qxf6 { Thanks for the bishop pair! } 6. Nbd2
{ The alternative knight development  6.Nc3  makes little sense. It can only be connected with the idea of playing e4, an option Black can immediately eliminate with  6...cxd4  7.exd4  d5  when the knight is simply misplaced on c3. }
6... cxd4
{ is simple and effective. Black clarifies the tension, entering a Carlsbad structure where only he can even be better. This is because White will find it very hard to take control of the e5 square and has no chance of mounting an attack on Black's king. }
7. exd4 Nc6 { Developing with a tempo on the d4 pawn. } 8. c3
{ 8.Nc4?!  makes little sense as  8...d5  kicks it back with tempo. After  9.Ne3  Bd6  12.Be2  Black can play it safe with  12...O-O=  or try to seize the initiative with  12...g5⭡ }
8... d5 { Next up is ...Bd6 and ...O-O with a very comfortable position. } 9.
Bb5
{ has been played a handful of times but the bishop isn't doing much here. }
9... Bd6 10. O-O O-O 11. Re1 Bd7
{ We're ready to kick White's bishop back with ...a6 and then follow up with ...b5-b4 - the typical minority attack in the Carlsbad structure. Black is very comfortable. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter (1...Nf6 2...e6)"]
[Black "Torre #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c3
{ is more flexible, giving White the possibility of heading for the Colle or Torre systems. }
3... c5 { Staying consistent with our approach vs 3. Bg5. } 4. Bg5 d5
{ White isn't fighting for the center but that doesn't mean we should follow suit. }
5. Nbd2 h6 { Putting the question to the bishop. } 6. Bxf6
{ White gives up the bishop, intending to break with e4. } 6... Qxf6 7. e4 cxd4
8. cxd4 { Natural but inaccurate. } 8... dxe4 9. Ne5
{ White wants to play Bb5+ next, but this idea is flawed. } 9... Bb4
{ Black pins the knight, and therefore hangs onto his pawn on e4. } 10. Qa4+
{ doesn't work on account of } 10... Nc6 11. Nxc6 Bxd2+
{ Intermezzo, forcing White's king out into the open. } 12. Kxd2 Bd7
{ The c6 knight is about to drop and White's king is completely exposed on d2. }
