1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c3
{ is more flexible, giving White the possibility of heading for the Colle or Torre systems. }
3... c5 { Staying consistent with our approach vs 3. Bg5. } 4. Bg5 d5
{ White isn't fighting for the center but that doesn't mean we should follow suit. White has two main approaches at this point: 5. Nbd2 or 5. e3. }
5. e3 h6 { Asking the bishop to define its position. } 6. Bxf6
{ 6.Bf4  is harmless. After  6...Bd6  7.Bxd6  Qxd6  White is unable to establish his knight on e5  8.Ne5  O-O  9.Nd2  Nfd7= }
6... Qxf6
{ Thanks once again for the bishop pair. The only justification behind White's last move is to play }
7. Ne5
{ establishing the knight on e5 and intending to disrupt our development with Bb5+. }
7... a6 { Simply stopping Bb5+. } 8. Nd2
{ White intends to transfer this knight to f3, reinforcing the knight on e5. }
8... Nd7 { Challenging White's knight. } 9. f4
{ Setting up a Stonewall structure without the bad bishop on c1. However, White's knight on e5 is short-lived.   Worse is  9.Ndf3?!  as  10...Bd6  expels the knight from e5. Following  10.Nxd7  Bxd7  11.Bd3  g5∓  Black is clearly for choice with the two bishops and extra space. }
9... Nxe5 10. fxe5
{ Worse is  10.dxe5  Qd8⩱  followed by ...Be7, ...O-O and ...b5 gives Black an advantage. }
10... Qg6
{ with a very pleasant position. We can complete development with ...Be7, ...O-O and ...Bd7 and then expand on the queenside with ...b5. }
