{ The g3 system, which was amongst others recommended by IM Cristof Sielecki in the book and Chessable course Keep it Simple: 1.d4.  White delays  (and sometimes entirely foregoes)  c2-c4, preferring to first develop the kingside and keep options open. Several Catalan players have tried this approach, hoping to avoid certain variations and hoping to later transpose into more favorable versions of the Catalan.  However, we can immediately put an end to this possibility with }
3... b5
{ which is a very interesting response, taking advantage of the fact that White did not play c4. We completely rule out c4 for the time being and prepare to quickly fianchetto our light-squared bishop, fully neutralizing White's Catalan bishop. }
4. Bg2
{ is almost invariably played. I'd also like to say a few words about some rare alternatives.   4.e4?!  is dubious as after  4...Nxe4  5.Bxb5  White exchanged a central pawn for a flank pawn, which is clearly in Black's favor.  5...Be7⩱  is already slightly better for Black.   4.Nc3  walks straight into  4...b4=   4.c3  is completely harmless. After  4...Bb7  5.Bg2  Be7  6.O-O  c5=  Black has comfortably equalized.   4.e3  also makes little sense. White voluntarily blocks his dark-squared bishop and makes his structure rigid. After  4...a6  5.Bg2  Bb7  6.O-O  Be7  7.b3  O-O  8.Bb2  d5=  Black has a great game with ...Nbd7 and ...c5 coming next. }
4... Bb7 5. O-O { 5.Bg5  Be7  6.O-O=  transposes to 5. O-O Be7 6. Bg5. } 5...
c5
{ White has tried a bunch of moves in this position: 6. c3, 6. a4, 6. Na3 and 6. Bg5 in order of decreasing popularity, none of which pose Black any real problems. }
6. c3 { Reinforcing the d4 pawn is White's most popular continuation. } 6...
Be7 7. Bg5
{ Alternatives are given as clickables since they lead to similar play as the previous variations.   7.a4  can once again be bypassed with  7...b4  8.dxc5  Bxc5  9.cxb4  Bxb4  10.Qb3  Na6=  Black had no issues in ½-½ @@StartBracket@@41@@EndBracket@@ Hacche,D @@StartBracket@@2131@@EndBracket@@ -Smerdon,D @@StartBracket@@2502@@EndBracket@@ Canberra 2010. He can comfortably complete development with ...O-O and ...Qe7.   If  7.Qd3  Black can simply defend the pawn with  7...a6  8.Nbd2  cxd4  9.cxd4  Nc6  10.a3  O-O  11.Nb3  Na5=  Black was in great shape in the blitz game ½-½ @@StartBracket@@91@@EndBracket@@ Jakovenko,D @@StartBracket@@2713@@EndBracket@@-Pridorozhni,A  @@StartBracket@@2512@@EndBracket@@ Khanty-Mansiysk 2013. Next on the agenda are ...Qb6 and ...Rac8. }
7... cxd4 8. Nxd4
{ Centralizes the knight at the expense of exchanging the light-squared bishops. }
8... Bxg2 9. Kxg2 Qb6
{ Covers the b5 pawn, intending to follow up with ...O-O. The queen can always drop back to b7 in the future and take up the mantle of the light-squared bishop.   A sample continuation is  9...Qb6  10.Qd3  Qb7+  11.f3  a6  12.e4  h6  13.Be3  d6  14.Nd2  Nbd7  15.Bf2  O-O=  followed by ...Nb6 and ...Rfc8 gives Black an excellent game. }
