1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Nbd2 { prepares the e4 break. } 3... d5
{ puts an end to any ideas of e2-e4. } 4. c4 { is strongly met by } 4... c5
{ with an excellent version of the Tarrasch. White's knight would much rather be on c3. }
5. e3
{ Alternatively  5.cxd5  can be met with  5...cxd4!?  6.Nxd4  Qxd5  7.e3  Be7=  followed by ...O-O was completely fine in ½-½ @@StartBracket@@30@@EndBracket@@ Madebrink, L @@StartBracket@@2192@@EndBracket@@-Jepson,C @@StartBracket@@2415@@EndBracket@@ Tylosand 2018. }
5... cxd4 6. exd4
{ is the more popular recapture with 20+ OTB games  (and well over 1000 online games!)  . }
6... dxc4
{ is the most challenging move, leaving White with an isolated pawn on d4 where his knight on d2 is completely misplaced. It would much rather be on c3. }
7. Bxc4
{ is the most natural recapture.   Alternatively  7.Nxc4  runs into the check  Bb4+  After  8.Bd2  Bxd2+  9.Qxd2  O-O⩱  Black can complete development with ...b6, ...Bb7, ...Nc6 and ...Qd6 with a slight advantage. White has little to show for the IQP.   Recapturing the pawn with the queen after  7.Qa4+  Bd7  8.Qxc4  is dubious as after  8...Bc6∓  Black will play ...Bd5, vacating the c6 square for the knight. The bishop on d5 is a monster. }
7... Nc6 8. Bb5
{ is the only good way to keep the d4 pawn alive.   8.O-O  drops a pawn after  Nxd4  9.Nxd4  Qxd4⩱   8.Nb3  Bb4+  9.Bd2  Bxd2+  10.Qxd2  O-O∓  followed by ...b6 and ...Bb7 is clearly better for Black. The d4 pawn is weak and White's pieces are misplaced. }
8... Be7 9. Bxc6+ bxc6
{ White has surrendered the bishop pair. Any hopes of targeting the c6 pawn are an illusion as Black is ready to play ...c5 next. }
10. O-O c5 11. dxc5 Bxc5
{ followed by ...O-O and ...Bb7 gives Black the upper hand. The two bishops are a force to be reckoned with in such an open position. }
