1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ The London system, which I believe is White's strongest d4 system. In the main theoretical section of the course, I expand on the merits of this move and my approach against it. Check it outhere. }
2... e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. e3 Bd6
{ immediately fighting for the e5 square and clearing the way for ...O-O. } 5.
Bg3
{ is at least 3x as popular as the alternatives. White invites Black to capture on g3, which would open the h-file for the rook on h1. A rule of thumb @@StartBracket@@although there are some exceptions@@EndBracket@@ is that we should only capture the bishop on g3 when White has castled short  @@StartBracket@@as the rook is no longer on h1@@EndBracket@@ . }
5... O-O
{ finishing kingside development. It's important to note that we develop the kingside first with ...Nf6, ...e6, ... Bd6, and ...O-O before touching anything else on the queenside.  The immediate pawn break   5...c5  gives White the extra option of playing Bb5+ }
6. c4
{ is an interesting approach. We're perfectly positioned to fight for the center with }
6... c5 7. cxd5
{ Alternatives such as  7.dxc5  and  7.Nc3  are examined in detail in the theory section of the course. You can check out the detailshere andhere respectively. }
7... exd5 8. Nc3 { 8.Bd3  can be met with  8...c4  9.Bc2  b5↑ } 8... c4
{ is rare but very interesting. It deprives White's bishop of the d3 square. The plan is to complete development with ... Be6 and ...Nbd7 and then expand on the queenside with ...a6 + ...b5. }
9. Bh4 Be6 10. Be2 Nbd7 11. O-O a6
{ Black is doing very well and can continue with ...Qc7 and ...b5. } *

