1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ The London system, which I believe is White's strongest d4 system. In the main theoretical section of the course, I expand on the merits of this move and my approach against it. Check it outhere. }
2... e6 3. e3 d5 4. Nf3 Bd6
{ immediately fighting for the e5 square and clearing the way for ...O-O. } 5.
Bd3
{ is not very popular. I see no reason not to exchange the dark-squared bishops with }
5... Bxf4 6. exf4 Qd6 { is very timely as } 7. Qd2
{ is the only way of holding onto the pawn, but a move White didn't want to make since it deprives the b1 knight of the d2 square.   The more desirable  7.g3?  loses material to  7...Qb4  8.Nc3  Qxb2∓  which nets Black a pawn. }
7... b6
{ prepares to undermine White's center with ...c5 and exchange the light-squared bishops with ...Ba6. }
8. O-O c5
{ The immediate  8...Ba6?!  is a mistake on account of  9.Bxa6  Nxa6  10.f5!  is very strong.   Black cannot afford to capture the pawn with  10...exf5??  as  11.Qe2+−  wins the knight.  10...O-O  is a better move but White has a big advantage after  11.Qe2± }
9. c3
{ is most natural but the knight on b1 is now fully restricted.   9.Nc3  and  9.Re1  are discussedhere. }
9... Ba6
{ forces the bishops off the board, an exchange that favors Black and leaves White will several light-square weaknesses. Black is now threatening to win a pawn with ...Bxd3 followed by ...Qxf4. }
10. Bxa6
{ Alternatives such as  10.g3  ,  10.Ne5  and  10.Re1  are discussed in themain section of the course. }
10... Nxa6 11. Re1
{ 11.f5  is not dangerous.  11...Nc7  12.fxe6  Nxe6  is perfectly satisfactory. }
11... O-O
{ Black can reroute the knight to c6 next with an excellent game. Without the light-squared bishops, White has no chances of mounting an effective kingside attack while Black can expand on the queenside with ...c4 and ...b5-b4. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter (1...Nf6 2...e6)"]
[Black "London 5. Nbd2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ The London system, which I believe is White's strongest d4 system. In the main theoretical section of the course, I expand on the merits of this move and my approach against it. Check it outhere. }
2... e6 3. e3 d5 4. Nf3 Bd6
{ immediately fighting for the e5 squared and clearing the way for ...O-O. The last 5th move option we'll examine in this Quickstarter is }
5. Nbd2
{ continuing development without worrying about the bishop on f4. White doesn't mind ...Bxf4 as this will increase his control over the e5 square. }
5... O-O 6. c3
{ White cleverly postpones the development of his light-squared bishop. He is anticipating our plan of ... b6 followed by ...Ba6 and wants to capture on a6 without having spent a tempo on Bd3. This gained some attention in 2020 when Anish Giri and Magnus Carlsen used this tricky move order to take down super-GM opposition. However, there is nothing to fear and he can only hold back the bishop for so long. }
6... c5 7. Ne5 Qc7
{ We've seen this before. The queen is very well placed on c7 and puts pressure on the e5 knight, which we have the option of challenging with ...Nbd7 next.   7...b6?!  is too slow. After  8.h4  Qc7  9.h5⩲  White's pawn is about to land on h6, a position we certainly shouldn't allow. }
8. Bd3 { White can't hold back this move any longer. } 8... a5
{ is a key novelty that solves all of Black's problems.   It starts play on the queenside, so if we choose to close down the center with ...c4, then we are already ready for a quick ...b5-b4.   Secondly, it makes it impossible for White to prevent us from exchanging the light-squared bishops with ...b6 followed by ...Ba6 should we choose to do so @@StartBracket@@note that the immediate ...b6 would be met with Qe2@@EndBracket@@. }
9. O-O Nbd7 { Our standard way of challenging the knight on e5. } 10. Ndf3
{ maintains White's knight on e5, but ties up all of White's pieces on this task. In particular, the e4 break is no longer available. That's green light for Black to start active operations on the queenside with }
10... c4 11. Bc2
{ 11.Bb1  is a worse square for the bishop, and doesn't change our plan  11...b5  12.Qc2  b4=  followed by ...Ne4 is very pleasant. }
11... b5 12. Re1 b4
{ Next up is ...Bb7. Black is in great shape and can easily take over if White isn't careful. }
*

[Event "?"]
