1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3
{ Threatens to expand in the center with e2-e4, which we immediately stop with }
2... d5
{ when White's knight on c3 is misplaced, stopping White from breaking in the center with c2-c4. }
3. e4 { is the so-called Hübsch Gambit. } 3... Nxe4
{ is the easiest way to punish White's dubious Gambit. After this move, White will not even be able to open the f-file. As such, the first player has even less compensation  (actually no compensation!)  for the pawn than in the Blackmar-Diemer Gambit.   3...dxe4  4.f3  transposes to the Blackmar-Diemer Gambit, which is covered via the 1. d4 d5 2. e4 move order. Refer to chapter9 for the details. }
4. Nxe4 dxe4 5. Bc4
{ This is White's most popular continuation.   The less common  5.Bf4  is also tackled in themain part of the course. }
5... Nc6 6. c3 e5 { is very strong, undermining White's center. } 7. d5
{ White doesn't really have an alternative.   7.Ne2  Bd6  8.O-O  O-O∓  White has zero compensation for the missing pawn. }
7... Ne7
{ We're now threatening to play ...c6. The knight can later be placed on f5. }
8. f3
{ Worse is  8.Qa4+  Bd7  9.Qb3  Nf5  when the pawn grab  10.Qxb7?  is a blunder. After  10...Rb8  11.Qa6  e3−+  White is in big trouble. }
8... Ng6 { Simple and effective. } 9. fxe4 { runs into } 9... Qh4+
{ when White's position collapses. } 10. Kf1 Qxe4
{ Black has an extra pawn and White's king is in no man's land on f1. White has no development let alone any compensation, and thus the second player is already winning. }
