1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3
{ Threatens to expand in the center with e2-e4, which we immediately stop with }
2... d5 3. Bg5
{ The Veresov or Richter-Veresov variation is named after the German IM Kurt Richter and the Soviet Union GM Gavriil Veresov, who regularly played 2. Nc3 3. Bg5 for over a quarter of a century. Despite never being popular at the top level, several strong players have essayed this variation from time to time. Most notably, the soviet GM David Bronstein played the Veresov against GM Gavriil Veresov himself in 1959.  White's main intention is to expand in the center with e2-e4. However, there is one big drawback behind developing the knight to c3, namely that White can no longer break with c2-c4. As we’re about to see, White will find it very hard to break with e4, meaning the knight frequently ends up being completely misplaced on c3. }
3... h6
{ Black has several other good options after 3. Bg5 such as 3...Nbd7 and 3...c5. Despite being 8x less common than 3...Nbd7, 3...h6 is one of the top choices of the neural network engines. This stat also means White is much less likely to be well versed in the resulting structures. }
4. Bh4 { is worse than 4. Bxf6, which we'll tackle very soon. After } 4... Nbd7
{ White is already struggling to equalize. } 5. e3 e6 6. Nf3 Be7
