1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3
{ Threatens to expand in the center with e2-e4, which we immediately stop with }
2... d5 3. Bg5
{ The Veresov or Richter-Veresov variation is named after the German IM Kurt Richter and the Soviet Union GM Gavriil Veresov, who regularly played 2. Nc3 3. Bg5 for over a quarter of a century. Despite never being popular at the top level, several strong players have essayed this variation from time to time. Most notably, the soviet GM David Bronstein played the Veresov against GM Gavriil Veresov himself in 1959.  White's main intention is to expand in the center with e2-e4. However, there is one big drawback behind developing the knight to c3, namely that White can no longer break with c2-c4. As we’re about to see, White will find it very hard to break with e4, meaning the knight frequently ends up being completely misplaced on c3. }
3... h6
{ Black has several other good options after 3. Bg5 such as 3...Nbd7 and 3.. .c5. Despite being 8x less common than 3...Nbd7, 3...h6 is one of the top choices of the neural network engines. This stat also means White is much less likely to be well versed in the resulting structures. }
4. Bxf6 { is White's most popular move by a wide margin. } 4... exf6
{ Let us compare this with my recommendation vs the Trompowsky @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.Bg5  d5  3.Bxf6  exf6  You might be led to believe this is a favorable version for White since he got in Nc3 in exchange for ... h6, which isn't particularly useful. However, White's knight is completely misplaced on c3 and would much rather be on b1 in this position as it deprives White of playing c4. The problem is that White's e4 break simply doesn't work, meaning he has no way of challenging our center. }
5. e4 { White's standard break doesn't work on account of } 5... Bb4
{ The pawn on e4 is now hanging so White has two options: taking on d5 or protecting it with Bd3. }
6. Bd3
{ 6.exd5  is worse. After  6...Qxd5  7.Nf3  O-O  8.Be2  Qa5∓  White's knight is under fire and Black's bishops give him a clear advantage. }
6... c5 { Boom. White's center now collapses. } 7. dxc5
{ 7.exd5  is once again met by  7...Qxd5⩱ } 7... d4 8. a3
{ White has no option but to try and break the pin. } 8... Ba5 9. b4 dxc3 10.
bxa5 O-O { is awful for White. All his queenside pawns are weak and isolated. }
