[Black "Colle #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. e3
{ The Colle system, also known as the Colle-Koltanowski system, is named after the Belgian masters Edgard Colle and George Koltanowski.    Characterized by the moves 2. Nf3 and 3. e3, White usually develops his light-squared bishop to d3, the queenside knight to d2, and tries to engineer the pawn break e3-e4. White typically reinforces the d4 pawn with c2-c3 in response to ...c5, setting up a triangle or pyramidal pawn structure with pawns on f2, e3, d4, c3, and b2.    Nowadays, this variation is considered innocuous as it does not put any pressure on the center and restricts White’s dark-squared bishop. It is a popular system at the club level mainly because it can be learned very quickly and is of very low maintenance.   It is particularly ineffective against the fianchetto with 2...g6 as White lacks control over the key e5 square and the second player can quickly undermine White's center with the ...c5 break. }
3... Bg7 4. b3
{ aiming to quickly fianchetto the dark-squared bishop. This is not very good as the bishop is often restricted by White's d4 pawn. }
4... c5 5. Bb2 cxd4
{ is timely. By immediately capturing the d4 pawn and following up with ...d5, we make sure White's bishop on b2 does is blocked. }
6. exd4
{ is better than 6. Nxd4 since it doesn't surrender the center. The drawback is that the bishop on b2 is essentially staring at his own pawn. }
6... O-O { White can now develop his bishop to e2 or d3. } 7. Bd3
{ is not the best position for the bishop. As we're about to see, it's vulnerable to both ...Nb4 and ...Nh5-f4, the latter taking advantage of the fact that White's dark-squared bishop on b2 no longer controls the f4 square. }
7... d5 8. O-O Nc6 9. a3
{ stopping ...Nb4.   9.Nbd2  can be met with  9...Nh5⩱  when ...Nf4 is coming next. }
9... Nh5
{ is very strong. Our knight is heading to f4 to attack the bishop on d3 before White has played Re1. White won't have enough time to safely tuck the bishop away on f1. }
10. Re1 { The problem is that } 10... Bg4 { Breaking the pin with } 11. Be2
{ is practically forced.   11.Bf1?  is the move White would like to play but it fails to  11...Bxf3  12.Qxf3  drops the d4 pawn.   Even worse is  12.gxf3?  as after  12...e6−+  White's king is in big trouble with ...Qg5 and ...Nf4 coming next.  12...Nxd4  13.Qd1  e5∓  Black is a clean pawn up.   11.Nbd2?  drops the d4 pawn to  11...Nxd4∓   11.c3??  loses to  11...e5  12.dxe5  Nxe5  13.Be2  Nf4−+  when White's position collapses. }
11... Nf4 { with the idea  12.--  Nxe2  13.Qxe2  Bxd4  winning the d4 pawn. }
12. Nbd2 Qd7
{ Black is ready to break with ...e5 while White can hardly move.   For example, trying to break the pin with  13.h3?  already loses to  13...Bxh3  14.gxh3  Nxh3  15.Kf1  Qg4−+  with a decisive attack. }
