1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Bg5
{ The Torre attack, characterized by the early development of the bishop to g5.   White typically places his light-squared bishop on e2 or d3, the queenside knight on d2, and reinforces the d4 pawn with c2-c3. The first player then hopes to push forward with e2-e4 and start a kingside attack, taking advantage of the fact that the bishop on g5 can chop off knight on f6 – the main defender of Black’s king – at an opportune moment.  Out of all the Torre's in this course, this is arguably the best one. Notwithstanding, Black is doing very well in all the variations. }
3... Bg7 4. Nbd2 O-O
{ There is no need to prevent e4 with ...d5 since it's not a good option for White. }
5. e4 { is strongly met by } 5... d5 { undermining White's center. } 6. e5
{ is a mistake on account of } 6... Ne4 7. Nxe4
{ leads to an almost lost position after the sequence } 7... dxe4 8. Ng1 c5
{ immediately undermining White's center. } 9. c3
{ Also no good is  9.dxc5  Qa5+  10.c3  Nc6−+  will pick up both the ...e5 and ...c5 pawns. }
9... Nc6 10. Ne2 cxd4 11. cxd4 Bg4 { and White's center collapses. } *

