1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Bg5
{ The Torre attack, characterized by the early development of the bishop to g5.   White typically places his light-squared bishop on d3, the queenside knight on d2, and reinforces the d4 pawn with c2-c3. The first player then hopes to push forward with e2-e4 and start a kingside attack, taking advantage of the fact that the bishop on g5 can chop off knight on f6 – the main defender of Black’s king – at an opportune moment.  Out of all the Torre's in this course, this is arguably the best one. Notwithstanding, Black is doing very well in all the variations. }
3... Bg7 4. Nbd2 O-O
{ There is no need to prevent e4 with ...d5 since it's not a good option for White. }
5. e3 d5 { White has tried several moves in this position. } 6. Be2 Be6
{ is incredibly rare @@StartBracket@@with 1 only game in the 90s@@EndBracket@@ but one of the top choices of the neural network engines. Alternatives with ...Nbd7 and ...c5 have been played in hundreds of games and thus have quite a lot of theory, which we'll just sidestep. The idea is to play ...Nbd7 followed by ...c5 without having our bishop blocked in on c8. This is made possible because White put his bishop on g5, meaning Ng5 is not available. }
7. c4 dxc4
{ is an obvious novelty. We're ahead in development so why not make White waste more time recapturing the pawn? }
8. Bxc4
{ 8.e4  allows Black to hang on to an extra pawn with  8...c6  9.O-O  b5= }
8... Bxc4 9. Nxc4 Ne4 { Centralizing the knight with tempo. } 10. Bf4 Qd5 11.
Qc2 c5
{ followed by ...Rc8 and the only question is how much better Black is. } *

