1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Bg5
{ The Torre attack, characterized by the early development of the bishop to g5.   White typically places his light-squared bishop on d3, the queenside knight on d2, and reinforces the d4 pawn with c2-c3. The first player then hopes to push forward with e2-e4 and start a kingside attack, taking advantage of the fact that the bishop on g5 can chop off knight on f6 – the main defender of Black’s king – at an opportune moment.  Out of all the Torre's in this course, this is arguably the best one. Notwithstanding, Black is doing very well in all the variations. }
3... Bg7 4. Nbd2 O-O
{ There is no need to prevent e4 with .. .d5 since it's not a good option for White. }
5. c3 d5
{ is my preferred approach. The alternative setup with 5...d6 is also fully playable, but why not take up more space in the center? }
6. e3 Nbd7
{ It's time to discuss our plan. We have two pawn breaks available here, namely ...c5 and ...e5. Given that White's bishop is on g5 instead of f4, the ...e5 break is easy to achieve and more challenging for White to meet. We can prepare it with ...Re8. }
7. h3
{ This is the recommendation of FM Marko Makaj in his course 'Calm and Collected: 1. d4' here on Chessable. }
7... Re8 8. Bf4
{ Trying to prevent ...e5 is FM Marko Makaj's choice, but it doesn't really work. He only examines 8...c5 and neglects the following powerful idea }
8... Nh5
{ hitting White's bishop and preparing to go ...e5 anyways. Moving forward with }
9. Be5 { fails to stop ...e5. } 9... c6 10. Bxg7
{ 10.g4  also fails to prevent ...e5 after  10...Nhf6  11.Bh2  Ne4  12.Nxe4  dxe4  13.Nd2  e5=  when Black can easily take over. }
10... Nxg7 11. Bd3 e5
{ we get our break in and have at the very least comfortably equalized. Further details can be found in themain theoretical section of the course. }
