1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. g3
{ We will now examine the g3 system. This approach was, amongst others, recommended by IM Cristof Sielecki in the book and Chessable course Keep it Simple: 1.d4.  White delays  (and often entirely foregoes)  c2-c4, preferring to first develop his kingside and keep options open. The problem with such an approach is that it fails to fight for the center effectively, meaning Black has little trouble emerging out of the opening with a good position. }
3... Bg7 4. Bg2 O-O 5. b3
{ This early fianchetto is much less popular than  5.O-O  or  5.c4  the reason being that Black can immediately strike with }
5... c5 { undermining White's center. } 6. Bb2 cxd4 7. Nxd4 e5
{ This move has only been played once, but it is the strongest available. } 8.
Nf3
{ If  8.Nb5  then  Qa5+!  9.N1c3  d5⩱  gives Black the upper hand, ...d4 being a big threat. }
8... e4 9. Nd4
{ This position occurred in the game ½-½ @@StartBracket@@17@@EndBracket@@ Secula,V @@StartBracket@@2118@@EndBracket@@-Walkewitz,H @@StartBracket@@2241@@EndBracket@@ Bad Wiessee 1999. Here Black missed the strong }
9... e3 { which creates a lot of problems for White. } 10. f3
{ Letting the e-pawn live is relatively best.   Worse is  10.fxe3?!  as after  10...Ng4  11.Qd2  Qg5∓  Black has a big initiative. }
10... Qa5+ { is a strong move, disrupting White's development. } 11. c3
{ 11.Bc3  blocks the check but also takes the c3 square away from White's knight. After  11...Qc5  12.O-O  Nc6⩱  Black has the upper hand. }
11... Nc6 12. O-O d5
{ Next up is ...Re8 when Black is clearly better. The pawn on e3 is a thorn in White's side and both of his bishops are completely restricted. }
