1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. g3
{ We will now examine the g3 system. This approach was, amongst others, recommended by IM Cristof Sielecki in the book and Chessable course Keep it Simple: 1.d4.  White delays  (and often entirely foregoes)  c2-c4, preferring to first develop his kingside and keep options open. The problem with such an approach is that it fails to fight for the center effectively, meaning Black has little trouble emerging out of the opening with a good position. }
3... Bg7 4. Bg2 O-O 5. O-O
{ is a flexible move. White can play c2-c4 next and transpose into the mainlines or instead choose from a number of alternative setups. }
5... d5 { is the move Grunfeld players should make. } 6. Ne5
{ is a typical move in these fianchetto structures. White's knight is well placed on e5 and supports the c4 break.   6.c4  Transposes to one of the Grunfeld mainlines, which is beyond the scope of this course. }
6... Bf5 7. c4
{ is the only critical continuation.   7.c3  is obviously harmless. Black can follow suit with  7...c6  8.Nd2  and then neutralize White's knight on e5 with  8...Nbd7  9.Ndf3  Nxe5  10.Nxe5  Nd7= }
7... c5
{ is rare with only a handful of games in the database but very dynamic. It sets White problem as early as move 7. We will consider three possibilities: 8. e3, 8. dxc5 and 8. cxd5, which is already a novelty. }
8. dxc5 { makes little sense as } 8... Qc7 { forces White's knight back. } 9.
Nf3 { 9.Bf4?  runs into  9...g5∓  when the knight on e5 will drop. } 9... dxc4
{ Restores material equality. White needs to immediately go after the c4 pawn as Black is threatening to hold on to it after ...Qxc5. }
10. Qd4 Ne4 11. Qxc4 Qxc5 12. Qxc5 Nxc5
{ The assessment of this position is on the verge of a Black advantage. Black's bishops are incredibly strong. }
