[White "Quickstarter (1...Nf6 2...g6)"]
[Black "5. O-O  6. b3 #6 [for KID players] "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. g3
{ We will now examine the g3 system. This approach was, amongst others, recommended by IM Cristof Sielecki in the book and Chessable course Keep it Simple: 1.d4.  White delays  (and often entirely foregoes)  c2-c4, preferring to first develop his kingside and keep options open. The problem with such an approach is that it fails to fight for the center effectively, meaning Black has little trouble emerging out of the opening with a good position. }
3... Bg7 4. Bg2 O-O 5. O-O
{ is a flexible move. White can play c2-c4 next and transpose into the mainlines or instead choose from a number of alternative setups. }
5... d6
{ is the move King's Indian players should make. Grunfeld players should play 5...d5, which is coveredhere. }
6. b3
{ is White's most popular alternative to 6. c4. It has been played 3000+ times OTB and was recommended by IM Cristof Sielecki in the Chessable course 'Keep it Simple: 1.d4'. White wants to play Bb2 next to dissuade us from breaking in the center with ...e7-e5.   6.c4  transposes to a mainline in the King's Indian, which is outside the scope of this course. }
6... e5
{ This typical King's Indian break is my preferred approach.   The alternative break  6...c5  was recommended by GM Boris Avrukh in the book GM Repertoire: Beating 1.d4 sidelines but after  7.c4  e5  8.dxe5  dxe5  9.Bb2⩲  White has decent chances for a slight advantage. Avrukh goes on for several moves, reaching an endgame where Black is a pawn down but should hold with correct play. I see no need to give White such a possibility. }
7. dxe5 dxe5 8. Ba3 { is more incisive than 8. Bb2. } 8... Qxd1 9. Rxd1 Re8
{ Removes the rook from danger and covers the e5 pawn, which can be pushed to e4 at an opportune moment. White has two different approaches now: 10. Nc3 and 10. c4. }
10. c4
{ is more ambitious than 10. Nc3. White grabs some space before developing the knight to c3. }
10... e4 { Displaces White's knight. Next up is ...e3. } 11. Nd4 e3
{ Attempts to create a lot of weaknesses in White's structure. } 12. f3
{ Stopping ...Ng4 is best. It has the downside of restricting the light-squared bishop but White can activate it later on with f4.   12.f4  allows  12...Ng4  and after  13.Nc3  Nf2  14.Ndb5  Na6=  White already needs to be very careful to maintain the balance. }
12... a5
{ is a strong move, taking control of the b4 square and preparing to develop the knight to a6. }
13. Nc3 Na6
{ From ...a6, the knight controls the b4 and c5 squares and preemptively defends the c7 pawn against Nb5. }
14. Rac1 Bd7
{ This is Black's strongest move, which was not considered by IM Cristof Sielecki in the Chessable course 'Keep it Simple: 1.d4'. The bishop is well placed on d7, controlling the b5 square and supporting the ...a5-a4 break at an opportune moment.   14...c6!?  allows  15.Bd6  with the idea Na4-b6 next. 'White has the easier game here' was Christof Sielecki's assessment. While Black is still okay, there is no need to weaken the b6 and d6 squares with 14...c6. }
15. Ndb5 h5 16. f4 Rab8
{ Steps out of the long diagonal. Black is very comfortable and can consider ...Bg4 next to attack White's weak pawn on e2. }
