1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Nbd2
{ intends to take over the center with e2-e4, which Black should immediately stop with }
3... d5 4. e3
{ 4.b4  is another possible move order, when  4...Bg7  5.e3  a5  transposes to the text.   4.c4  is innocuous. Black can immediately strike with  4...c5  when White is likely regretting putting his knight on d2.  5.cxd5   5.dxc5  Bg7  6.e3  O-O⩱  followed by ...Na6xc5 is very comfortable.  cxd4  6.Qa4+  Qd7  7.Qxd4  Qxd5=  is an endgame where only Black can be better. }
4... Bg7 5. b4
{ is the only independent plan worth considering. White is trying to clamp down on the c5 square, preventing Black from executing his natural break.   5.Bd3  O-O  6.O-O  c5  7.c3  transposes to the Colle. }
5... a5
{ is an important move, immediately undermining White's pawn before he can establish a blockade with Nb3. }
6. b5 c5
{ and Black gets his break in anyway, meaning White's strategy with b4 wasn't effective. We will examine White's three main possibilities, namely 7. dxc5, 7. bxc6 and 7. c4. }
7. bxc6 Nxc6 { is the most logical recapture, developing a piece. } 8. Ba3
{ 8.Bb5  looks active but the bishop isn't doing anything here. After  8...O-O  9.O-O  Bf5  10.Bxc6  bxc6  11.Ne5  Qc7=  Black comfortably equalized and went on to win in 0-1 @@StartBracket@@36@@EndBracket@@ Roy Chowdhury,S @@StartBracket@@2469@@EndBracket@@ -Karavade,E @@StartBracket@@2359@@EndBracket@@ Canberra 2009.   Similarly, after  8.Be2  O-O  9.O-O  Bf5=  gives Black a great game. He can aim to target the c2 pawn with ...Rc8 and ...Nb4 next. }
8... O-O 9. Be2
{ 9.Rb1  can be met with  9...Bf5  and after  10.Rxb7  Nb4  11.Bxb4  axb4  12.Bd3  Rxa2=  the entire queenside is vacuumed off the board. }
9... Bf5 10. c3 Rb8
{ with the idea ...b5-b4 and ...Ne4. Black had an excellent game in ½-½ @@StartBracket@@70@@EndBracket@@ Chadaev,N @@StartBracket@@2556@@EndBracket@@-Bartel, M @@StartBracket@@2658@@EndBracket@@ Moscow 2012. }
