1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. b4
{ is a relatively obscure sideline but one that packs some danger if Black does not pay sufficient attention to White's plans. With 3. b4, White prevents the immediate ...c5 break and wants to also make ...e5 hard to achieve by putting his bishop on b2. }
3... Bg7 4. Bb2
{ 4.e3  O-O  5.Bb2  is another possible move order, which will transpose to the text. }
4... O-O 5. e3 d6
{ Black has developed in typical King's Indian fashion. However, rather than aim for the traditional ...e5 break, we're actually going to undermine White's queenside with ...c5. }
6. Be2 { is White's most popular continuation, clearing the way for O-O. } 6...
c5 { forces White to clarify the tension. } 7. bxc5
{ Worse is  7.dxc5?!  as after  7...dxc5  then he risks landing in trouble,as in the following example  8.Qxd8  Rxd8  9.bxc5  Ne4⩱  Black will recoup the c-pawn while White will be left with split queenside pawns. The pawn on c2 on the open c-file will be very vulnerable. }
7... dxc5 8. O-O
{ 8.dxc5  Qxd1+  9.Bxd1  Ne4⩱  Black will pick up the c-pawn next with a slight advantage. White has nothing to show for the split pawns on the queenside.   8.c4  cxd4  9.exd4  Nc6  10.O-O  transposes to the text. }
8... cxd4
{ is a timely recapture, intending to leave White with a weak pawn on d4 that can be targeted with ...Nc6, ...Qb6 and ...Rd8. }
9. exd4
{ 9.Nxd4  can be met with  9...Nc6  10.Nxc6  bxc6=  followed by ...Qc7 and ...Rd8 with no problems. }
9... Nc6 10. c4 Qb6
{ gave Black an excellent game in 0-1 @@StartBracket@@51@@EndBracket@@ Bryzgalin,K @@StartBracket@@2439@@EndBracket@@-Santos Latasa,J @@StartBracket@@2584@@EndBracket@@ Rome 2018. Black followed up with ...Rd8 and ...Ne4 with good play against White's d4 pawn. }
