1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Nc3 d5
{ is our default reaction when White develops his knight to c3, taking control over the e4 square and thus preventing e2-e4. }
4. Bg5
{ Writing this from the other side of the pond, I'm pretty clueless when it comes to British slang but detailed analysis shows that White is under serious pressure after }
4... Ne4
{ which is 5 times less popular than 4...Bg7 but much stronger. While 4...Bg7 comfortably equalizes, 4...Ne4 gives Black a significant advantage @@StartBracket@@or even an outright winning position@@EndBracket@@ in every single line. }
5. Nxe4
{ is the most popular move at the club level. It is however fairly dubious as }
5... dxe4
{ forces White's knight back, which has no good place to retreat to. } 6. Ng1
{ at least does not lose the d4 pawn. Nevertheless, if White is forced to undevelop his pieces, then the opening has obviously been a disaster. }
6... Bg7 7. c3 { 7.e3  c5  8.c3  O-O  transposes to the text. } 7... O-O 8. e3
{ is most logical, preparing to complete development with Bc4 and Ne2. Notice how our pawn on e4 stops White from developing the knight to f3, which is its best square.  Alternatively   8.g3  intending to fianchetto the light-squared bishop is strongly met by  8...Qd5!  hitting White's bishop and threatening ...e4-e3, thus forcing  9.Be3  and after  9...Nd7  10.Bg2  Nf6∓  Black is clearly better. The pawn on e4 gives the second player a big space advantage and severely restricts White's pieces. }
8... c5 { increases the pressure on the d4 pawn. Next up is ...Nc6. } 9. Bc4
Nc6 10. Ne2
{ This position was reached in the correspondence game 0-1 @@StartBracket@@35@@EndBracket@@ Jina,J @@StartBracket@@2113@@EndBracket@@ -Eilmes,D @@StartBracket@@2349@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2005, where Black the opportunity to gain the bishop pair advantage with }
10... Na5 11. Bb3 Nxb3 12. axb3 h6
{ Black is clearly better with the extra space afforded by the e4 pawn and the two bishops. Next up are ...Be6 and ...Qb6 to attack the weak pawn on b3. }
