1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Nc3 d5
{ is our default reaction when White develops his knight to c3, taking control over the e4 square and thus preventing e2-e4. }
4. Bg5
{ Writing this from the other side of the pond, I'm pretty clueless when it comes to British slang but detailed analysis shows that White is under serious pressure after }
4... Ne4
{ which is 5 times less popular than 4...Bg7 but much stronger. While 4...Bg7 comfortably equalizes, 4...Ne4 gives Black a significant advantage @@StartBracket@@or even an outright winning position@@EndBracket@@ in every single line. }
5. Bf4
{ is the most popular move at the master level and basically an admission that 4. Bg5 was not a good move. If White wanted to place his bishop on f4, he should have done so on move 4! }
5... Nxc3
{ permanently damages White's pawn structure just like in the 5. Bh4 variation. The doubled c-pawns will remain a weakness for the rest of the game.   5...Bg7  is playable but the text is far stronger. }
6. bxc3 c5
{ immediately undermines White's center. Black will be able to pressure it with ...Bg7 and .. .Qa5 in the near future. }
7. e3
{ is the most popular continuation.   7.Qd2  with the idea ...Bh6 has also been tried. However, after  7...Bg7  8.Bh6  Bxh6  9.Qxh6  Apart from wasting valuable time, White did not achieve anything with this Bh5 excursion. In fact  9...Qa5∓  forces White's queen back with a clear advantage. White has nothing to show for his crippled pawn structure.   7.dxc5?!  is obviously terrible, leaving White with tripled pawns on an open file.  7...Bg7  8.Be5  f6  9.Bg3  Qa5∓  with a clear advantage for Black. }
7... Bg7 8. Bb5+
{ is the most popular position for the light-squared bishop. The alternatives below give Black at least a clear advantage.   8.Be2  is very passive. After  8...Qa5  9.Qd2  Nd7  10.O-O  O-O∓  Black is clearly better. White has less space and no compensation for his crippled pawns.   8.Bd3?!  is an OTB novelty and not a particularly good one as it runs straight into  8...c4  9.Be2  Qa5  10.Qd2  Protecting the pawn  10...Nd7!  Heading to f6 and then e4, which will for White's queen and pawn.  11.O-O  Nf6  12.Be5  fails to solve White's problems as after  12...Ne4  13.Qe1  f6  14.Bg3  Qxc3-+  the c3 pawn falls anyway. }
8... Nd7 9. Ne5
{ is the logical continuation after 8. Bb5. White is trying to exchange off as many minor pieces as possible to simplify the position, hoping that Black won't have enough material to attack White's weak queenside pawns. However, the first player won't have such luck.   9.O-O?!  makes little sense as after  9...O-O∓  White's bishop on b5 isn't doing anything constructive and is even liable to tempo moves like ...Qa5. }
9... O-O 10. Nxd7 Bxd7 11. a4
{ is White's best chance. The idea is that after ...Bxb5, Black no longer has the option of playing ...Qa5 and White can try to make use of the a-file. Notwithstanding, White is still in dire straits.   Alternatively  11.Be2  can be met with  11...Qa5  attacking the pawn on c3.  12.Qd2  Rfc8∓  is clearly better for Black. White has nothing to show for the crippled c-pawns. }
11... Bxb5 12. axb5 Qd7
{ gives Black a clear advantage with ...Rfc8 coming next. The pawn on b5 is very weak and White's doubled c-pawns are also big targets. Further details can be found in themain part of the course. }
