1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 { The London system. } 2... g6 3. Nc3
{ In this chapter, we'll cover all the setups with White's knight on c3. } 3...
d5
{ Now we will examine each of White's three main options: 4. e3, 4. Qd2 and 4. Nf3. }
4. e3
{ White's most popular choice, which is 3x as common as the alternatives 4. Qd2 and 4. Nf3 that we already tackled. }
4... Bg7 5. h4 { Pushing Harry is ever popular. } 5... O-O 6. h5 c5
{ Thematic. This central reaction to White's flank attack works wonders here.  And not   6...Nxh5?  as after  7.Rxh5!  gxh5  8.Qxh5→  White has a very dangerous attack. }
7. dxc5 { This pawn capture should always be examined. } 7... Qa5
{ Our usual queen sortie in response to ...dxc5. Our immediate threat is ...Nxh5 followed by ...Bxc3. Apart from this, White needs to constantly be wary of ...Ne4, exploiting the pin along the e1-a5 diagonal.  This move was not considered by GM Simon Williams in the Chessbase FritzTrainer 'The London System with 2.Bf4'. }
8. hxg6 hxg6 9. Qd2 { White does best in immediately breaking the pin. } 9...
Nc6 10. Nf3 Qxc5 11. O-O-O
{ is most common at the club level, but it once again runs into the powerful knight jump }
11... Ne4 12. Qxd5 { 12.Nxe4?!  dxe4  13.Nd4  Rd8∓  is awful for White. } 12...
Qxd5 13. Rxd5 Nxf2
{ Equal material but not an equal position. White's pawn structure has suffered irreparable damaged. }
