{ White has a zoo of different move orders, whether to start with h3, include c3 or not, play Nbd2 first, develop the light-squared bishop to e2, d3 or c4, etc. This can easily catch a Black player off guard and trick him into a variation he did not want to enter. Worry not, we're going to avoid all of this. To make this repertoire practical, I chose to recommend a setup with ...d6, ...c5 followed by ...Qb6, which we'll play in almost all the lines where White plays e3. Not only is this easy to learn and remember, but it's also one of the top choices of the neural network engines. In the rare cases where White opts for e4, we'll mostly aim for a quick ...e7-e5 instead of breaking with ...c5. }
4. h3
{ is White's second most popular continuation, creating a square for the dark-squared bishop to drop back to in case of ...Nh5. }
4... O-O 5. e3 c5 { Our typical pawn break, fighting for the center. } 6. c3 d6
7. Be2 Qb6
{ is my preferred setup, immediately putting pressure on the b2 pawn. It's also the top choice of the neural network engines.  Another good setup for Black is fianchettoing the light-squared bishop with   7...b6  which was recommended by GM Boris Avrukh in the book 'GM Repertoire: Beating 1. d4 Sidelines' published in 2012. }
8. Qb3 { is more active than 8. Qc1 and four times as popular. } 8... Be6
{ Avoiding the queen exchange with } 9. Qa3 { is strongly met by } 9... cxd4
10. cxd4
{ immediately landed White in trouble following   10.exd4  isn't much better. After  10...Qc6!  11.Nbd2  b5⩱  followed by ...a5 leaves White's queen in quite a predicament. }
10... Nd5 11. Bg3 Nb4 { Note that } 12. Qa4
{ fails to solve White's problems on account of } 12... Bf5
{ with the dual threat of ...Nc2 and ...Nd3. } *

