[Round "?"]
[White "1. Stonewall + Rare 2nd moves (1...d5)"]
[Black "2. e3 5. Nf3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. e3
{ is typically an indication White is aiming for the Stonewall. He can of course transpose into the Colle by playing Nf3 later on. }
2... Nf6 3. Bd3 c5 { immediately pressuring the center. } 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3
{ instead of sticking with the Stonewall, White decides to head for a Colle setup. }
5... Bg4
{ when White uses the 2. e3 move order, it makes sense for us to develop the light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain. }
6. O-O e6 7. Nbd2
{ If  7.h3  we can simply retreat the bishop with  7...Bh5=  followed by ...Bd6 and ...O-O. }
7... Bd6 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. e4 { may look logical but doesn't work very well. }
9... O-O 10. Qc2 dxe4 { resolves the central tension in our favor. } 11. Nxe4
{ is the better recapture. } 11... Bxf3 12. Nxc5
{ Worse is  12.gxf3?!  Nxe4  13.Bxe4  Qh4∓  when White's king is in trouble. }
12... Qd5 13. gxf3 Qxc5
{ followed by ...Ne5 gives Black the upper hand. White's kingside pawn structure is severely compromised. }
