[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Stonewall + Rare 2nd moves (1...d5)"]
[Black "2. e3 5. Nf3 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. e3
{ is typically an indication White is aiming for the Stonewall. He can of course transpose into the Colle by playing Nf3 later on. }
2... Nf6 3. Bd3 c5 { immediately pressuring the center. } 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3
{ instead of sticking with the Stonewall, White decides to head for a Colle setup. }
5... Bg4
{ when White uses the 2. e3 move order, it makes sense for us to develop the light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain. }
6. O-O e6 7. Nbd2 Bd6 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. b4
{ is reminiscent of the Meran variation in the Semi-Slav. } 9... Bd6 10. h3 Bh5
11. a3 O-O { completing development. } 12. Bb2
{ 12.Be2  a5⩱  gives Black good play. } 12... Ne5
{ Our plan is to attack White's backward c-pawn. The first step is to exchange the knights to clear the e5 square for our bishop. }
13. Be2 Nxf3+ 14. Bxf3 Bxf3 15. Qxf3
{ The alternative recapture  15.Nxf3  changes very little. After  15...Rc8⩱  Black is clearly for choice as White won't be able to break with c4. White's dark-squared bishop on b2 is severely restricted. }
15... Be5
{ followed by ...Rc8 is very pleasant. White won't be able to get c4 in, meaning the backward pawn on c3 is a target, and White's dark-squared bishop is very passive. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Stonewall + Rare 2nd moves (1...d5)"]
[Black "2. a3 Prie attack"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. a3
{ The so-called Grand Prie Attack, irreverently named after and by the French Grandmaster Eric Prie himself! He racked up a surprising score with this flexible move, which has the idea of meeting ...c5 with dxc5 and following up with b2-b4 when White has good chances to hold onto the c5 pawn. However, as long as Black avoids this, he'll easily emerge out of the opening with zero problems.   Another possible move order is  2.Nf3  Nf6  3.a3  e6  which transposes to the text. }
2... Nf6
{ And not  2...c5  because of  3.dxc5!  when a3 turns out to be a useful move. Black will find it hard to recoup the c-pawn with b2-b4 coming next. }
3. Nf3
{ While Black should not go for the immediate ...c5, he can prepare it with }
3... e6 4. Bg5
{ White can also develop akin to the London system with  4.Bf4  but here the move a3 is nothing but a waste of a valuable tempo. After  4...c5  5.e3  Nc6  6.c3  Bd6  7.Bxd6  Qxd6=  Black is very comfortable and already threatening to take over with ...e5. }
4... c5 5. e3 cxd4
{ is simple and effective. The ensuing Carlsbad structure is innocuous as White has insufficient control over the e5 square. Thus, the typical plans with Ne5 are not available. }
6. exd4 Nc6 7. Bd3 h6
{ Puts the question to the bishop, which does not have many good squares to retreat to. }
8. Be3
{ 8.Bf4  runs into  8...g5  9.Bg3  Ne4⩱  which will pick up White's dark-squared bishop.  Similarly   8.Bh4  g5  9.Bg3  Ne4⩱  will give Black the two bishops advantage.   8.Bxf6  gives up the bishop pair. After  8...Qxf6  9.O-O  Bd6  10.c3  O-O=  Black can engineer the ...e5 break with ...Re8. }
8... Bd6
{ takes control over the e5 square, preventing White from installing his knight on this outpost. Black can complete development with ...b6, ...Bb7, and ...O-O. }
9. h3 b6 10. O-O Bb7
{ followed by ...O-O and ...Rc8 is very comfortable. Black can later look to jump into the c4 and e4 squares with ...Na5-c4 and ...Ne4.   A sample continuation is  11.c3  O-O  12.Nbd2  Rc8  13.Re1  Re8  14.Qe2  Qc7  15.Rac1  Na5=  when Black can jump into c4 and e4 with excellent prospects.  The Prie 'attack' is, as expected, completely harmless. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Stonewall + Rare 2nd moves (1...d5)"]
[Black "2. f4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. f4
{ dramatically weakens the e4 square and is an even worse move order than the regular Stonewall via 2. e3 as we'll be the first to occupy the h7-b1 diagonal first with ...Bf5. }
2... Nf6 3. Nf3 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. c3 cxd4
{ clarifies the central tension in our favor as White will find it difficult to entrench his knight on e5. }
6. exd4
{ is the only sensible recapture.   Worse is  6.cxd4  Bf5  as White will now constantly have to watch out for ...Nb4. After  7.Be2  e6  8.O-O  Be7  9.Ne5  O-O  10.Nc3   10.Nd2  runs into  10...Nb4∓  h6  11.g4  Bh7∓  gives Black a clear advantage as White has only weakened his kingside. For example  12.Qe1  Rc8  13.Qg3?  Nxe5  14.fxe5  Ne4-+  gives Black an overwhelming position. }
6... Bf5
{ As mentioned earlier, we're the first to occupy the key h7-b1 diagonal, meaning White has zero chances to create a kingside attack. }
7. Be2
{ 7.Bd3?!  is a strategic mistake as White's light-squares will be critically weak after the bishop trade.  7...e6  8.O-O  Bd6  9.Bxf5  exf5  10.Re1+  Kf8⩱  Yes, White displaced our king but this is only temporary as we'll safely tuck it away with ...g6 and ...Kg7. More importantly, White's light-squares are permanently weak. }
7... e6 8. O-O Bd6 9. Ne5 Qb6
{ is a ruthless Stockfish suggestion. Black is threatening to win material with ...Nxe5 following by ... Bxe5, exploiting the fact that the d4 pawn is pinned.  Another good option is   9...h5  ruling out ...g4. After  10.Nd2  g6  11.Ndf3  O-O  12.h3  Kg7⩱  Black is at least slightly better as White's kingside play has been brought to a halt.  Also possible is   9...h6  10.Nd2  Qc7  11.Ndf3  Ne4  12.Qa4  O-O  13.Nd2  f6∓  booted White's knight from e5 and gave Black the upper hand in 1/ 2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@42@@EndBracket@@ Kritz,L @@StartBracket@@2424@@EndBracket@@ -Vallejo Pons,F @@StartBracket@@2554@@EndBracket@@ Oropesa del Mar 2000. }
10. Qb3
{ 10.g4  loses a pawn to  10...Bxb1  11.Rxb1  Nxe5  12.fxe5  Bxe5∓   Stepping out of the diagonal with  10.Kh1  can simply be met with  10...O-O  11.Nd2  h6  12.Ndf3  Ne7∓  with an advantage. White's knights are stepping onto each other's toes. }
10... Qc7
{ So what did Black achieve with ...Qb6-c7? It may seem like a waste of tempo as we could have played ...Qc7 directly. The point, however, is that White's queen is completely misplaced on b3. In this structure, White wants to attack on the kingside and typically plays Qe1-h4 which is not possible here as the queen is all the way over on the queenside. }
11. Nd2 O-O 12. Ndf3 Rab8
{ prepares to expand on the queenside with ...b5-b4. White has no chances of mounting a kingside attack as his queen is on the wrong side of the board. As such, Black is clearly for choice. }
