1. d4 d5 2. b4
{ does stop Black from undermining the d4 pawn with ...c5 but dramatically weakens White's queenside. }
2... e5
{ immediately opens up the dark-squared bishop. The b4 pawn is about to drop while we'll easily recoup the e5 pawn. }
3. dxe5 Bxb4+ 4. c3
{ Blocking with  4.Bd2  will drop the e5 pawn after the following sequence.  4...Bxd2+  5.Nxd2  Ne7  6.Ngf3  Nbc6  7.e3  O-O  8.Bd3  Ng6  9.O-O  Qe7∓  The e5 pawn is about to drop when Black will be a clean pawn up.  Similarly   4.Nd2  c5  5.e3  Nc6  6.Rb1  Nge7  7.Ngf3  O-O  8.Be2  Bc3  9.Rb3  Bxe5∓  leaves Black with an extra pawn. }
4... Ba5 5. Nf3 Ne7
{ The f6 square is not available but the knight will be very well placed on g6. }
6. Bf4
{ 6.e3  fails to keep the e5 pawn alive after  Nbc6  7.Be2  O-O  8.O-O  Ng6∓ }
6... Bg4 { Prepares to exchange off one of the key defenders of the e5 pawn. }
7. e3 Bxf3 8. Qxf3 c6 9. Bd3 Nd7 { The e5 pawn is now doomed. } 10. O-O Ng6 11.
Qg3 O-O
{ Next up is ...Qe7 when the e5 pawn will drop. White will have nothing to show for the pawn deficit. }
