1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3
{ The Colle system, also known as the Colle-Koltanowski system, is named after the Belgian masters Edgard Colle and George Koltanowski.    Characterized by the moves 2. Nf3 and 3. e3, White usually develops his light-squared bishop to d3, the queenside knight to d2, and tries to engineer the pawn break e3-e4. White typically reinforces the d4 pawn with c2-c3 in response to …c5, setting up a triangle or pyramidal pawn structure with pawns on f2, e3, d4, c3, and b2.    Nowadays, this variation is considered innocuous as it does not put any pressure on the center and restricts White’s dark-squared bishop. It is a popular system at the club level mainly because it can be learned very quickly and is of very low maintenance.   White's setup is definitely solid but also very unambitious.   3.c3  is an attempt to move order us out of our repertoire. We'll avoid any unfavorable transpositions with  3...Bf5  which has been played in 800+ OTB games. }
3... c5
{ is both principled and very practical, immediately fighting for the center. I always felt there was no need to go for 3...e6, which has a lot more theory and leads to stale positions where it is difficult to play for a win. }
4. dxc5
{ doesn't pose any significant problems as White won't be able to hold onto the c5 pawn. }
4... e6 5. b4
{ Heading for a reversed Noteboom.   The Noteboom is a variation of the Slav that arises after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  c6  3.Nc3  e6  4.Nf3  dxc4  5.e3  b5   Harmless is  5.c4  Bxc5= }
5... a5 { undermines White's construction. } 6. c3 axb4 7. cxb4 b6
{ breaks apart White's pawn chain. } 8. Bb5+
{ was recommended by GM Milos Pavlovic in 'The Modernized Colle-Zukertort Attack'.   8.cxb6  runs into  8...Bxb4+  followed by ... Qxb6 when White has been left with a weak, isolated pawn on a2. }
8... Bd7 9. Bxd7+ Nbxd7 10. a4
{ 10.O-O  has little independent value.  10...bxc5  11.b5  Bd6  12.a4  transposes to the text. }
10... bxc5 11. b5
{ White is banking on his two connected passed pawns giving him enough compensation for the lack of central control. }
11... Bd6
{ Next up are ...O-O and ...Qc7 completing development.   11...g5!?  in this position is very interesting if you're looking for a spicier alternative. }
12. O-O
{ White can also start with  12.Bb2  or  12.Nbd2  but they'll likely transpose into each other }
12... O-O 13. Nbd2 Qc7 14. Bb2 e5
{ is a complex position that was not covered in GM Milos Pavlovic's book and Chessable course 'The Modernized Colle-Zukertort' nor in the book 'A Killer Chess Opening Repertoire' by GM Aaron Summerscale and Sverre Johnsen. Black has full control over the center while White's queenside pawns are well contained.   A sample continuation with precise play by both sides is  14...e5  15.e4  c4  16.Qc2  Rfc8  17.Rfc1  Bb4=  with a good game. }
