1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3
{ The Colle system, also known as the Colle-Koltanowski system, is named after the Belgian masters Edgard Colle and George Koltanowski.    Characterized by the moves 2. Nf3 and 3. e3, White usually develops his light-squared bishop to d3, the queenside knight to d2, and tries to engineer the pawn break e3-e4. White typically reinforces the d4 pawn with c2-c3 in response to …c5, setting up a triangle or pyramidal pawn structure with pawns on f2, e3, d4, c3, and b2.    Nowadays, this variation is considered innocuous as it does not put any pressure on the center and restricts White’s dark-squared bishop. It is a popular system at the club level mainly because it can be learned very quickly and is of very low maintenance.   White's setup is definitely solid but also very unambitious.   3.c3  is an attempt to move order us out of our repertoire. We'll avoid any unfavorable transpositions with  3...Bf5  which has been played in 800+ OTB games. }
3... c5
{ is both principled and very practical, immediately fighting for the center. I always felt there was no need to go for 3...e6, which has a lot more theory and leads to stale positions where it is difficult to play for a win. }
4. c3
{ White establishes the Triangle setup, a trademark of the Colle system. } 4...
e6
{ Black does best in delaying ...Nc6 so as not to run into dxc5. My preferred setup is to fianchetto the light-squared bishop with ...b6 and ...Bb7, place the dark-squared bishop on e7 and castle short. We can then decide where best to place our knight on b8, which is usually developed to d7. }
5. Nbd2 b6
{ intending to quickly fianchetto the light-squared bishop. This will make it hard for White to achieve the e3-e4 break in the future. }
6. Bd3 Bb7 7. O-O Be7
{ clearing the way for ...O-O. White has played several moves in this position and we'll examine the two most popular ones, which are 8. Ne5 and 8. Qe2. }
8. Qe2 { intending to break with e4. } 8... O-O
{ There is no need for us to prevent White's e4 break since it fails to bring the first player anything of value. }
9. e4
{ The only continuation worth training as the alternatives are completely harmless.   9.dxc5  bxc5  10.e4  Nc6  11.Re1  Qc7=  followed by ...a5 and ...Rd8 gives Black easy play.   9.Ne5  Nbd7  10.f4  Ne4=  is a position we've seen before. Black is completely fine. }
9... dxe4 10. Nxe4 cxd4
{ is the simplest, getting rid of all the central pawns. } 11. Nxd4 Nc6
{ Black had comfortably equalized in the correspondence game ½-½ @@StartBracket@@48@@EndBracket@@ Wittal,W @@StartBracket@@2376@@EndBracket@@-Zidu,J @@StartBracket@@2553@@EndBracket@@ Remote email 2014. }
