1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. c3
{ is an attempt to move order us out of our repertoire.   For example, if we play  3...c5  then after  4.Bf4  we've transposed to a line of the London that's not covered in the course. }
3... Bf5
{ Adopting a reversed London is a practical solution, avoiding any unpleasant transpositions. It's also very logical as the bishop is very active on f5 and controls the key e4 square.   White has two main moves in this position, namely  4.Qb3  and  4.Bf4  . }
4. Bf4
{ is White's second most popular move in this position. It transposes to a completely harmless variation of the London system. Natural developing moves give Black a great game.   4.Bg5  is probably the lamest version of the Torre ever. After  4...Ne4  5.Bh4  c6=  followed by ...Qb6 is very comfortable. }
4... e6 5. e3 Be7
{ We're going to castle short next and can then break with ...c5.   5...Bd6  is also playable. }
6. Be2 O-O 7. O-O c5 { The standard pawn break. } 8. Nbd2 h6
{ A typical move, making space for the bishop in case of Nh4. Next up is ...Nc6 with a comfortable game. }
