[White "2. Colle (1...d5)"]
[Black "3. c3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. c3
{ is an attempt to move order us out of our repertoire.   For example, if we play  3...c5  then after  4.Bf4  we've transposed to a line of the London that's not covered in the course. }
3... Bf5
{ is a practical solution, avoiding any unpleasant transpositions. It's also very logical as the bishop is very active on f5 and controls the key e4 square.   White has two main moves in this position, namely  4.Qb3  and  4.Bf4 }
4. Qb3
{ tries to exploit the drawback of 3...Bf5, that is the fact that the b7 pawn is no longer defended. }
4... Qc8 5. Bf4
{ The alternative bishop development  5.Bg5  can be met with natural moves like  5...Nbd7  6.e3  e6  7.Nbd2  h6  8.Bf4  Be7  followed by ...O-O with a comfortable game. }
5... c5
{ intending to hit White's queen with ...c4 next, gaining space on the queenside. }
6. Nbd2 c4 7. Qd1
{ If  7.Qa4+  then simply  7...Qc6  8.Qxc6+  Nxc6=  is very pleasant. } 7... h6
{ is a useful move, creating a square for our light-squared bishop on h7 in case of Nh4. }
8. Ne5 Nc6 9. e3 e6
{ followed by ...Be7 and ...O-O with an excellent game. Black can play on the queenside with ...b5-b4. White's usual counter to this plan consists of breaking with e4, which is very hard to achieve when our bishop is outside the pawn chain on f5. }
