1. d4 d5 2. Bg5
{ This early bishop development is known as the Pseudo-Trompowsky. This variation has also been called the Levitsky Attack, named after the Russian GM and 1911 Russian Champion Stepan Levitsky. This variation has also been dubbed the Hodgson Attack as it was played extensively by English GM Julian Hodgson. Other names for this variation are the Queen's Bishop Attack or simply the Bishop attack.    White’s main idea behind  2.Bg5  is to meet  2...Nf6  with  3.Bxf6  damaging Black’s kingside pawn structure.   This theme is analogous to one of the mainlines of the Trompowsky variation @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.Bg5  d5  3.Bxf6  exf6  However, unlike the Trompowsky, our knight is not yet on f6. This is a crucial difference, enabling us to instead immediately knock back White’s bishop with }
2... f6
{ is Black's best move. We are going to consider the three main bishop retreats   3.Bh4  played in 500+ OTB games   3.Bf4  seen in 400+ OTB games   and  3.Bd2  essayed in 50+ OTB games. }
*

