1. d4 d5 2. Bg5
{ This early bishop development is known as the Pseudo-Trompowsky. This variation has also been called the Levitsky Attack, named after the Russian GM and 1911 Russian Champion Stepan Levitsky. This variation has also been dubbed the Hodgson Attack as it was played extensively by English GM Julian Hodgson. Other names for this variation are the Queen's Bishop Attack or simply the Bishop attack.  White’s main idea behind 2. Bg5 is to meet 2...Nf6 with 3. Bxf6, damaging Black’s kingside pawn structure.   This theme is analogous to one of the mainlines of the Trompowsky variation @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.Bg5  d5  3.Bxf6  exf6  However, unlike the Trompowsky, our knight is not yet on f6. This is a crucial difference, enabling us to instead immediately knock back White’s bishop with }
2... f6
{ After this move, White @@StartBracket@@no typo!@@EndBracket@@ is already struggling to maintain the balance. }
3. Bf4
{ The engines are already claiming White is worse after this retreat. I'll do my best to convince you of the veracity of this assessment in the next couple of variations. }
3... Nc6 4. Nf3 { is White's most popular move by a large margin. } 4... g5 5.
Bg3 { The alternatives are considerably worse. } 5... h5
{ This is stronger than the immediate 5...g4. Another example of Nimzowitsch's famous saying: 'The threat is stronger than the execution.' }
6. h3 Nh6
{ Unorthodox but very strong. The knight is coming to f5, where it'll attack White's bishop and pressure the d4 pawn. }
7. e3 Nf5 8. Bh2 e5
{ Taking over the center. It's not often Black has 4 pawns on the 5th rank by move 8!  Watch out   8...g4?  is a big mistake.  9.hxg4  hxg4  10.Bxc7!  is a bolt from the blue  10...Qxc7  11.Rxh8±  when White is much better. }
9. dxe5 g4 10. Nd4 { Now both captures on d4 give Black the advantage. } 10...
Ncxd4
{ also leads to a Black advantage.   10...Nfxd4  is mymain recommendation. }
11. exd4 g3 { A thematic pawn sacrifice. } 12. Bxg3
{ 12.fxg3?  fxe5  13.dxe5  Qg5−+  is awful for White as the threats ...Nxg3 and ...Ne3 are hard to meet. }
12... Nxg3 13. fxg3 fxe5 14. dxe5 Qg5 { immediately hits White's split pawns. }
15. Bb5+ c6 16. O-O
{ A strong move, which keeps White in the game and the reason why 10...Nfd4 is mymain recommendation. }
16... Bc5+
{ The point is that  16...cxb5  17.Qxd5∞  gives White a dangerous initiative. }
17. Kh1 Bd7
{ Breaking the pin. We're finally threatening to capture White's bishop.   Note that  17...Qxg3?  loses to  18.Qxd5−+  since the c6 pawn is pinned. }
18. Bd3 O-O-O
{ is slightly better for Black with ...Rde8 and ...Rhg8 coming next. Black's bishop pair is very strong and White's position looks very sketchy, although the engines claim White can maintain the balance with precise play. I expect most club players to quickly collapse with White, so 10...Ncxd4 is certainly an excellent practical choice. }
