1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bg5
{ The Torre Attack, where White brings out his dark-squared bishop on move 3. He typically places his light-squared bishop on d3, the queenside knight on d2, and reinforces the d4 pawn with c2-c3. The first player then hopes to push forward with e2-e4 and start a kingside attack, taking advantage of the fact that the bishop on g5 can chop off knight on f6 – the main defender of Black’s king – at an opportune moment.  This is all sounds great were it not for }
3... Ne4
{ immediately hitting White's bishop. As we shall see, White cannot get e4 in under advantageous conditions and has no hopes of ever starting a kingside attack. }
4. h4
{ The Torre Pseudo-Raptor @@StartBracket@@yes, I totally made that up!@@EndBracket@@. Whatever the name of this variation, the bottom line is that it's pretty bad.   The real Raptor is a variation of the Trompowsky that occurs after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.Bg5  Ne4  3.h4 }
4... c5
{ Undermining White's d-pawn and intending a quick ...Qb6, which will hit both d4 and b2. }
5. e3 Qb6
{ Highlights one of the big drawbacks of an early Bg5. The pawn on b2 is unprotected. }
6. Qc1 { Black quickly takes over with } 6... f6 7. Bf4 cxd4 8. exd4 e5
{ with a big edge. The pawn on e5 is taboo as f2 would then hang.   A sample continuation with accurate play by both sides is  9.Be3  Nc6  10.c3  exd4  11.Nxd4  Nxd4  12.Bxd4  Bc5  13.Bxc5  Qxc5  14.Qe3  Qxe3  15.fxe3  Ng3  Black is clearly for choice in this endgame. }
*

