1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bg5
{ The Torre Attack, where White brings out his dark-squared bishop on move 3. He typically places his light-squared bishop on d3, the queenside knight on d2, and reinforces the d4 pawn with c2-c3. The first player then hopes to push forward with e2-e4 and start a kingside attack, taking advantage of the fact that the bishop on g5 can chop off knight on f6 – the main defender of Black’s king – at an opportune moment.  This is all sounds great were it not for }
3... Ne4
{ immediately hitting White's bishop. As we shall see, White cannot get e4 in under advantageous conditions and has no hopes of ever starting a kingside attack. }
4. Bf4 { is twice as popular as 4. Bh4. } 4... c5
{ not only challenges White's center, but makes way for ...Qb6. } 5. e3 Qb6
{ This early queen sortie exploits one of the downsides of bringing the dark-squared bishop out so early, that is White's b2 pawn lacks protection. }
6. Nc3 Qa5 7. Nd2
{ was recommended by FM Marko Makaj in the Chessable course 'Calm and Collected: 1. d4'. }
7... Nxc3 8. bxc3 Nc6
{ is precise. The c3 pawn isn't going anywhere   The immediate  8...Qxc3  allows  9.Bxb8  Rxb8  when  10.Bb5+=  is an annoying check. }
9. Rb1 Qxc3
{ We're now a clean pawn up. It's up to White to show he has enough compensation. }
10. Bb5 e6 11. O-O Be7 { Next up is ...O-O when we'll be a pawn to the good. }
12. Rb3 Qa5 13. c4
{ This was all recommended in the Chessable course 'Calm and Collected: 1. d4' by Marko Makaj. There he only considered the dubious 13...a6?! and completely neglected the simple and strong }
13... O-O { which gives Black the upper hand. } 14. dxc5 Bxc5 15. cxd5 exd5
{ Next up is ...Be6 with an extra pawn. White has insufficient compensation for the material deficit. }
