[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. Veresov (1...d5 and 1...Nf6)"]
[Black "Chapter overview"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bg5
{ The Veresov or Richter-Veresov variation is named after the German IM Kurt Richter and the Soviet Union GM Gavriil Veresov, who regularly played 2. Nc3 3. Bg5 for over a quarter of a century. Despite never being popular at the top level, several strong players have essayed this variation from time to time. Most notably, the soviet GM David Bronstein played the Veresov against GM Gavriil Veresov himself in 1959.  White's main intention is to expand in the center with e2-e4. However, there is one big drawback behind developing the knight to c3, namely that White can no longer break with c2-c4. As we’re about to see, White will find it very hard to break with e4, meaning the knight frequently ends up being completely misplaced on c3.   The Richter Attack with  3.f3  is also covered in depth. }
3... h6
{ is my recommendation. Despite being 8x less common than 3...Nbd7, it is one of the top choices of the neural network engines.   French defense players may wish to know that  3...e6  which was my choice vs the Jobava, allows a transposition to the French after  4.e4 }
4. Bxf6
{ is White's most popular move with 500+ OTB games.   4.Bh4  is second most common with 300+ OTB games.   4.Bf4  is much rarer with only 50+ OTB games. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. Veresov (1...d5 and 1...Nf6)"]
[Black "3. f3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nc3
{ Threatens to expand in the center with e2-e4, which we immediately stop with }
2... Nf6
{ when White's knight on c3 is misplaced, stopping White from breaking in the center with c2-c4. }
3. f3
{ The so-called Richter Attack. White prepares to expand in the center with e2-e4. In doing so, he however deprives the knight on g1 of its best square.   While the engines rate this attack as dubious, White scores quite well in fast time controls. As such, good knowledge of the variations is required to punish White's dubious play. }
3... c5 { is a typical reaction when White is threatening e4. } 4. e4
{ The only logical follow up to White's previous move.   4.e3  is incongruent. The pawn on f3 now makes no sense.  4...Nc6  5.Bb5  e6  6.Nge2  Bd6  7.O-O  O-O∓  followed by ...Bd7 and ...a6 gave Black a clear advantage, which he easily converted in 0-1 @@StartBracket@@15@@EndBracket@@ Bucher,R @@StartBracket@@2055@@EndBracket@@ -Klovans,J @@StartBracket@@2394@@EndBracket@@ Triesen 2002. White's knight on e2 is completely misplaced and the bishop on c1 is restricted. }
4... cxd4 5. Qxd4 Nc6 { Developing with tempo. } 6. Bb5
{ is almost invariably played. White wants to keep the queen on d4, where it pressures the d5 pawn and supports e4-e5 in some variations. }
6... Bd7 { Breaks the pin, practically forcing } 7. Bxc6 bxc6
{ is the strongest recapture. It is Stockfish's top choice and much rarer than 7...Bxc6, thus packing good surprise value. The idea behind ...bxc6 is to play ...e6 and then kick back White's queen with ... c5, taking over the center.   7...Bxc6  was recommended by GM Boris Avrukh in the book 'GM Repertoire: Beating 1.d4 Sidelines'. The text is however stronger. }
8. Bg5
{ is White's third most popular continuation. As Black will go ...e6, White wants to try and take advantage of the pin on the knight on f6 with e5.   8.Nge2  is the 4th move common move.  8...e6  9.Bg5   9.e5  runs into  9...c5  kicking White's queen. After  10.Qh4  Ng8  11.Qg3  Qc7∓  Black is clearly better.  Qb6  10.b3  occurred in the game 0-1 @@StartBracket@@54@@EndBracket@@ Cooper,N @@StartBracket@@2178@@EndBracket@@-Chen, F @@StartBracket@@2327@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2019. Now  10...Qxd4  is simple and effective, leading to a clearly better endgame for Black after  11.Nxd4  h6  12.Bf4  Bb4∓  White's knight will soon be kicked back with ...c5, and Black's bishop pair will shine in this endgame. }
8... e6 { Black is now ready to push White's queen back with ...c5. } 9. e5
{ 9.Nge2  can be met with  9...h6  10.Bh4  Be7∓  followed by ...c5. } 9... c5
{ A strong counterblow, forcing White's queen away from the center. } 10. Qh4
{ is the most popular position for the queen. Alternatives are analyzed below.   10.Qd2  is the better place. Now Black should break the pin with  10...h6  11.Bh4  Ne4!  A fantastic move with a double-attack on White's bishop and queen! After the forced sequence  12.fxe4  Qxh4+  13.g3  Qg5  14.exd5  Qxd2+  15.Kxd2  O-O-O  16.Nge2  exd5⩱  we have a slightly better endgame for Black, who has the bishop pair and is ready to push ahead with ...d4.   10.Qf2  is strongly met by  10...Qb8  breaking the pin and hitting the b2 pawn. After  11.exf6  Qxb2  12.Nge2  Qxa1+  13.Bc1  d4  Black is winning. For example  14.O-O  dxc3  15.Bh6  Qxa2  16.fxg7  Bxg7  17.Bxg7  Rg8  18.Nxc3  Qa5  19.Bf6  Rg6−+  is decisive. Black is up an exchange.   10.Qe3  gets hit by the fork  10...d4  The best White has is  11.exf6  dxe3  12.fxg7  Bxg7  13.Bxd8  Kxd8  14.O-O-O  Ke7∓  when Black is clearly better in this endgame due to the pair of bishops. }
10... Qb8
{ steps out of the pin and threatens to fork White's knight and rook with ...Qxb2. }
11. exf6
{ Worse is  11.O-O-O?!  as after  11...Ng8  12.Nge2  Qb7  13.Kb1  Rb8−+  Black has full control over the center and a big queenside attack. }
11... Qxb2 12. Rb1 Qxc3+
{ not only recoups the minor piece but also leaves White's king stranded in the middle of the board. Oh, and by the way, we're already a pawn up! }
13. Kd1 Qa5 { Steps out of Ne2. } 14. Ne2
{ 14.fxg7  only helps Black develop his bishop. After  14...Bxg7  15.Ne2  Qxa2  16.Rc1  Qb2−+  Black has an overwhelming position. }
14... g6
{ gives Black a decisive advantage. We are a pawn up and if that were not already enough, White's king is stranded on d1 and the queenside pawns are incredibly weak. Black can play ...Bc6 next and can, if required, place his king on d7, where it will be perfectly safe. }
*

