1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. f3
{ The so-called Richter Attack. White prepares to expand in the center with e2-e4. In doing so, he however deprives the knight on g1 of its best square.   While the engines rate this attack as dubious, White scores quite well in fast time controls. As such, good knowledge of the variations is required to punish White's dubious play. }
3... c5 { is a typical reaction when White is threatening e4. } 4. e4
{ The only logical follow up to White's previous move.   4.e3  is incongruent. The pawn on f3 now makes no sense.  4...Nc6  5.Bb5  e6  6.Nge2  Bd6  7.O-O  O-O  followed by ...Bd7 and ...a6 gave Black a clear advantage, which he easily converted in 0-1 @@StartBracket@@15@@EndBracket@@ Bucher,R @@StartBracket@@2055@@EndBracket@@ -Klovans,J @@StartBracket@@2394@@EndBracket@@ Triesen 2002. White's knight on e2 is completely misplaced and the bishop on c1 is restricted. }
4... cxd4 5. Qxd4 Nc6 { Developing with tempo. } 6. Bb5
{ is almost invariably played. White wants to keep the queen on d4, where it pressures the d5 pawn and supports e4-e5 in some variations. }
6... Bd7 { Breaks the pin, practically forcing } 7. Bxc6 bxc6
{ is the strongest recapture. It is Stockfish's top choice and much rarer than 7...Bxc6, thus packing good surprise value. The idea behind ...bxc6 is to play ...e6 and then kick back White's queen with ... c5, taking over the center.   7...Bxc6  was recommended by GM Boris Avrukh in 'GM Repertoire: Beating 1.d4 Sidelines'. The text is however stronger. }
8. exd5 { is an OTB novelty but has been played 50+ times in online games. }
8... cxd5 9. Nxd5 Qa5+ { forces White's knight back. } 10. Nc3 e5
{ The engines are already giving back a clear advantage @@StartBracket@@evals around -1@@EndBracket@@. Nevertheless, White won 56% of the games compared to only 40% for Black, suggesting Black should be aware of the following continuations to swiftly convert his advantage. }
11. Qd3
{ 11.Qh4  is equally popular as 11. Qd3  11...Bc5  12.Bg5  And now Black has the stunning  12...Ba3!  13.Bd2  Be7  14.Nge2  O-O  15.Ne4  Qb6−+  stops White from castling and hits the b2 pawn. White's pieces are completely uncoordinated giving Black a decisive advantage.   11.Qe3  is rarer. Black can continue in similar fashion, a sample continuation being  11...Bb4  12.Bd2  O-O  13.Nge2  Rab8  14.Rd1  Qc7  15.Qf2  Bf5−+  with a decisive advantage.   11.Qd2?!  makes the least sense as the queen is blocking the bishop and is exposed on the b-file. After  11...Rd8  12.Nge2  Be6  the queen is forced to move again.  13.Qg5  Be7  14.Qg3  h5  15.h4  O-O  16.O-O  Bf5∓  is clearly better for Black. The two bishops here are a big asset. }
11... Bb4
{ Developing the bishop to its most active position and pinning the c3 knight. ...Bb5 ideas are now in the air. }
12. Ne2
{ Worse is  12.Bd2  O-O  13.a3  is White's best but Black can just ignore it as the rook on a1 is pinned.   13.Nge2?!  is inferior. After  13...Rfd8  14.Rd1  Bh3  15.Qe3  Bxg2−+  Black wins material.  13...Rfd8  14.Nge2  Be6  15.Qe3  Rab8−+  gives Black a decisive advantage. White's king is stuck in the center as O-O runs into ...Bc5 and O-O-O into ...Bxa3. }
12... Bb5 { Takes advantage of the pin, displacing White's queen. } 13. Qf5
{ 13.Qe3?!  runs into  13...Bxe2  14.Kxe2  O-O−+  when White's king is too exposed. }
13... O-O
{ Black is fully mobilized while White has no good way of finishing development. The immediate threat is ...Bxe2 followed by ...Bxc3. }
14. a3 Bxe2
{ Forces the king to recapture, a move White definitely didn't want to make. Note that the pawn on a3 is pinned as the rook on a1 is unprotected. }
15. Kxe2 Bxc3 16. bxc3 Rad8
{ White's king is completely exposed and won't survive the incoming assault. White has no development while Black is fully mobilized. As such, the second player has a decisive advantage. }
