1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bg5 { The Veresov. } 3... h6
{ is my recommendation. Despite being 8x less common than 3...Nbd7, it is one of the top choices of the neural network engines. This stat indicates that White is much less likely to be well versed in the resulting structures.   French defense players may wish to know that  3...e6  which was my choice vs the Jobava Attack, allows a transposition to the French after  4.e4 }
4. Bxf6 { is White's most popular move by a big margin. } 4... exf6
{ Let us compare this with my recommendation vs the Trompowsky @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.Bg5  d5  3.Bxf6  exf6  You might be led to believe this is a favorable version for White since he got in Nc3 in exchange for ... h6, which isn't particularly useful. However, White's knight is completely misplaced on c3 and would much rather be on b1 in this position as it deprives White of playing c4. The problem is that White's e4 break simply doesn't work, meaning he has no way of challenging our center. }
5. e4 { White's standard break doesn't work on account of } 5... Bb4
{ The pawn on e4 is now hanging so White has two options: taking on d5 or protecting it with Bd3. }
6. Bd3
{ 6.exd5  is worse. After  6...Qxd5  7.Nf3  O-O  8.Be2  Qa5∓  White's knight is under fire and Black's bishops give him a clear advantage. }
6... c5 { Boom. White's center now collapses. } 7. dxc5
{ 7.exd5  is once again met by  7...Qxd5⩱ } 7... d4 8. a3
{ White has no option but to try and break the pin. } 8... Ba5 9. b4 dxc3 10.
bxa5 O-O { is awful for White. All his queenside pawns are weak and isolated. }
