{ Let us compare this with my recommendation vs the Trompowsky @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.Bg5  d5  3.Bxf6  exf6  You might be led to believe this is a favorable version for White since he got in Nc3 in exchange for ... h6, which isn't particularly useful. However, White's knight is completely misplaced on c3 and would much rather be on b1 in this position as it deprives White of playing c4. The problem is that White's e4 break simply doesn't work, meaning he has no way of challenging our center. }
5. e3 c6 6. Bd3 Nd7
{ Heading to f6. If we're allowed to get ...Bd6, ...g6 and ... f5 in, we'll simply be better. }
7. Qf3
{ is connected with an ambitious plan. White's idea is to expand on the kingside with g4 and h4. While it might look somewhat scary, Black is very well equipped to deal with this. }
7... g6
{ An important move, allowing us to play ...h5 and ...f5, which will make it hard for White to execute his plan. }
8. h3 h5
{ puts an end to g4. We're now threatening to play ...f5 next, so White really needs to break with }
9. e4 { However, Black comes out on top after } 9... dxe4 10. Qxe4+
{ is the only sensible recapture.  Worse is   10.Nxe4  f5  sends White's knight packing.  11.Nd2  Nf6  12.c3  Bh6  followed by ...O-O with a clear advantage.   10.Bxe4?!  makes even less sense. After  10...Bg7  11.O-O-O  we get a free tempo with  11...f5  12.Bd3  O-O∓ }
10... Be7 11. Nf3 Nb6
{ is an important nuance. We should not commit our king to the kingside before White decides where to castle. }
12. O-O-O Kf8 { maintaining the rook on h8 so that after } 13. g4
{ the pawn on h5 is already defended. Following } 13... Bb4 14. Ne2 Qd5
{ forces the queens off the board, when Black's two bishops and superior pawn structure mean he's clearly for choice. }
