8... Bxc5 9. Nd4
{ stops Black from playing ...Nh5 and winning the bishop pair as in theprevious line.   9.a3  is an interesting engine suggestion intending to expand with b4. Black can do the same with  9...b5  10.b4  Be7  11.h3  Bb7  12.O-O  Qc8!  with the idea ...Qc6 is very strong. The engine insists White can maintain the balance with  13.Qb1  which I doubt many players would find. Nevertheless, after  13...e5=  Black's position is much easier to play. Up next are ...d4 followed by ...Qc6 as well as the simple ...O-O, completing development with full control over the center. }
9... b5
{ Prepares to fianchetto the light-squared bishop and take firm control over the e4 square. Black can also consider pushing the pawn one step further to disrupt White's development. }
10. O-O Bb7 11. a4 b4 { knocks back one of White's knight } 12. Na2 e5
{ takes over the center and sends the other knight packing. } 13. Nb3 Bd6
{ Black will castle short next with an excellent position. While the engine insists White is still within the realms of equality, Black's position is much easier to play and I expect the second player to score very well here. }
