1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bf4
{ The Jobava Attack, named after the strong Georgian GM Baadur Jobava. This variation has also been called the Jobava-Prie Attack in honor of GM Éric Prié, who used to annotate the d4 systems column for Chesspublishing. Lichess calls it the Rapport-Jobava Attack since super-GM Richard Rapport has also played it extensively. Chess.com and 365chess.com refer to it as the Chigorin Variation. Finally, GM Simon Williams in his Chessable course called it the Jobava London System.  Jobava racked up quite a score a few years ago but has largely given it up. The reason for this is there are multiple systems where Black is very comfortable, such as 3...c5, 3...g6, and 3...a6. }
3... e6
{ is my recommendation and one of the most challenging systems. The idea is to quickly play ...Bb4 @@StartBracket@@or ...Bd6@@EndBracket@@. }
4. a3 { prevents ... Bb4 but does nothing about } 4... Bd6 5. Bg3
{ The alternatives are completely harmless.   5.Bg5  is essentially a waste of tempo. After  5...c5  6.e3  Nc6  7.Nf3  O-O  Black is already slightly for choice as White's knight doesn't belong on c3.   Protecting the bishop with  5.Qd2  can be met with  5...O-O  6.Bxd6  Qxd6  7.e3  c5  followed by ...b6 and ...Bb7 gives Black a great game. }
5... O-O 6. e3 c5
{ immediately challenges White's center. White's knight on c3 is once again misplaced, preventing White from fighting for the center with c4 or reinforcing his d4 pawn with c3. }
7. Nf3 b6 8. Bd3 Bb7
{ The bishop stands very well on b7, making it almost impossible for White to break with e4. }
9. O-O Bxg3
{ Once again - whenever White castles with the bishop on g3, we go for the exchange as the rook is no longer on h1 and White can't benefit from the open h-file. }
10. hxg3 Nc6
{ followed by ...c4 and a queenside expansion with ...a6 and ...b5 gives Black the upper hand. }
*

