1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bf4
{ The Jobava Attack, named after the strong Georgian GM Baadur Jobava. This variation has also been called the Jobava-Prie Attack in honor of GM Éric Prié, who used to annotate the d4 systems column for Chesspublishing. Lichess calls it the Rapport-Jobava Attack since super-GM Richard Rapport has also played it extensively. Chess.com and 365chess.com refer to it as the Chigorin Variation. Finally, GM Simon Williams in his Chessable course called it the Jobava London System.  Jobava racked up quite a score a few years ago but has largely given it up. The reason for this is there are multiple systems where Black is very comfortable, such as 3...c5, 3...g6, and 3...a6. }
3... e6
{ is my recommendation and one of the most challenging systems. The idea is to quickly play ...Bb4 @@StartBracket@@or ...Bd6@@EndBracket@@. }
4. Nb5 { The only serious move in my opinion. } 4... Na6
{ may look awkward but is perfectly fine. We parry White's threat of Nxc7 and are ready to kick back his knight with ...c6 after we develop our kingside. }
5. e3 Be7 6. g4 { is certainly enterprising, but not particularly good. } 6...
Ne4
{ is an excellent reply, taking control over the c3 square before playing ...c6. }
7. Bd3 c6
{ is the point. White's knight on b5 is very short on squares, effectively forcing White to part with the light-squared bishop. }
8. Bxe4
{ 8.Nc3  Nxc3  compromises White's structure. After  9.bxc3  c5⩱  Black is already better. }
8... dxe4 9. Nc3 O-O 10. a3
{ Importantly, the e-pawn is taboo as  10.Nxe4?  loses material to  10...g5!  11.Bg3  f5⩱ }
10... c5 11. Nge2 Qb6
{ The queen pops out to b6 with pressure on the b2 pawn. Black is already slightly better and White can hardly create anything on the kingside to justify 6. g4. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7. London (1...d5 and 1...Nf6 2...e6)"]
[Black "Chapter overview"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ Nimzo/QID/Bogo-Indian players can use the following move order  1...Nf6  2.Bf4  e6  3.e3  d5  4.Nf3  Bd6  to reach the mainline. }
2. Bf4
{ The London system, some love to play it, others hate to face it.    Out of all the 1. d4 systems, it is certainly the best and most ambitious one. Over the past few years, almost all the top players have added the London to their repertoire. Magnus Carlsen, in particular, has racked up an impressive score with this opening. Through the use of clever move orders, White can play this opening ambitiously and fight for an opening advantage. Therefore, it is important to not underestimate it.   Attempts to refute or crush the London usually backfire. One course with such a title on Chessable fails to even equalize with Black. Now I'm all for trying to 'crush' incorrect openings, but the London certainly does not fall into this category.     Moreover, I do not believe in goofy systems such as @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.Bf4  c5  3.e3  Nd5?!   or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Bf4  c6  3.e3  Qb6  , which have been proposed by a few authors on this platform. White has excellent chances for an advantage when Black plays like this.  Instead, I chose to recommend one of the most reliable systems against the London involving 2...Nf6, 3...e6 and 4...Bd6, where our goal is to first equalize. After all, we're playing with Black and 2. Bf4 or 2. Nf3 3. Bf4 doesn't break any opening principles. That being said, I made every effort to avoid stale 0.00 positions and did my best to recommend variations that give Black enough room to fight for the full point wherever possible.   The system I'm about to propose has the advantage of neutralizing White's standard plan of entrenching a knight on e5 and attacking on the kingside. This is especially effective against club players that play the London unambitiously, going for the same setup all the time.   Furthermore, it's also very practical and avoids the need of having to memorize long computer lines.   Finally, it's suitable for both 1...d5 and 1...Nf6 2...e6 players, meaning you don't have to learn different systems if you play more than one defense with Black.   In summary, the repertoire I'm about to present is not only bulletproof but also gives you enough scope to fight for an advantage if White makes a few inaccuracies. }
2... Nf6 3. e3
{ Starting with  3.Nf3  makes no difference in the setup we're going for  3...e6  4.e3  Bd6  transposes to the mainline. }
3... e6 4. Nf3
{ White can also start with  4.Nd2  . However, White can only delay  Nf3  for so long and therefore this has no independent value. }
4... Bd6 { We're going to cover White's top 5 choices in this position. } 5.
Bg3
{ is White's most popular move with 3000+ OTB games.   5.Ne5  is the 2nd most popular move with 1300+ OTB games.   5.Bxd6  is the 3rd most popular move with 900+ OTB games.   5.Nbd2  is the 4th most popular move with 500+ OTB games.   5.Bd3  is the 5th most popular line with 400+ OTB games. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7. London (1...d5 and 1...Nf6 2...e6)"]
[Black "Part 1 - 5. Bg3 retreat line - Our setup explained"]
[Result "*"]

{ In this info line, I'd like to discuss our setup in the 5. Bg3 retreat line. Here's the formula you should remember:  1. Develop the kingside with ...Nf6, ...e6, ...Bd6 and ...O-O  2. Break with ...c5  3. Place the queen on c7  4. Develop the b8 knight to d7  Our main goal is to break in the center with ...e5. }
1. d4 d5 2. Bf4
{ 1. Develop the kingside with ...Nf6, ...e6, ...Bd6 and ...O-O } 2... Nf6 3.
e3 e6 4. Nf3 Bd6
{ immediately fighting for the e5 square and clearing the way for ...O-O. } 5.
Bg3 O-O
{ Notice how we first develop the kingside before touching anything on the queenside. }
6. Nbd2 { 2. Break with ...c5 } 6... c5
{ putting pressure on White's center and vacating the c7 square for our queen. }
7. c3 { 3. Place the queen on c7 } 7... Qc7
{ The queen is better placed on c7 than on e7. This is because in the former it fights for the e5 square.  Notice that we also develop the queen first and only then b8 knight. This is so we can meet dxc5 with ...Qxc5. }
8. Bd3 { 4. Develop the b8 knight to d7 } 8... Nbd7
{ The knight should be placed on d7 rather than on c6.   The reason is that  8...Nc6  runs into  9.dxc5  taking advantage of the pin and the fact that the knight on c6 is blocking our queen from covering the c5 pawn.  From d7, the knight takes control over the e5 square without blocking our queen from protecting the c5 pawn.   This piece arrangement - bishop on d6, queen on c7, and knight on d7  a@@EndBracket@@ takes firm control over the e5 square, meaning White can't install a knight here  b@@EndBracket@@ prepares the e6-e5 break. Once we achieve this break, we have comfortably equalized. }
9. Qc2 { 5. Break with e6-e5 } 9... e5
{ The final step in our plan, which gives us an excellent game. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7. London (1...d5 and 1...Nf6 2...e6)"]
[Black "5. Bg3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 { The London system. } 2... Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Nf3 Bd6
{ immediately fighting for the e5 square and clearing the way for ...O-O. } 5.
Bg3
{ is at least 3x as popular as the alternatives. White invites Black to capture on g3, which would open the h-file for the rook on h1.  A rule of thumb  (although there are some exceptions)  is that we should only capture the bishop on g3 when White has castled short  (as the rook is no longer on h1)  . }
5... O-O
{ finishing kingside development. It's important to note that we develop the kingside first with ...Nf6, ...e6, ...Bd6, and ...O-O before touching anything else on the queenside.   The immediate pawn break  5...c5  gives White the extra option of playing  6.Bb5+ }
6. c4
{ is not standard but has been played several times. We're perfectly positioned to fight for the center with }
6... c5
{ White has 3 main options now, namely 7. cxd5, 7. dxc5 and 7. Nc3 in order of increasing popularity. }
7. cxd5 exd5 8. Nc3 { 8.Bd3  can be met with  8...c4  9.Bc2  b5↑ } 8... c4
{ is rare but very interesting. It deprives White's bishop of the d3 square. The plan is to complete development with ... Be6 and ...Nbd7 and then expand on the queenside with ...a6 + ...b5. }
9. Bh4
{ White is threatening to win the d5 pawn @@StartBracket@@or spoil our pawn structure@@EndBracket@@ with Bxf6 followed by Nxd5. }
9... Be6 10. Be2 Nbd7 11. O-O a6
{ Black is doing very well and can continue with ...Qc7 and ...b5.   A sample continuation is  12.a4  h6  13.a5  b5  14.axb6  Qxb6  15.Ra2  Qc7  followed by ...Rfb8 with a great position.   12.Ng5  is also possible. Black should continue with  12...b5  13.Nxe6  fxe6  14.e4  b4  15.Na4  Be7  16.e5  Ne8  17.Bxe7  Qxe7=  Black is in excellent shape and can easily create a passed pawn on the queenside later on. }
*

