{ has never been played OTB but was a suggestion of a GM I analyzed this position with. His idea was to quickly expand on the queenside with a3 and b4, an approach that should be taken seriously. }
8... Nc6 9. a3
{ stops ...Bb4, so that White can develop with Nc3 without running into a pin with ...Bb4 as happened after 8. Nc3. It also prepares to expand on the queenside with b4. }
9... d4
{ An important move, or else White can easily take over. Being fully developed, Black is in a great position to immediately strike in the center. }
10. b4 { leads nowhere for White. } 10... Bd6 11. exd4 Bxg3 12. hxg3 a5
{ is a good move to throw in before capturing on d4. It makes White place another one of his pawns on light squares. }
13. b5 Nxd4 14. Nxd4 Qxd4 15. Nc3 e5
{ Black is ready to bring out the light-squared bishop with a very comfortable position. White's advanced pawns on the queenside can easily end up being targets in an ensuing endgame. }
