1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 { The London system. } 2... Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Nf3 Bd6
{ immediately fighting for the e5 square and clearing the way for ...O-O. } 5.
Bg3 { is at least 3x as popular as the alternatives. } 5... O-O 6. Nbd2 c5
{ It's now time to discuss the setup we're aiming for. We're going to place our queen on c7 and b8 knight on d7, taking complete control over the e5 square. This will completely neutralize White's typical plan of entrenching a knight on e5 and starting a kingside attack. }
7. c3 Qc7 { Next up is ...Nbd7, taking full control over e5. } 8. Ne5
{ This early knight sortie once again achieves very little. } 8... Nbd7 9. f4
{ This stonewall setup is ineffective when we're able to immediately jump into e4 with }
9... Ne4 10. Nxe4 dxe4 11. Qc2
{ Attacking the c2 pawn is the second most popular move at the club level. }
11... cxd4
{ is a timely recapture, exploiting the fact that the c3 pawn is pinned. } 12.
exd4 f5 13. Qb3
{ 13.Be2  can be met with  13...Be7  14.O-O  Nxe5  15.dxe5  b5⩱ } 13... Nxe5
14. fxe5
{ The alternative recapture  14.dxe5  is even worse. After the novel  14...Bc5  N  15.Bc4  Re8  White's king cannot castle kingside. If he goes to the other side of the board with  16.O-O-O?!  then  16...a6∓  followed by ...b5 starts a big attack on White's king. }
14... Be7 15. Bc4
{ This position was reached in three blitz games. In all three games, Black missed the winning shot  Trying to stop the f-pawn with   15.Bf4  runs into  15...g5  16.Bc1  Kh8∓  when ...f4 is coming anyway. }
15... f4
{ ignoring the attack on the e6 pawn and instead going after White's bishop.   The point is that after  15...f4  16.Bxe6+  Kh8  White's bishop is very short on squares.  17.Bf2  e3  18.Bg1  is the only way to keep the bishop alive but after  18...Bh4+  19.g3  fxg3  20.hxg3  Qc6  21.Rxh4  Qf3−+  White's king is toast. }
