{ immediately fighting for the e5 square and clearing the way for ...O-O. } 5.
Bg3 { is at least 3x as popular as the alternatives. } 5... O-O 6. Nbd2
{ White can also start with   6.Bd3  which will transpose to the mainline after  6...c5 }
6... c5
{ It's now time to discuss the setup we're aiming for. We're going to place our queen on c7 and b8 knight on d7, taking complete control over the e5 square. This will completely neutralize White's typical plan of entrenching a knight on e5 and starting a kingside attack. }
7. c3 Qc7 { Next up is ...Nbd7, taking full control over e5. } 8. dxc5
{ has been played a couple of times by Aronian. } 8... Qxc5 9. Bd3 Nbd7
{ The correct square for the knight.   Watch out  9...Nc6??  drops a piece to  10.Nb3+− }
10. Qe2
{ Alternatively  10.Qc2  is well met by  10...h6  waiting for  11.O-O  to play  11...Bxg3  now that White's rook is no longer on the h-file.  12.hxg3  b6=  followed by ...Bb7 with a comfortable game.   Heading to the other side of the board after  10.Qc2  h6  with  11.O-O-O?!  is ill-advised. White's king and queen are misplaced on the c-file and ripe for an attack after  11...b5!   The simple  11...Bxg3  12.hxg3  Re8  followed by ...e5 is perfectly satisfactory if you don't want to attack on the queenside.  12.Kb1  Rb8  13.Bxd6  Qxd6  14.Rhg1  White prepares g4 but there's no way to get to our king.  14...Ba6  15.g4  Rfc8  16.g5  hxg5  17.Rxg5  b4  And Black's attack is much faster. For example  18.c4  Kf8  19.Rdg1  g6  10.h4  Ke7∓  Our king is perfectly safe on e7 while the same certainly cannot be said for White's monarch. With ...Rc5 followed by ...Rbc8 on the way, I certainly wouldn't want to be in White's shoes. }
10... Qb6
{ Attacking the b2 pawn and clearing the way for ...Nc5.   10...Bxg3  is also good and is given as analternative recommendation. }
11. Bxd6
{ Covering the b2 pawn with   11.O-O-O  runs into  11...Nc5  12.e4?!  featured in the game 0-1 Yurovskich, O @@StartBracket@@2260@@EndBracket@@-Riff, J @@StartBracket@@2504@@EndBracket@@ chess.com INT 2020   Better is  12.Bc2  although after  12...Be7=  Black is doing very well with ...Bd7-a4 on the agenda.  Now the novel  12...Na4  13.Nb3  Ba3!!  14.bxa3  dxe4∓  would have given Black a clear advantage. The point is that  15.Bxe4?  runs into a fork after  15...Nxc3−+   Worse is  11.Nb3  because of  11...e5∓  when White cannot stop ...e4. }
11... Qxd6 12. e4
{ The alternative pawn break  12.c4  can be met with  12...Nc5  13.O-O  e5=  Next up are ...e4 and ...Bg4. }
12... e5 13. O-O Nc5
{ gave Black a slight advantage in 1-0  (29)  Golubov,S  (2469)  -Studer,N  (2546)  Moscow 2019.   A sample continuation is  14.Bc2  Bg4  15.Qe3  Bxf3  16.Qxf3  d4  17.Rad1  Ne6  followed by ...Rfd8 with a great game. }
