{ It's now time to discuss the setup we're aiming for. We're going to place our queen on c7 and b8 knight on d7, taking complete control over the e5 square. This will completely neutralize White's typical plan of entrenching a knight on e5 and starting a kingside attack. }
7. c3 Qc7 { Next up is ...Nbd7, taking full control over e5. } 8. dxc5
{ has been played a couple of times by Aronian. } 8... Qxc5 9. Bd3 Nbd7
{ The correct square for the knight.  Watch out   9...Nc6??  drops a piece to  10.Nb3+- }
10. e4 { has been played by several 2600+ GMs, but doesn't bring White much. }
10... dxe4 { Now both recaptures have been tried. } 11. Nxe4 Nxe4
{ initiating a forced sequence involving a series of captures. } 12. Bxe4
{ The bishop on d6 is now hanging, so we should chop off on g3. } 12... Bxg3
{ Yes, this opens the h-file for the rook on h1 but White is not in a position to be exploit it. }
13. hxg3 Nf6 { protects the h7 pawn with a tempo on White's bishop. } 14. Bc2
{ White is now threatening to play g4, taking advantage of the fact that the knight on f6 is tied down to the defense of the h7 pawn. }
14... e5
{ stops White from playing g4.  Next up is ...Bg4 with a comfortable position.   A sample continuation is  15.O-O  Bg4  16.Re1  Rfe8  17.Qd2  e4  18.Ng5  Bf5  19.Qf4  Re5=  with good play. Black is now threatening to go ...e3. }
