1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 { The London system } 2... Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Nf3 Bd6
{ immediately fighting for the e5 square and clearing the way for ...O-O. } 5.
Bg3 { is at least 3x as popular as the alternatives. } 5... O-O 6. Nbd2
{ White can also start with  6.Bd3  which will transpose to the mainline after  6...c5 }
6... c5
{ It's now time to discuss the setup we're aiming for. We're going to place our queen on c7 and b8 knight on d7, taking complete control over the e5 square. This will completely neutralize White's typical plan of entrenching a knight on e5 and starting a kingside attack. }
7. c3 Qc7 { Next up is ...Nbd7, taking full control over e5. } 8. Rc1
{ is a creative idea by 2600+ GM Jumabayev, who won a couple of blitz games with it in 2020.  It was recently recommended by IM Levy Rozman, commonly known as GothamChess, in the online course D4 Dynamite.   White's idea is to meet  8...Nbd7  with  9.c4  b6  10.b4  with good play along the c-file.  While this aggressive plan has decent surprise value in fast time controls, it can be easily neutralized by starting with }
8... b6
{ which was not considered by IM Levy Rozman in the aforementioned online course. We preemptively reinforce the c5 pawn, effectively neutralizing White's plan of undermining it with c4 and b4. }
9. c4
{ is the logical follow-up to 8. Rc1.   Alternatively  9.Bxd6  Qxd6  10.Ne5  Ba6  fully equalizes. After the exchange of light-squared bishops  11.Bxa6  Nxa6  12.f4  Nb8  13.O-O  Nc6  Black is in great shape. Without the light-squared bishops, starting an attack with  14.g4  isn't effective. Black can simply play  14...Ne7  15.g5  Ne4=  with a good game. }
9... Bb7 10. b4
{ The more restrained  10.Be2  creates zero problems for Black.  10...Bxg3  11.hxg3  Nbd7  12.O-O  dxc4  13.Nxc4  Rac8=  is fully equal. }
10... Bxg3 11. hxg3 cxd4
{ is a timely capture, leaving White with an isolated pawn on d4. } 12. exd4
dxc4 13. Bxc4
{ Also possible is  13.Nxc4  when Black can sidestep any knight jumps with  13...Qe7  hitting the b4 pawn.  14.Qd2  Rc8  15.Bd3  Nc6⩱  gives Black the upper hand.   Worse is  13.Rxc4?!  as the rook is completely misplaced. After  13...Qd6∓  Black will soon kick it back with ...b5 or ...Bd5. }
13... Qd6
{ gives Black an excellent game with ...Rc8 coming next. White's Rc1+b4+c4 excursion achieved nothing significant. In fact, the d4 and b4 pawns are merely targets. }
