1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 { The London system } 2... Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Nf3 Bd6
{ immediately fighting for the e5 square and clearing the way for ...O-O. } 5.
Bxd6
{ This looks very unambitious but has been played several times by GM Tamir Nabaty with reasonable success. }
5... Qxd6 6. c4
{ This is White's only chance to fight for an advantage.  Alternatives like   6.Nbd2  give Black very easy play. For example  6...O-O  7.Bd3  Nbd7  8.O-O  e5=  is very pleasant. }
6... O-O 7. Nc3 dxc4
{ The simplest and most direct route towards equality. We're ready to break in the center next with ...c7-c5. Note that the immediate break 7... c5 leaves us with an isolated pawn after 8. cxd5 exd5 9. dxc5 which I'd rather avoid. This is the reason we first take on c4. }
8. Bxc4 c5 { Immediately challenging White's center. } 9. Nb5
{ displaces our queen but we'll recoup the tempo by pushing White's knight back in the future with ...a6. }
9... Qe7 10. dxc5 Qxc5 11. Rc1
{ White is threatening to drop back the bishop and play Nc7, but Black shouldn't be afraid of ghosts. }
11... a6 { Kicking White's knight. } 12. Nbd4 Qb4+
{ is a small nuance, forcing White's queen to d2 where it will be exposed to ...Ne4.   The immediate  12...Qe7  is also playable. }
13. Qd2 Qe7 { The queen is well placed on e7, supporting ...e7-e5. } 14. O-O e5
{ followed by ...Bg4 and ...Nc6. Black can then bring the rooks to c and d-files with no issues whatsoever. }
