1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 { The London system } 2... Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Nf3 Bd6
{ Instead of retreating the bishop } 5. Nbd2
{ saw an upswing in popularity towards the end of 2020 with Carlsen and Giri playing it a couple of times. White's main point is to hold back the development of the light-squared bishop so that if we play ...b6 and ...Ba6 he can go Bxa6 in one go  (that is, without having first spent a tempo on Bd3)  . }
5... O-O
{ White hasn't yet committed the light-squared bishop with Bd3 so we should first castle instead of capturing on f4.   In the Chessable course 'The London System: Essential Theory', IM John Bartholomew and FM Daniel Barrish only consider  5...Bxf4  .   We don't go for  5...Bxf4  as after  6.exf4  Qd6  does not come with the threat of ...Qb4+ as in the5.Bd3 line since White already has his knight on d2.  7.g3  Qb4  is simply met by  8.Rb1⩲  when our queen on b4 is misplaced. While this position is still playable, White has a small advantage. }
6. Bxd6
{ is essentially harmless as White won't be able to establish a knight on e5 this way. }
6... Qxd6 7. c4 c5 { gives White no chances for an advantage. } 8. dxc5 Qxc5 9.
cxd5 Qxd5
{ Black comfortably equalized and the point was later split in ½-½ @@StartBracket@@29@@EndBracket@@ Carlsen, M @@StartBracket@@2832@@EndBracket@@ -Anand, V  @@StartBracket@@2786@@EndBracket@@ Leuven 2017. }
