1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 { The London system } 2... Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Nf3 Bd6
{ immediately fighting for the e5 square and clearing the way for ...O-O. } 5.
Nbd2 O-O
{ White hasn't yet committed the light-squared bishop with Bd3 so we should first castle instead of capturing on f4.   In the Chessable course 'The London System: Essential Theory', IM John Bartholomew and FM Daniel Barrisch only consider  5...Bxf4 }
6. Bd3
{ Once White has committed to Bd3, we can safely chop off the bishop on f4 with }
6... Bxf4
{ This is the most straightforward approach.   It is also possible to delay this capture with  6...b6  , which is analternative recommendation. }
7. exf4 b6
{ preparing to both undermine White's center with ...c5 and exchange the light-squared bishops with ...Ba6. }
8. O-O c5
{ challenging White's center. Next up is ...Ba6.   The immediate  8...Ba6  is also possible although it gives White the extra option of playing  9.Rc1  and trying to break with c4. By playing 8...c5 first, we provoke 9. c3 which eliminates this possibility. }
9. c3 Ba6 10. Bxa6 Nxa6 11. Ne5 Qc7
{ White has no prospects of a kingside attack without the bishops. He has good control over the e5 square, but Black has more space on the queenside and can quickly expand on this side of the board. }
12. Qe2 Nb8 13. Ndf3 Nc6
{ Black has comfortably equalized. He can start thinking about playing for an advantage with ...c4 followed by a queenside expansion with ...b5, ...a5 and ...b4. Another common maneuver in this structure is ...Ne7-f5. }
*

