1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 { The London system } 2... Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Nf3 Bd6
{ immediately fighting for the e5 square and clearing the way for ...O-O. } 5.
Nbd2 O-O
{ White hasn't yet committed the light-squared bishop with Bd3 so we should first castle instead of capturing on f4.   In the Chessable course 'The London System: Essential Theory', IM John Bartholomew and FM Daniel Barrisch only consider  5...Bxf4 }
6. c3
{ White cleverly postpones the development of his light-squared bishop. He is anticipating our plan of ... b6 followed by ...Ba6 and wants to capture on a6 without having spent a tempo on Bd3. This gained some attention in 2020 when Anish Giri and Magnus Carlsen used this tricky move order to take down super-GM opposition. However, there is nothing to fear and he can only hold back the bishop for so long. }
6... c5 7. Bd3 Bxf4
{ is an important move.   Here we have to deviate from our standard plan of  7...Qc7  as after  8.Bxd6  Qxd6  9.Ne5  Nbd7  10.f4  White is in time to establish his knight on e5 since we don't have the option of ...Ne4 followed by ...f6. }
8. exf4 Qb6
{ is rather awkward for White. There is no convenient way of covering the b2 pawn.   8...b6  is another reliable option but the text is more incisive. }
9. Qc2
{ 9.Qb3?!  drops a pawn to  9...Qc7∓  when we're threatening a fork with ...c4 and the f4 pawn is hanging.   9.Rb1  cxd4  10.Nxd4  Qc7=  followed by ... Nc6 is very comfortable.   9.b3  only weakens White's position. After  9...Nc6  Black has good pressure against the d4 pawn. }
9... cxd4 { is very timely. } 10. Nxd4
{ Worse is  10.cxd4?!  as after  10...Nc6  the d4 pawn is falling. Note that  11.Nb3  gets hit by  11...Nb4∓ }
10... Qc7
{ dropping back to attack the f4 pawn, which effectively forces White's knight back. }
11. Ne2 { 11.g3?!  runs into  11...e5⩱ } 11... b6
{ followed by ...Ba6 is very pleasant for Black. White's doubled f-pawns mean the position is already ever slightly preferable for Black. }
