[Black "5. Nbd2 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 { The London system } 2... Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Nf3 Bd6
{ immediately fighting for the e5 square and clearing the way for ...O-O. } 5.
Nbd2 O-O
{ White hasn't yet committed the light-squared bishop with Bd3 so we should first castle instead of capturing on f4.   In the Chessable course 'The London System: Essential Theory', IM John Bartholomew and FM Daniel Barrisch only consider  5...Bxf4 }
6. c3
{ White cleverly postpones the development of his light-squared bishop. He is anticipating our plan of ... b6 followed by ...Ba6 and wants to capture on a6 without having spent a tempo on Bd3. This gained some attention in 2020 when Anish Giri and Magnus Carlsen used this tricky move order to take down super-GM opposition. However, there is nothing to fear and he can only hold back the bishop for so long. }
6... c5 7. Ne5 Qc7
{ We've seen this before. The queen is very well placed on c7 and puts pressure on the e5 knight, which we have the option of challenging with ...Nbd7/...Nc6 next. We're effectively following the same approach as the 6. Bg3 lines.   7...b6?!  is too slow. After  8.h4  Qc7  9.h5⩲  White's pawn is about to land on h6, a position we certainly shouldn't allow. }
8. h4
{ is premature and backfires right away because White lacks control over the e4 square. We first challenge the knight with }
8... Nc6 9. Ndf3
{ 9.Nxc6  is met by  9...Bxf4  10.exf4  bxc6  11.g3  Qb6⩱  with a double-attack on the d4 and b2 pawns gives Black the advantage. }
9... cxd4
{ is a timely moment to capture on d4.   The immediate  9...Ne4  allows  10.Nxc6  Bxf4  and  11.Ne7  Qxe7  12.exf4  . This position is still playable but Black can get more.  By chopping on d4 first with 9...cxd4, after 10. exd4, White no longer has this option because the bishop on f4 will no longer be hanging  (i.e. White no longer has a pawn on e3 to be able to play exf4 at the end of the line)  . }
10. exd4
{ Because White didn't play Bd3 and had to reinforce his knight on e5 with Ndf3, he has completely surrendered control over the e4 square, enabling us to jump ahead with }
10... Ne4
{ followed by ...f6, which will purge White's knight from e5. White is already in trouble due to the pin. }
