{ Our standard way of challenging the knight on e5.   9...Nc6  or  9...b6  are also playable. }
10. Ndf3
{ once again maintains White's knight on e5, but ties up all of White's pieces on this task. In particular, the e4 break is no longer available. That's green light for Black to start active operations on the queenside with }
10... c4 11. Bc2
{ 11.Bb1  is a worse square for the bishop, and doesn't change our plan  11...b5  12.Qc2  b4=  followed by ...Ne4 is very pleasant. }
11... b5 12. Re1 b4
{ Next up is ...Bb7.   Black is in great shape and can easily take over, as the following sample continuation illustrates  13.Nxd7  Bxd7  14.Bxd6  Qxd6  15.Ne5  Bb5  16.e4  Nxe4  17.Bxe4  dxe4  18.Rxe4  f6  19.Ng4  Be8⩱  rerouting the bishop to g6 with a slight advantage. @@StartBracket@@Note: you can choose to train this continuation in the next alternative line@@EndBracket@@. }
