[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7. London (1...d5 and 1...Nf6 2...e6)"]
[Black "5. Nbd2 #7 [details #1]"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 { The London system } 2... Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Nf3 Bd6
{ immediately fighting for the e5 square and clearing the way for ...O-O. } 5.
Nbd2 O-O
{ White hasn't yet committed the light-squared bishop with Bd3 so we should first castle instead of capturing on f4.   In the Chessable course 'The London System: Essential Theory', IM John Bartholomew and FM Daniel Barrisch only consider  5...Bxf4 }
6. c3
{ White cleverly postpones the development of his light-squared bishop. He is anticipating our plan of ... b6 followed by ...Ba6 and wants to capture on a6 without having spent a tempo on Bd3. This gained some attention in 2020 when Anish Giri and Magnus Carlsen used this tricky move order to take down super-GM opposition. However, there is nothing to fear and he can only hold back the bishop for so long. }
6... c5 7. Ne5 Qc7
{ We've seen this before. The queen is very well placed on c7 and puts pressure on the e5 knight, which we have the option of challenging with ... Nbd7 next.   7...b6?!  is too slow. After  8.h4  Qc7  9.h5⩲  White's pawn is about to land on h6, a position we certainly shouldn't allow. }
8. Bd3 { White can't hold back this move any longer. } 8... a5
{ is a key novelty that solves all of Black's problems. It starts play on the queenside, so if we choose to close down the center with ... c4, then we're already ready for a quick ...b5-b4. Secondly, it makes it impossible for White to prevent us from exchanging the light-squared bishops with ...b6 followed by ... Ba6 should we choose to do so @@StartBracket@@note that the immediate ...b6 would be met with Qe2@@EndBracket@@. }
9. O-O Nbd7 { Our standard way of challenging the knight on e5. } 10. Ndf3
{ once again maintains White's knight on e5, but ties up all of White's pieces on this task. In particular, the e4 break is no longer available. That's green light for Black to start active operations on the queenside with }
10... c4 11. Bc2
{ 11.Bb1  is a worse square for the bishop, and doesn't change our plan  11...b5  12.Qc2  b4=  followed by ...Ne4 is very pleasant. }
11... b5 12. Re1 b4
{ Next up is ... Bb7. Black is in great shape and can easily take over, as the following sample continuation illustrates }
13. Nxd7 Bxd7 14. Bxd6 Qxd6 15. Ne5 Bb5
{ Having defended the c4 pawn, we're now ready to plant our knight on e4. } 16.
e4
{ brings White nothing.   16.Qf3  stops ...Ne4 but that's about it. We can press on with our queenside play with  16...bxc3   16...a4  is also good.  17.bxc3  Qa3  Black has easy play with ... Ba4 and ... Rab8 up next. }
16... Nxe4 17. Bxe4 dxe4 18. Rxe4 f6 { send White's knight packing. After } 19.
Ng4 Be8
{ is an instructive maneuver, rerouting the bishop to g6 with a slight advantage.   Note that  19...f5  does not win material on account of  20.Re5  attacking our bishop. }
