[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7. London (1...d5 and 1...Nf6 2...e6)"]
[Black "3. e3 4. c3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 d5 3. e3 e6 4. c3
{ only has independent value when after...   4.Nf3  transposes to the mainline }
4... Bd6 { ...White goes for } 5. Bxd6
{ and follows up with f4, erecting a Stonewall pawn structure. } 5... Qxd6 6.
f4
{ At first sight, this might look clever and was recommended by GM Simon Williams in the Chessbase FritzTrainer 'The London System with 2.Bf4'. White exchanged the dark-squared bishops and only then set up the Stonewall. As such, there is no bad bishop on c1.   However, we're on move 6 and White hasn't developed a single piece while Black already has two pieces out! Given this, it's not surprising that the evaluation bar is already dipping below zero, meaning the engines already think Black is better. }
6... c5
{ was not considered by Simon Williams in the aforementioned DVD. He only examined 6...O-O, which is equally popular to 6...c5. The NNUE engines much prefer delaying castling and instead develop the light-squared bishop first. }
7. Nf3
{ Alternatively  7.Nd2  can be met with  7...Bd7  when  8.Ngf3  runs into   8.g3  O-O  9.Bd3  Qb6⩱  8...Ng4  hitting the e3 pawn. White can cover it with  9.Qe2  but after  9...cxd4  10.cxd4  O-O⩱  White's pieces are stepping on each other. Black is already considerably better.   7.Nh3?!  heading to f2 has been played a couple of times when  7...Qb6  is novel and strong. After  8.Qb3  Nc6  9.Nf2  Ne7!  threatening to attack the e3 pawn with Nf5.  10.Bd3  Bd7  11.O-O  c4⩱  gives Black the upper hand. }
7... Bd7
{ A very clever move suggested by both Stockfish and Leela! The idea is to play ...Qb6, hitting the b2 pawn and preparing ...Bb5 to exchange the light-squared bishops. Once they're off the board, White will be riddled with light-squared weaknesses. }
8. Bd3
{ 8.a4  runs into  8...cxd4  9.cxd4  Qb4+  10.Qd2  Qxd2+  11.Nbxd2  Ke7⩱  with a superior endgame }
8... Qb6 { Hitting the b2 pawn. Next up is ...Bb5. } 9. Qc2 Bb5 10. Bxb5+ Qxb5
{ The light-squared bishops are off the board. White, who placed all his pawns on dark-squares, has now been left with several weak squares on this color complex. For example, the e4 square is now a fantastic outpost for our knight. If that weren't already enough, White can't even castle right now. }
11. Qe2
{ 11.Nbd2  can be met with  11...O-O  12.a4  Qb6  13.O-O  Nc6⩱  with a slight advantage. }
11... Qb6
{ keeps tabs on the b2 pawn, making it very hard for White to develop the knight on b1. }
12. O-O O-O
{ Next up are ...Nc6, ...Ne4 and ...Rc8 with a slight advantage. White's light squares are weak and he'll have a hard time developing his queenside. }
