1. d4 d5 2. e4
{ 2.f3  Nf6  3.e4  dxe4  4.Nc3  is another way to reach the Blackmar-Diemer Gambit. }
2... dxe4 { Before considering the main move } 3. Nc3
{ we are first going to discuss  3.f3  which has been played in 300+ OTB games. }
3... Nf6 4. f3
{ is the true Blackmar-Diemer gambit @@StartBracket@@BDG for short@@EndBracket@@, one of the few gambits at White's disposal after 1. d4. This gambit has been played in over 11000 OTB games.  In exchange for a pawn, White gains a tempo and a half-open f-file. Rapid development and active positioning of the minor pieces with Bc4 and Nf3-e5 is typically the name of the game in this gambit, hoping to start an attack against Black's king.  It might have enjoyed some success in the romantic era, but today's engines believe it is very suspect. I'll be recommending a fianchetto setup with ...g6, which completely neutralizes White's attacking chances and is the top choice of the neural network engines.   Also covered are  4.Bg5  and  4.Bc4  which are objectively very dubious but still relatively popular in online blitz. They have occurred in 900+ and 100+ OTB games respectively. }
4... exf3 5. Nxf3 g6
{ is my recommendation and the top choice of the neural network engines, coming very close to putting the BDG out of business. We are going to cover White's three main moves in this position, namely   6.Bg5  which occurred in 130+ OTB games   6.Bf4  seen in 170+ OTB games   and  6.Bc4  played in 1700+ OTB games }
*

