1. d4 d5 2. e4 dxe4 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. f3
{ is the true Blackmar-Diemer gambit @@StartBracket@@BDG for short@@EndBracket@@, one of the few gambits at White's disposal after 1. d4.   In exchange for a pawn, White gains a tempo and a half-open f-file. Rapid development and active positioning of the minor pieces with Bc4 and Nf3-e5 is typically the name of the game in this gambit, hoping to start an attack against Black's king.  It might have enjoyed some success in the romantic era, but today's engines believe it is very suspect. I'll be recommending a fianchetto setup with ...g6, which completely neutralizes White's attacking chances and is the top choice of the neural network engines. }
4... exf3 5. Qxf3 Qxd4 6. Be3 Qg4
{ Simple and logical, proposing a queen exchange as we're a pawn up. } 7. Qf2
Qf5 { insisting on the queen exchange and threatening a fork with ...Ng4. } 8.
Qd2 e6
{ is solid, preparing to develop the bishop to e7 and castle short. We will have no trouble developing the light-squared bishop as it can get out with ...Bd7-c6.   The text is slightly more accurate than  8...e5  which blocks our queen from being able to swing over to the queenside in case it is attacked. For example  9.O-O-O  Be7  10.h3  O-O  11.g4  Here we have to drop our queen back, which would not be the case with 8...e6 when we could have swung it over to a5.  11...Qe6  12.g5  Nh5  Black is still better here but there is no need to give White these options. This is the main reason why 8...e6 is better. }
9. O-O-O Be7 10. Nf3 O-O
{ followed by ...Nc6 and ...e5 gives Black a clear advantage. White has close to no compensation for the missing pawns. }
