[White "9. Blackmar-Diemer Gambit (1...d5)"]
[Black "5. Nxf3 6. Bf4 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. e4 dxe4 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. f3
{ is the true Blackmar-Diemer gambit @@StartBracket@@BDG for short@@EndBracket@@, one of the few gambits at White's disposal after 1. d4.   In exchange for a pawn, White gains a tempo and a half-open f-file. Rapid development and active positioning of the minor pieces with Bc4 and Nf3-e5 is typically the name of the game in this gambit, hoping to start an attack against Black's king.  It might have enjoyed some success in the romantic era, but today's engines believe it is very suspect. I'll be recommending a fianchetto setup with ...g6, which completely neutralizes White's attacking chances and is the top choice of the neural network engines. }
4... exf3 5. Nxf3 g6
{ is both Leela and Stockfish's top choice. It also makes perfect sense. White is a pawn down and his only chance is to try and mount an attack against our king. By fianchettoing the dark-squared bishop, White's chances of mounting a successful attack are very slim. }
6. Bf4
{ Scheerer in his book on the BDG calls this the Longo Bogo. He believes it is a promising continuation for White. Today's neural network engines @@StartBracket@@which to be fair were not available when he wrote his book@@EndBracket@@ do not agree. }
6... Bg7 7. Qd2
{ 7.Bc4  can be met with  7...O-O  After  8.Qd2  Nc6  9.O-O-O   9.d5  runs into  9...Na5!  9...Bg4  10.Rhe1  Nb4  11.a3  Nbd5  heading to d5.  12.Nxd5  Nxd5  13.Bh6  Bxf3  14.gxf3  e6  Black is a clean pawn up. }
7... O-O
{ Our king is very safe on the kingside. The fianchetto setup is notoriously difficult to crack. }
8. O-O-O c6 9. Bh6 { is more to the point than 9. h4. } 9... Bg4
{ We bring out our light-squared bishop first before developing the knight. We can chop off White's knight at an opportune moment and reduce his attacking potential. }
10. Be2 Nbd7 11. h3 Bxf3 12. Bxf3 Nb6
{ Exclam! We're threatening ...Nc4, attacking White's queen which is the sole defender of the bishop on h6. This forces White to either retreat his dark-squared bishop or capture on g7.   This powerful move was not considered in the 'The Blackmar-Diemer Gambit' book by Christoph Scheerer nor in IndrekR's Chessable course BDG for Blitz. }
13. h4
{ is White's most natural move, intending to push ahead with h5 to try and open up the h-file @@StartBracket@@I say try because it won't happen!@@EndBracket@@. White's attack won't ever get off the ground if Black plays precisely. The upcoming variation is rather long but Black's play is very logical and any deviations by the first player lead to a completely lost position. }
13... Nc4
{ brings the knight into the attack with tempo. Yes, we're about to attack White's king with ...Qb6! }
14. Qg5 Bxh6
{ is an important move, distracting the queen from the 5th rank. As we're about to see, we need access to the a5 square to attack White's king. }
15. Qxh6 Qb6 { Threatens mate on b2, forcing White to weaken his king with }
16. b3 Qa5
{ threatening mate in 2 with ...Qa3+ and Qb2#. Black is the only one attacking here! Now it becomes clear why we played 14...Bxh6. If White's queen were still on g5, ...Qa5 would not be possible. }
17. Nb1
{ Finally, our knight on c4 is hanging so we have to drop it back with } 17...
Nd6
{ which is an excellent square for the knight. We're threatening ...Nf5, which will expel White's queen from the kingside and end any hopes of an attack. Thus }
18. g4 { is the only way to continue the attack. Now } 18... Rae8
{ is very strong! The idea is to break in the center with ...e5. As the famous saying goes, flank attacks are best met with counterplay in the center! }
19. h5 { 19.g5??  loses on the spot to  19...Nf5−+  trapping White's queen! }
19... g5
{ not only closes the door on White's attack but threatens to win his queen with ...Kg8 and ...Ng8 as well as ...Nfe4, ...f6 and ...Nd6f7! We could already stop here but let's consider the last of White's resources. }
20. Rhe1
{ with the idea Re5 is the only way to continue.   20.d5?  loses to  20...Nfe4  21.dxc6  f6−+  Next up is ...Nf7 which will capture White's queen. Black is winning. }
20... Nd7 21. Re5
{ is practically forced, transfering the game into a hopeless endgame for the first player after...   21.Be4?  loses to  21...Nxe4  as after  22.Rxe4  f6−+  locks out White's queen. Black will break through on the queenside with ...b5, ...Qc7 and ...c5 with a decisive advantage. }
21... Nxe5 22. Qxg5+ Kh8 23. Qxe5+
{ 23.dxe5??  loses on the spot to  23...f6  exploiting the pin along the 5th rank. After  24.Qf4  Qxe5−+  Black is winning. }
23... Qxe5 24. dxe5 Nb5
{ The smoke has cleared and Black is up an exchange. White can penetrate along the 7th rank with }
25. Rd7 { but } 25... Rc8
{ with the idea ...Rc7 puts an end to any hopes White had of getting enough compensation. }
26. a4
{ Alternatively  26.Rxb7  can be met with  26...Rc7  27.Bxc6  Rxc6  28.Rxb5  a6−+  Next up are ...Re6 and ...Rg8 when White's pawns will drop one by one.   Worse is  26.Rxe7?  as  26...Rc7  forces the rooks off the board when  27.Rxc7  Nxc7−+  is hopeless for White. }
26... Nc7 27. Rxe7 Kg8
{ Black will play ...Rfe8 next and shouldn't have much trouble converting the extra exchange.   I know we went until move 27, but White has to play like this to not lose immediately while Black's play is very logical. We came across several important defensive @@StartBracket@@and attacking!@@EndBracket@@ resources for Black, the knowledge of which are extremely valuable in a practical game and justify examining these 27 moves. }
