[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10. Hübsch Gambit (1...d5 and 1...Nf6 2. Nc3 3. e4)"]
[Black "Chapter overview"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3
{ 2.f3  d5  3.e4  dxe4  4.Nc3  transposes to the Blackmar-Diemer Gambit covered in chapter9.   2.g4  The Bronstein Gambit - a bullet weapon with a cult following - is refuted in one trainable line.  Threatens to expand in the center with e2-e4, which we immediately stop with }
2... d5
{ when White's knight on c3 is misplaced, stopping White from breaking in the center with c2-c4. }
3. e4
{ The Hübsch Gambit, overall very dubious but Black does need to know how to punish it.   This gambit can also arise from the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Nc3  Nf6  3.e4  Nxe4  move order. }
3... Nxe4
{ is the easiest way to punish White's dubious Gambit. After this move, White will not even be able to open the f-file. As such, the first player has even less compensation  (actually no compensation!)  for the pawn than in the Blackmar-Diemer Gambit.   3...dxe4  4.f3  transposes to the Blackmar-Diemer Gambit, which is covered via the 1. d4 d5 2. e4 move order. Refer to chapter9 for the details. }
4. Nxe4 dxe4 5. Bc4
{ is White's most popular continuation with 800+ OTB games.   5.f3  is the 2nd most common move with 300+ OTB games.   5.Be3  is pretty rare with 50+ OTB games.   5.Bf4  is also not very popular with 70+ OTB games. }
*

