{ As we'll see throughout this course, when White places his knight on d2 early on, it's often a good idea to break with ...c5 as the d4 pawn is unprotected. }
4. dxc5 e6
{ Having examined the alternatives, its now time to turn our attention to White's main move A better way to defend the c5 pawn is }
5. Nb3 { although after } 5... Nbd7 { it's certainly dropping. } 6. e4
{ was once played by Baduur Jobava, which is about the only reason to have a look at this move. It's unlikely to be repeated again since White will have to waste valuable time recouping the pawn. }
6... dxe4 7. Ne2 h6
{ Putting the question to the bishop.   This is stronger than the hasty  7...Bxc5  as after  8.Nxc5  Qa5  9.Nc3  Qxc5  10.Be3  Qc6  11.Qd4  White has good compensation for the pawn with O-O-O coming next. }
8. Bh4 a5 9. Nc3 a4 { sends White's knight packing. } 10. Nd2 Be7
{ This is stronger than the immediate  10...Nxc5  as after  11.Ndxe4  Ncxe4  12.Nxe4  Bd7  13.Nxf6⩱  compromises Black's structure and gives White some compensation. The c5 pawn isn't going anywhere so Black does best in starting with 10. Be7 and is now threatening to go ...Nxc5 in better conditions @@StartBracket@@after the same sequence he'll be able to recapture with the bishop on f6@@EndBracket@@. }
11. Bxf6
{ 11.Bb5  O-O  12.Nxa4  runs into  12...e3  13.fxe3  Nd5⩱  when White's pieces are scattered all over the board. }
11... Nxf6 12. Ndxe4 O-O
{ White won't be able to hold on to the c5 pawn @@StartBracket@@we can even play ...Ra5 if required@@EndBracket@@. Once it falls, the two bishops will make their presence felt. }
