[White "11. Trompowsky (1...Nf6)"]
[Black "3. Nd2 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5
{ The Trompowsky is named after the one-time Brazilian champion Octávio Trompowsky, who played it extensively in the 1930s and 1940s.  It is one of the most popular d4 systems, not due to 2. Bg5 being a particularly good move, but mainly because it sidesteps large bodies of theory in the various Indian Defenses such as the Nimzo, QID, KID, and Grünfeld.  White’s intention is to double Black’s pawns with Bxf6 and try to exploit the resulting rigidity in Black’s structure. However, this comes at cost of the two bishops and valuable time as White spent two tempi with the bishop only to trade it off for a knight that only moved once.   As such, I see no need to avoid White’s ‘threat’ of Bxf6 and prefer immediately occupying the center with }
2... d5 3. Nd2 c5
{ As we'll see throughout this course, when White places his knight on d2 early on, it's often a good idea to break with ...c5 as the d4 pawn is unprotected. }
4. dxc5 e6
{ Having examined the alternatives, its now time to turn our attention to White's main move A better way to defend the c5 pawn is }
5. Nb3 { although after } 5... Nbd7 { it's certainly dropping. } 6. e3 Nxc5 7.
Nxc5 Bxc5
{ We're now threatening ...Qb6, which not only hits the b2 pawn but breaks the pin, enabling ...Ne4. }
8. Bb5+
{ 8.c3  O-O  9.Nf3  h6  10.Bh4  Be7=  was very comfortable for Black in ½-½ @@StartBracket@@33@@EndBracket@@ Demian,M @@StartBracket@@2210@@EndBracket@@-Geiger,W @@StartBracket@@2232@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2013. }
8... Kf8
{ Unusual but very strong. The point is that ...Qb6 will come with a tempo on White's light-squared bishop. }
9. c3 Qb6 10. Bd3
{ This position was reached in the game ½-½ @@StartBracket@@35@@EndBracket@@ Matuszewski, M @@StartBracket@@2508@@EndBracket@@-Wojtaszek, R @@StartBracket@@2717@@EndBracket@@ Warsaw 2020, where Black played 10...e5. Stronger was }
10... Ne4
{ hitting the bishop on g5.   10...Qxb2  also gives Black an advantage but the text is stronger. }
11. Bf4 { is strongly met by } 11... f6
{ followed by ...e5 with complete control.   And not  11...Qxb2??  as  12.Bxe4  wins a piece due to back rank mate on d8, i.e.  12...Qxc3  13.Kf1  dxe4  14.Qd8  is game over. }
*

