1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 d5 3. Bxf6 { is the main move by a wide margin. } 3... exf6 4.
e3 c6
{ It's time to take stock. Black has the two bishops in exchange for doubled f-pawns. We'll usually place our dark-squared bishop on d6, play ...f5 to take control over the e4 square, and develop with ...Nd7-f6. White has three main setups depending on how he develops his light-squared bishop:   @@StartBracket@@1@@EndBracket@@ fianchetto it with g3 and Bg2.   @@StartBracket@@2@@EndBracket@@ place it on d3 and follow up with Qf3.   @@StartBracket@@3@@EndBracket@@ break in the center with c4 and develop the light-squared bishop to c4. }
