[White "11. Trompowsky (1...Nf6)"]
[Black "5. g3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5
{ The Trompowsky is named after the one-time Brazilian champion Octávio Trompowsky, who played it extensively in the 1930s and 1940s.  It is one of the most popular d4 systems, not due to 2. Bg5 being a particularly good move, but mainly because it sidesteps large bodies of theory in the various Indian Defenses such as the Nimzo, QID, KID, and Grünfeld.  White’s intention is to double Black’s pawns with Bxf6 and try to exploit the resulting rigidity in Black’s structure. However, this comes at cost of the two bishops and valuable time as White spent two tempi with the bishop only to trade it off for a knight that only moved once.   As such, I see no need to avoid White’s ‘threat’ of Bxf6 and prefer immediately occupying the center with }
2... d5 3. Bxf6 { The main move by a wide margin. } 3... exf6 4. e3 c6
{ It's time to take stock. Black has the two bishops in exchange for doubled f-pawns - a favorable exchange in my book as a fan of the two bishops.   We'll usually play ...f5 to take control over the e4 square, develop with ...Nd7-f6 and place our dark-squared bishop on d6. }
5. g3
{ Setup @@StartBracket@@1@@EndBracket@@: the fianchetto   The g3 pawn limits the scope of our dark-squared bishop but acts as a hook for ...h5-h4. If White isn't careful, Black can easily launch a big kingside attack. }
5... f5 { Taking control over the e4 square. Next up is ...Nd7-f6. } 6. Bg2 Nd7
7. Ne2 Bd6 8. O-O
{ is very natural but inaccurate. White essentially castles into an attack.   8.Nd2  will transpose to the mainline with7. Nd2. }
8... h5 { Starts immediate play against White's king. } 9. h4
{ stops the h-pawn but Black can break open the kingside with } 9... g5 10.
hxg5 Qxg5 11. Nd2
{ with the idea Nf3, attacking Black's queen and taking control over the h4 square. }
11... Qh6 { Stepping out of Nf3. } 12. Nf3 Nf8
{ followed by ...Be6 and ...O-O-O gives Black the advantage. White will have a very hard time stopping our kingside attack once we complete development.   The immediate  12...Be7  intending a quick ...h4 is also strong. }
*

