1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5
{ The Trompowsky is named after the one-time Brazilian champion Octávio Trompowsky, who played it extensively in the 1930s and 1940s.  It is one of the most popular d4 systems, not due to 2. Bg5 being a particularly good move, but mainly because it sidesteps large bodies of theory in the various Indian Defenses such as the Nimzo, QID, KID, and Grünfeld.  White’s intention is to double Black’s pawns with Bxf6 and try to exploit the resulting rigidity in Black’s structure. However, this comes at cost of the two bishops and valuable time as White spent two tempi with the bishop only to trade it off for a knight that only moved once.   As such, I see no need to avoid White’s ‘threat’ of Bxf6 and prefer immediately occupying the center with }
2... d5 3. Bxf6 { The main move by a wide margin. } 3... exf6 4. e3 c6
{ It's time to take stock. Black has the two bishops in exchange for doubled f-pawns - a favorable exchange in my book as a fan of the two bishops.   We'll usually play ...f5 to take control over the e4 square, develop our knight with ...Nd7-f6 and place our dark-squared bishop on d6. }
5. g3
{ Setup @@StartBracket@@1@@EndBracket@@: the fianchetto. The g3 pawn limits the scope of our dark-squared bishop but acts as a hook for ... h5-h4. If White isn't careful, Black can easily launch a big kingside attack. }
5... f5 { Taking control over the e4 square. Next up is ...Nd7-f6. } 6. Bg2 Nd7
7. Nd2 Nf6
{ It's slightly more accurate to start with this move rather than 7. ...Bd6. The reason is that if White goes for an early c4, we can chop the pawn and then develop the bishop with tempo by playing ...Bb4+. }
8. Ne2 Bd6 9. c4 dxc4 10. Nxc4 Bc7
{ Preserving the dark-squared bishop. Next up is ...h5-h4. } 11. O-O
{ 11.Qc2  doesn't have much independent value. We can continue with  11...h5  which was not covered in IM Richard Pert's book 'Playing the Trompowsky'.  12.h4  O-O  with similar play to the mainline. }
11... h5
{ with the idea ...h4 to open up the h-file. This logical move was not considered in Kamil Plitcha's Chessable course 'Break the rules: Play the Trompowsky'. }
12. h4 Be6 { stops d5 and hits White's knight. } 13. Qc2 Ng4
{ with the idea ...g5 gives Black easy play.   14.Nd2  prevents ...g5 as it can be strongly met with Nf3. In this case, Black should instead go for  14...O-O  15.Rac1  g6  16.Nb3  Bd5=  proposing an exchange of light-squared bishops, which favors Black. }
*

