1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5
{ The Trompowsky is named after the one-time Brazilian champion Octávio Trompowsky, who played it extensively in the 1930s and 1940s.  It is one of the most popular d4 systems, not due to 2. Bg5 being a particularly good move, but mainly because it sidesteps large bodies of theory in the various Indian Defenses such as the Nimzo, QID, KID, and Grünfeld.  White’s intention is to double Black’s pawns with Bxf6 and try to exploit the resulting rigidity in Black’s structure. However, this comes at cost of the two bishops and valuable time as White spent two tempi with the bishop only to trade it off for a knight that only moved once.   As such, I see no need to avoid White’s ‘threat’ of Bxf6 and prefer immediately occupying the center with }
2... d5 3. Bxf6 { The main move by a wide margin. } 3... exf6 4. e3 c6
{ It's now time to examine Setup @@StartBracket@@2@@EndBracket@@ where White goes }
5. Bd3 { and follows up with Nd2 and Qf3. } 5... Bd6 6. Nd2 Qe7 7. Qf3
{ White's plan is quite ambitious. He wants to expand on the kingside with h3 and g4, and will tuck his king away on the queenside. However, Black is very well equipped to deal with this. }
7... g6 { The immediate pawn advance } 8. g4 { is premature because of } 8...
h5 { The point is that reinforcing the g4 pawn with } 9. h3
{ drops a pawn after } 9... hxg4 { 9...Bc7⩱  also gives Black an edge. } 10.
hxg4 Rxh1 11. Qxh1 Bxg4 12. Qh8+ Kd7
{ White has insufficient compensation for the material deficit.   A sample continuation is  13.Ne2  Be6  14.O-O-O  Qd8  15.Qh6  Na6  Black has disentangled and is still a pawn up. }
