1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5
{ The Trompowsky is named after the one-time Brazilian champion Octávio Trompowsky, who played it extensively in the 1930s and 1940s.  It is one of the most popular d4 systems, not due to 2. Bg5 being a particularly good move, but mainly because it sidesteps large bodies of theory in the various Indian Defenses such as the Nimzo, QID, KID, and Grünfeld.  White’s intention is to double Black’s pawns with Bxf6 and try to exploit the resulting rigidity in Black’s structure. However, this comes at cost of the two bishops and valuable time as White spent two tempi with the bishop only to trade it off for a knight that only moved once.   As such, I see no need to avoid White’s ‘threat’ of Bxf6 and prefer immediately occupying the center with }
2... d5 3. Bxf6 { The main move by a wide margin. } 3... exf6 4. e3 c6
{ Setup @@StartBracket@@3@@EndBracket@@: White breaks with 5. c4 } 5. c4
{ This is White's most popular continuation. } 5... dxc4 6. Bxc4
{ White's bishop is more active on c4, but in the process White has also opened up the position for our two bishops. }
6... Bd6 7. Nc3
{ is by far White's most common move.   7.Nf3  is also possible  7...O-O  8.O-O  f5  9.Qc2  Nd7=  comfortably equalizes. Note that  10.Qxf5??  loses as  10...Ne5  11.Qc2  Nxf3+!  12.Kh1  Qh4  is lights out   7.Qb3  is similar  7...O-O  8.Nc3  Nd7  9.Nf3  Nb6  10.Bd3  g6  11.Qc2  Be6=  gives Black a great game   Worse is  7.Qh5  when  7...O-O  8.Nc3  Nd7  9.Nf3  Nb6  10.Bb3  a5⩱  with the idea ...a4 gives Black the upper hand. }
7... Nd7
{ Next up are ...O-O, ...f5 and ...Nf6. Notice how once White gave up his dark-squared bishop, we're placing our pawns on light squares. This restricts White's bishop while giving our unopposed dark-squared bishop extra scope. }
8. Qc2
{ fails to stop f5.   Similarly, after  8.Qf3  we can still play  8...f5!   8.Bd3  also doesn't stop ...f5. After  8...g6  ...f5 is coming anyways. }
8... f5 9. Qxf5 { loses to } 9... Ne5
{ with a double-attack on White's queen and light-squared bishop. } 10. Qe4 f5
{ breaks the pin. Black will pick up the bishop on the next turn with a decisive advantage. }
