[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12. Stonewall (1...Nf6 2...e6)"]
[Black "Chapter overview"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. e3 e6 3. Bd3 d5 4. f4
{ The Stonewall system. White takes firm control over the e5 square with f2-f4. White wants to plant a knight on e5 and then start a kingside attack with Qe1-h4. However, I'm sure the bishop on c1 isn't too happy with the way White arranged his pawns.  When Black has already played ...e6, White's Stonewall system gains slightly in strength. This is because we no longer have the option of developing the light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain. That being said, it's still very unambitious and Black can obtain a great game in a number of ways.   Note that  4.Nf3  b6  5.O-O  Bb7  transposes to the Colle system, which is covered in chapter13. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12. Stonewall (1...Nf6 2...e6)"]
[Black "8. Ne5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. e3 e6 3. Bd3 d5 4. f4
{ The Stonewall system. White takes firm control over the e5 square with f2-f4. White wants to plant a knight on e5 and then start a kingside attack with Qe1-h4. However, I'm sure the bishop on c1 isn't too happy with the way White arranged his pawns.  When Black has already played ...e6, White's Stonewall system gains slightly in strength. This is because we no longer have the option of developing the light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain. That being said, it's still very unambitious and Black can obtain a great game in a number of ways. }
4... c5 5. c3 Bd6
{ Next up is ...O-O. We're then going to fianchetto our light-squared bishop with ...b6 and ...Bb7 taking control over the key e4 square. We delay ...Nc6 in order to better control the e4-square. }
6. Nf3 O-O 7. O-O b6
{ Let us first consider the situation when White immediately jumps into e5 with }
8. Ne5 Bb7
{ We're ready to jump into e4 on the next turn.   Also good is  8...Ba6  to exchange the light-squared bishops. }
9. Nd2
{ Heading to f3 to reinforce his colleague on e5.   9.Qf3  leads to similar play.  9...Ne4  10.Nd2  f5=  is very comfortable. }
9... Ne4
{ Anchoring the knight on the e4 outpost. We're now threatening to kick White's knight with ...f6 and can always reinforce our knight ...f5 if required. }
10. Qc2
{ has never been played but is the top engine choice, challenging the knight on e4. }
10... f5
{ followed by ...Nd7 is very comfortable for Black.   A sample continuation is  10...f5  11.Ndf3  Nd7  12.Bd2  Nxe5  13.fxe5   13.Nxe5  a5  with ...Ba6 up next.  13...Be7⩱  Black has the upper hand. He can transfer the queen to the kingside with ... Qe8-h5 as well as expand on the queenside with ...a6, ...b5 and ...c4. }
*

