1. d4 Nf6 2. e3 e6 3. Bd3 d5 4. f4
{ The Stonewall system. White takes firm control over the e5 square with f2-f4. White wants to plant a knight on e5 and then start a kingside attack with Qe1-h4. However, I'm sure the bishop on c1 isn't too happy with the way White arranged his pawns.  When Black has already played ...e6, White's Stonewall system gains slightly in strength. This is because we no longer have the option of developing the light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain. That being said, it's still very unambitious and Black can obtain a great game in a number of ways. }
4... c5 5. c3 Bd6
{ Next up is ...O-O. We're then going to fianchetto our light-squared bishop with ...b6 and ...Bb7 taking control over the key e4 square. }
6. Nf3 O-O 7. O-O b6
{ Let us first consider the situation when White immediately jumps into e5 with }
8. Ne5 Bb7
{ We're ready to jump into e4 on the next turn.   Also good is  8...Ba6  to exchange the light-squared bishops. }
9. Nd2
{ Heading to f3 to reinforce his colleague on e5.   9.Qf3  leads to similar play.  9...Ne4  10.Nd2  f5=  is very comfortable. }
9... Ne4 10. Nxe4 { is a logical move, eliminating our monster knight on e4. }
10... dxe4 11. Be2 Nc6 12. Bd2
{ intending to activate the dark-squared bishop with Bc1-d2-e1-h4 is a thematic maneuver in the Stonewall. }
12... Ne7
{ heading to f5/d5. We're also ready to kick out White's knight with ...f6 next. }
13. Be1 Nd5 { hits the backward e3 pawn. } 14. Bf2 f6 15. Nc4 Be7
{ Next up is ...Rc8 with a slight advantage. White has less space and a weak pawn on e3. }
