[White "13. Colle (1...Nf6 2...e6)"]
[Black "6. b3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. e3
{ The Colle system, also known as the Colle-Koltanowski system, is named after the Belgian masters Edgard Colle and George Koltanowski.    Characterized by the moves 2. Nf3 and 3. e3, White usually develops his light-squared bishop to d3, the queenside knight to d2, and tries to engineer the pawn break e3-e4. White typically reinforces the d4 pawn with c2-c3 in response to …c5, setting up a triangle or pyramidal pawn structure with pawns on f2, e3, d4, c3, and b2.    Another possible setup is to fianchetto the dark-squared bishop with b3 and Bb2. This is known as the Colle–Zukertort system, named after the Polish-German-British master Johannes Hermann Zukertort. World-renowned German GM and trainer Artur Yusupov played it extensively at the grandmaster level in the 90s. The idea behind White’s construction is to take control firm control over e5 and anchor a knight on this square with Nf3-e5, which can be further reinforced by f2-f4. Yusupov won countless games by then starting a kingside attack with Qe1-h4 and lifting a rook along the third rank with Rf1-f3.   Ever since Black has found several effective ways of countering these plans and the Colle system is nowadays considered innocuous. }
3... b6
{ Having played the Nimzo and QID extensively myself, I always liked meeting the Colle system with the fianchetto. }
4. Bd3 Bb7 5. O-O d5
{ taking a stake in the center. It's time to discuss the setup we're aiming for. We'll place our bishop on d6, b8 knight on d7 and castle kingside. If allowed, we'll then entrench our knight on e4 with . ..f7-f5 and can even start a kingside attack with ... Rf6-h6 and/or ... Qe8-h5. }
6. b3
{ aiming for a Zukertort-style setup. White wants to fianchetto the dark-squared bishop to solidify his control over the e5 square.   6.c4  Bd6  7.Nc3  O-O  transposes to the mainline. }
6... Bd6 7. Bb2 O-O 8. Nbd2 Nbd7 9. c4
{ Black should proceed in similar fashion by jumping into e4 with } 9... Ne4
10. cxd5
{ 10.Ne5  is harmless. After  10...Nxd2  11.Qxd2  Nxe5  12.dxe5  Bc5=  Black is completely fine. }
10... exd5 11. Ne5
{ White is ready to entrench the knight on e5 with f4 next. } 11... Qe7 12. f4
Ndf6
{ reinforcing the knight on e4. We'll always be able to boot White's knight with ...f6, while White no longer has this option since his f-pawn is already on f4. }
13. Rf3
{ is White's typical attacking plan in these structures, intending to swing the rook over to h3. However, it's very hard for White to create any real threats when Black has no weaknesses on the kingside and his bishop on d3 is blocked. }
13... a5
{ is also thematic in these structures. Black intends to create counterplay on the queenside with ...a4 and has the option of proposing an exchange of light-squared bishops with ...Ba6.  This strong move was not considered by GM Milos Pavlovic in the book 'The Modernized Colle-Zukertort'. }
14. Rh3 Bc8 15. g4 g6
{ Stops White's attack before it even started. Black is now threatening to win the g4 pawn with ...Nxd2 followed by ...Nxg4  (without running into Bxh7+ at the end of the line)  .   Note that  15...Bxe5?  does not win a pawn as after  16.dxe5  Bxg4  17.Nxe4  dxe4  18.exf6  Qe6  White can ignore the attack on his queen and play  19.Bxe4  as  19...Bxd1  20.Bxh7  Kh8  21.fxg7  is checkmate! }
16. Bxe4
{ is White's best but White can hardly hope for an attack after the ensuing exchanges.   16.Qe2  loses material after  16...Bxe5  17.fxe5  Bxg4−+   16.Qc2  drops a pawn after  16...Nxd2  17.Qxd2  Bxg4∓ }
16... Nxe4 17. Nxe4 dxe4
{ With the exchange of two pairs of minor pieces, White's attack has been completely neutralized. Black has the two bishops, can start active play on the queenside with ...a4, and has the option of booting White's knight with ...f6 at a suitable moment. }
