[White "14. Torre (1...Nf6 2...e6)"]
[Black "4. d5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bg5
{ The Torre attack is White's third most popular option on move 3 with 25000+ games. White typically places his light-squared bishop on d3, the queenside knight on d2, and reinforces the d4 pawn with c2-c3. The first player then hopes to push forward with e2-e4 and start a kingside attack, taking advantage of the fact that the bishop on g5 can chop off knight on f6 – the main defender of Black’s king – at an opportune moment.   We’re not going to give White such easy play and will be challenging White’s bishop with ...h6 early on. Another recurring theme is to play ...Qb6, targeting the b2 pawn which White has left undefended.   Also covered is the more flexible  3.c3  giving White the possibility of heading for the Colle or Torre systems.  3...c5  4.Bg5   4.e3  d5  transposes to the Colle system, which is covered inchapter 13.   4.Nbd2  d5  5.e3  also transposes to the Colle system.  4...d5  is the starting point of the 3. c3 variation, where we'll consider White's two most common moves  5.e3  played in 1000+ OTB games,   and  5.Nbd2  which featured in 300+ OTB games. }
3... c5
{ My preferred system vs the Torre, immediately fighting for the center. } 4.
d5
{ is a funky move, which has most notably been played by Dubov in a couple of blitz games with good success @@StartBracket@@scoring 2.5/3@@EndBracket@@. That being said, it is hard to take seriously. }
4... Qa5+ { Breaking the pin with tempo. } 5. Bd2
{ 5.c3  Nxd5  6.e4  Nf6  7.e5  Nd5=  gives White enough compensation for the material deficit but no more. In fact, White can easily end up significantly worse if he isn't precise. }
5... Qd8 6. Bg5
{ Now if a draw makes you World Champion, then, by all means, repeat with 6...Qa5. Instead }
6... exd5 { is also perfectly fine. } 7. Nc3
{ Going after the d5 pawn is White's most popular continuation.   7.e3  can be met with  7...Be7  8.Nc3  d6  9.Nxd5  O-O  10.Bxf6  Bxf6=  followed by ...Nd7-b6 will expel White's knight from d5. }
7... d4 8. Bxf6 { This intermezzo is White's point. } 8... Qxf6 9. Nd5 Qd6
{ This is better than 10...Qc6, which featured in the game 1-0 @@StartBracket@@24@@EndBracket@@ Dubov,D  @@StartBracket@@2702@@EndBracket@@-Anton,T @@StartBracket@@2464@@EndBracket@@ Chess.com INT 2020. There is no reason to take the c6 square away from the knight. }
10. e4 Nc6
{ Next up are ...Be7 and ...O-O with zero issues. Black can then consider ...Qh6 and ...d6 to develop the light-squared bishop. White is a pawn down and thus needs to play accurately to maintain the balance. }
