1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bg5
{ The Torre attack is White's third most popular option on move 3 with 25000+ games. White typically places his light-squared bishop on d3, the queenside knight on d2, and reinforces the d4 pawn with c2-c3. The first player then hopes to push forward with e2-e4 and start a kingside attack, taking advantage of the fact that the bishop on g5 can chop off knight on f6 – the main defender of Black’s king – at an opportune moment.   We’re not going to give White such easy play and will be challenging White’s bishop with …h6 early on. Another recurring theme is to play …Qb6, targeting the b2 pawn which White has left undefended.   Also covered is the more flexible  3.c3  giving White the possibility of heading for the Colle or Torre systems.  3...c5  4.Bg5   4.e3  d5  transposes to the Colle system, which is covered inchapter 13.   4.Nbd2  d5  5.e3  also transposes to the Colle system.  4...d5  is the starting point of the 3. c3 variation, where we'll consider White's two most common moves  5.e3  played in 1000+ OTB games,   and  5.Nbd2  which featured in 300+ OTB games. }
3... c5
{ My preferred system vs the Torre, immediately fighting for the center. } 4.
e4
{ I was surprised to find this move was played in 200+ OTB games, including several GM encounters. }
4... cxd4 5. Qxd4
{ is better than 5. e5 but White needs to be precise to maintain the balance. }
5... Nc6 6. Qe3
{ Worse is  6.Qd3  as it blocks the light-squared bishop. After  6...h6  7.Bh4  Qb6  8.Bxf6  gxf6  9.Qb3  Bc5∓  Black was clearly for choice and went on to win in 0-1 @@StartBracket@@41@@EndBracket@@ Littke,H @@StartBracket@@2283@@EndBracket@@-Johansson,B @@StartBracket@@2329@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2013. }
6... d5
{ is a timely moment to strike in the center, taking advantage of the fact that White cannot push the e-pawn forward. }
7. Nbd2
{ Simply developing, but after the sequence   Note that  7.e5?  is a mistake.  7...Qa5+  breaks the pin with check and after  8.c3  Ng4  9.Qe2  Qc7  10.Bf4  f6−+  the e5 pawn will drop. }
7... dxe4 8. Nxe4 Qa5+ { Breaks the pin with check. } 9. c3 Nd5
{ forces White's queen to move yet again.   Black is obviously doing very well, a sample continuation being  10.Qc1  h6  11.Bd2  Qc7  12.c4  Nf6  13.Nxf6+  gxf6  14.Be2  e5  15.O-O  Be6  followed by ...O-O-O gives Black a great game. He can make use of the open g-file to attack White's king. }
