[White "14. Torre (1...Nf6 2...e6)"]
[Black "3. Bg5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bg5
{ The Torre attack is White's third most popular option on move 3 with 25000+ games. White typically places his light-squared bishop on d3, the queenside knight on d2, and reinforces the d4 pawn with c2-c3. The first player then hopes to push forward with e2-e4 and start a kingside attack, taking advantage of the fact that the bishop on g5 can chop off knight on f6 – the main defender of Black’s king – at an opportune moment.   We’re not going to give White such easy play and will be challenging White’s bishop with …h6 early on. Another recurring theme is to play …Qb6, targeting the b2 pawn which White has left undefended.   Also covered is the more flexible  3.c3  giving White the possibility of heading for the Colle or Torre systems.  3...c5  4.Bg5   4.e3  d5  transposes to the Colle system, which is covered inchapter 13.   4.Nbd2  d5  5.e3  also transposes to the Colle system.  4...d5  is the starting point of the 3. c3 variation, where we'll consider White's two most common moves  5.e3  played in 1000+ OTB games,   and  5.Nbd2  which featured in 300+ OTB games. }
3... c5
{ My preferred system vs the Torre, immediately fighting for the center. } 4.
e3
{ is White's most popular move.   4.c3  d5  is covered via the 3. c3 move order. }
4... h6
{ This natural move was not considered in the Chessable course Calm & Collected: 1.d4 by FM Marko Makaj. }
5. Bxf6
{ 5.Bh4  d5  6.c3  Nbd7  is covered via the 3. c3 move order.   5.Bf4  d5  is a completely harmless London where Black got in ...h6 move for free. If White wanted to play like this, he should have gone Bf4 on move 3. }
5... Qxf6 { Thanks for the bishop pair! } 6. Nbd2
{ White can also start with  6.Bd3  or  6.c3  These moves will transpose to lines covered throughout this chapter as White cannot do without Nbd2.   6.Nc3  makes little sense. It can only be connected with the idea of playing e4, an option Black can immediately eliminate with  6...cxd4  7.exd4  d5  when the knight is simply misplaced on c3. }
6... cxd4
{ is simple and effective. Black clarifies the tension, entering a Carlsbad structure where only he can even be better. This is because White will find it very hard to take control of the e5 square and has no chance of mounting an attack on Black's king. }
7. exd4 Nc6 { Developing with a tempo on the d4 pawn. } 8. c3
{ 8.Nc4?!  makes little sense as  8...d5  kicks it back with tempo. After  9.Ne3  Bd6  12.Be2  Black can play it safe with  12...O-O=  or try to seize the initiative with  12...g5⭡ }
8... d5 { Next up is ...Bd6 and ...O-O with a very comfortable position. } 9.
Bb5
{ has been played a handful of times but the bishop isn't doing much here. }
9... Bd6 10. O-O O-O 11. Re1 Bd7
{ We're ready to kick White's bishop back with ...a6 and then follow up with ...b5-b4 - the typical minority attack in the Carlsbad structure. Black is very comfortable. }
*

