1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Bg5
{ The Torre attack is White's third most popular option on move 3 with 25000+ games. White typically places his light-squared bishop on d3, the queenside knight on d2, and reinforces the d4 pawn with c2-c3. The first player then hopes to push forward with e2-e4 and start a kingside attack, taking advantage of the fact that the bishop on g5 can chop off knight on f6 – the main defender of Black’s king – at an opportune moment.   We’re not going to give White such easy play and will be challenging White’s bishop with …h6 early on. Another recurring theme is to play …Qb6, targeting the b2 pawn which White has left undefended.   Also covered is the more flexible  3.c3  giving White the possibility of heading for the Colle or Torre systems.  3...c5  4.Bg5   4.e3  d5  transposes to the Colle system, which is covered inchapter 13.   4.Nbd2  d5  5.e3  also transposes to the Colle system.  4...d5  is the starting point of the 3. c3 variation, where we'll consider White's two most common moves  5.e3  played in 1000+ OTB games,   and  5.Nbd2  which featured in 300+ OTB games. }
3... c5
{ My preferred system vs the Torre, immediately fighting for the center. } 4.
e3 { 4.c3  d5  is covered via the 3. c3 move order. } 4... h6
{ Simple and effective. This move was not considered by FM Marko Makaj in his Chessable course 'Calm & Collected: 1.d4'. }
5. Bxf6 { 5.Bh4  d5  6.c3  Nbd7  is covered via the 3. c3 move order. } 5...
Qxf6 { Thanks for the bishop pair! } 6. Nbd2 cxd4 7. exd4 Nc6 8. c3 d5
{ Next up is ...Bd6 and ...O-O with a very comfortable position. } 9. Bd3
{ is a more sensible square for the bishop. } 9... Bd6
{ Simply developing. Black intends to castle and decide on a plan from there. }
10. Qe2 { 10.O-O  O-O  11.Qe2  transposes to the text. } 10... O-O 11. O-O
{ Going to the other side of the board with  11.O-O-O  walks into an attack. After  11...Bd7  12.Kb1  a5∓  Black is dictating the play. }
11... Re8 { Preparing the ...e5 break, which will liberate our c8 bishop. } 12.
Rae1 e5
{ solves all of Black's problems. The immediate threat is ...e4, which forces White to play }
13. Nxe5
{ The alternative recapture  13.dxe5  has little independent value.  13.Nxe5  Nxe5  transposes to thenext trainable line. }
13... Nxe5 14. f4
{ may look clever, trying to take advantage of the loose rook on e8. However, it doesn't work. }
14... Nxd3 15. Qxe8+ Kh7 { The e1-rook is now under attack, and after } 16. Re3
Nxf4
{ Black has two minor pieces for a rook, which is a decisive material advantage.   Note that  17.g3  can be met with  17...Qg6  stepping out of the pin along the f-file and pinning White's pawn.  18.Kh1  Qc2−+  gives Black a decisive advantage. }
