1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c3
{ is more flexible, giving White the possibility of heading for the Colle or Torre systems. }
3... c5 { Staying consistent with our approach vs 3. Bg5. } 4. Bg5
{ 4.e3  d5  transposes to the Colle system, which is covered in chapter 13.   4.Nbd2  d5  5.e3  also transposes to the Colle system. }
4... d5
{ White isn't fighting for the center but that doesn't mean we should follow suit. White has two main approaches at this point: 5. Nbd2 or 5. e3. }
5. Nbd2 { instead of 5. e3 is usually connected with the idea of going e4. }
5... h6 { Putting the question to the bishop. } 6. Bxf6
{ White trades the bishop, intending to break with e4.   6.Bh4  Nbd7  7.e3  is covered via the 5. e3 move order. }
6... Qxf6 7. e4
{ The more passive  7.e3  is obviously harmless. After  7...Nc6  8.Bd3  cxd4  9.exd4  Bd6  10.O-O  Black can either  10...O-O=  with a good game or go for the more ambitious  10...g5!? }
7... cxd4 8. exd5
{ 8.Nxd4  Bc5=  gives Black easy play.   8.e5  leads to a very favorable version of the French for Black. After  8...Qd8  9.cxd4  Nc6⩱  Black is already better. Black has the bishop pair, the d4 pawn is a big target and White's knight should be on c3 instead of d2. }
8... exd5
{ 8...dxc3?!  runs into  9.Ne4  Qf4  10.Nxc3⩲  when White has decent chances for a small advantage. }
9. Bb5+ { ...but we can easily block with } 9... Nc6 10. Nxd4 Bd7 11. O-O Be7
{ Blocking the e-file and clearing the way for ...O-O. } 12. N2f3
{ Supporting the knight on d4, essentially making White's blockade against the IQP stronger. }
12... O-O
{ The two bishops more than compensate for the isolated pawn on d5. Next up is ...Bd6 followed by ...Rfe8 and ...Rad8, centralizing the rooks. }
