11... Qxf6 { And not  12...Nxf6?  because of  13.e5+− } 12. cxd4 dxe4
{ e5 was a threat, so liquidating in the center makes sense. } 13. Bxe4
{ Worse is  13.Nxe4  Qe7  14.Nxd6  Qxd6⩱  when White has no compensation for the isolated d-pawn. }
13... Rb8
{ We're ready to exchange off the light-squared bishops with ...Bb7 next. } 14.
Nc4 Qe7
{ Black is not afraid of exchanging the bishop as the more minor pieces are exchanged, the more exposed the isolani becomes. }
15. Nxd6 Qxd6 16. Rc1
{ White is aiming to infiltrate on the c-file, but after } 16... Bb7
{ White had little to show for the isolated d-pawn. Black went on to win in 0-1 @@StartBracket@@68@@EndBracket@@ Jones, G @@StartBracket@@2665@@EndBracket@@-Meier,G @@StartBracket@@2646@@EndBracket@@ Tromsoe 2014. This game is annotated in themodel games chapter. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14. Torre (1...Nf6 2...e6)"]
[Black "3. c3 #10"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c3
{ is more flexible, giving White the possibility of heading for the Colle or Torre systems. }
3... c5 { Staying consistent with our approach vs 3. Bg5. } 4. Bg5 d5
{ White isn't fighting for the center but that doesn't mean we should follow suit. White has two main approaches at this point: 5. Nbd2 or 5. e3. }
5. e3 h6 { Asking the bishop to define its position. } 6. Bh4
{ is ten times as popular as the alternatives. } 6... Nbd7
{ Our plan is to complete development with ...Bd6 and ...O-O. We can then fianchetto the light-squared bishop with ...b6 and ...Bb7. }
7. Nbd2 Bd6 8. Bd3 O-O 9. O-O b6
{ Preparing to fianchetto the light-squared bishop. White can also prepare the e4 break with }
10. Re1
{ with the idea e4 occurred in the game 1-0 @@StartBracket@@92@@EndBracket@@ Fedoseev, V @@StartBracket@@2661@@EndBracket@@ -Leko,P @@StartBracket@@2723@@EndBracket@@ Moscow 2014. Here, I would like to propose the novel }
10... c4 11. Bb1
{ White wants to stay on the b1-h7 diagonal in hopes of a checkmate on h7 one day. However, this is nothing but a pipe dream. }
11... Qc7
{ Stepping out of the pin. We're ready to start active play on the queenside with ...b5. }
12. e4
{ White's usual pawn break. We're very well equipped to deal with this. } 12...
Nxe4 13. Nxe4 dxe4 14. Bxe4 { The rook is under fire, but after } 14... Rb8
{ with the idea of marching the b-pawn down the board gives Black a great game. There is no need to worry about White creating a battery with Bb1 and Qc2, as Black can easily parry this with ...Re8 and ...Nf8 or ...f7-f5. }
