[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "15. 3.g3 system (1...Nf6 2...e6)"]
[Black "4. Bg2 6. Bg5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3
{ The g3 system, which was amongst others recommended by IM Cristof Sielecki in the book and Chessable course Keep it Simple: 1.d4.  White delays  (and sometimes entirely foregoes)  c2-c4, preferring to first develop the kingside and keep options open. Several Catalan players have tried this approach, hoping to avoid certain variations and hoping to later transpose into more favorable versions of the Catalan.  However, we can immediately put an end to this possibility with }
3... b5
{ which is a very interesting response, taking advantage of the fact that White did not play c4. We completely rule out c4 for the time being and prepare to quickly fianchetto our light-squared bishop, fully neutralizing White's Catalan bishop.   3...d5  4.c4  transposes to the Catalan.   4.Bg2  Be7  5.c4  allows another transposition to the mainline Catalan.   Bb7  Queen's Indian Defense players can instead choose  3...b6  4.Bg2  Bb7  5.c4=  with direct transposition to the mainline Bb7 QID.   5.O-O  Be7  6.c4=  is another transposition to the Bb7 QID. }
4. Bg2
{ is almost invariably played. I'd also like to say a few words about some rare alternatives.   4.e4?!  is dubious as after  4...Nxe4  5.Bxb5  White exchanged a central pawn for a flank pawn, which is clearly in Black's favor.  5...Be7⩱  is already slightly better for Black.   4.Nc3  walks straight into  4...b4=   4.c3  is completely harmless. After  4...Bb7  5.Bg2  Be7  6.O-O  c5=  Black has comfortably equalized.   4.e3  also makes little sense. White voluntarily blocks his dark-squared bishop and makes his structure rigid. After  4...a6  5.Bg2  Bb7  6.O-O  Be7  7.b3  O-O  8.Bb2  d5=  Black has a great game with ...Nbd7 and ...c5 coming next. }
4... Bb7 5. O-O { 5.Bg5  Be7  6.O-O=  transposes to 5. O-O Be7 6. Bg5. } 5...
c5
{ White has tried a bunch of moves in this position: 6. c3, 6. a4, 6. Na3 and 6. Bg5 in order of decreasing popularity, none of which pose Black any real problems. }
6. Bg5
{ developing the bishop to its most active position. This is White's fourth most popular continuation.   The alternative bishop development  6.Bf4  can be met with  6...cxd4  7.Nxd4  Bxg2  8.Kxg2  Qb6=  when Black has no issues whatsoever. }
6... cxd4
{ Simple and effective. This is a good moment to capture on d4 as it leads to the exchange of the light-squared bishops. }
7. Nxd4
{ 7.Qxd4  doesn't make much sense as the queen will be exposed to ...Nc6. For example  7...Be7  8.Nc3  h6  9.Bf4  a6  10.Rfd1  Nc6⩱  gains a tempo on the queen and gives Black the upper hand. }
7... Bxg2 8. Kxg2
{ when Black can ignore the attack on the b5 pawn and instead prioritze development with }
8... Be7 { the point being that after } 9. Nxb5 Qb6 10. N1c3
{ Alternatively  10.N1a3  can be met with  10...a6  when  11.Bxf6  gxf6  12.Nd4  Qxb2  13.Nc4  This was White's idea with N1a3 but is nothing to worry about.  13...Qb7  14.Kg1  Qc7=  Black is in great shape with ...d5 and ...Nd7 coming next. }
10... a6 11. Nd4
{ 11.Bxf6  compromises Black's pawn structure but gives up the bishop. After  11...gxf6  12.Nd4  Qxb2  13.Qd3  Qb7=  Black is doing very well with ...Nc6 and ...O-O up next. }
11... Qxb2
{ recoups the pawn. The position is unbalanced enough to play for a win. } *

