6. c3 { Reinforcing the d4 pawn is White's most popular continuation. } 6...
Be7 7. Bg5
{ Alternatives are given as clickables since they lead to similar play as the previous variations.   7.a4  can once again be bypassed with  7...b4  8.dxc5  Bxc5  9.cxb4  Bxb4  10.Qb3  Na6=  Black had no issues in ½-½ @@StartBracket@@41@@EndBracket@@ Hacche,D @@StartBracket@@2131@@EndBracket@@ -Smerdon,D @@StartBracket@@2502@@EndBracket@@ Canberra 2010. He can comfortably complete development with ...O-O and ...Qe7.   If  7.Qd3  Black can simply defend the pawn with  7...a6  8.Nbd2  cxd4  9.cxd4  Nc6  10.a3  O-O  11.Nb3  Na5=  Black was in great shape in the blitz game ½-½ @@StartBracket@@91@@EndBracket@@ Jakovenko,D @@StartBracket@@2713@@EndBracket@@-Pridorozhni,A  @@StartBracket@@2512@@EndBracket@@ Khanty-Mansiysk 2013. Next on the agenda are ...Qb6 and ...Rac8. }
7... cxd4 8. Nxd4
{ Centralizes the knight at the expense of exchanging the light-squared bishops. }
8... Bxg2 9. Kxg2 Qb6
{ Covers the b5 pawn, intending to follow up with ...O-O. The queen can always drop back to b7 in the future and take up the mantle of the light-squared bishop.   A sample continuation is  9...Qb6  10.Qd3  Qb7+  11.f3  a6  12.e4  h6  13.Be3  d6  14.Nd2  Nbd7  15.Bf2  O-O=  followed by ...Nb6 and ...Rfc8 gives Black an excellent game. }
