[Black "4. Bg2 6. c3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3
{ The g3 system, which was amongst others recommended by IM Cristof Sielecki in the book and Chessable course Keep it Simple: 1.d4.  White delays  (and sometimes entirely foregoes)  c2-c4, preferring to first develop the kingside and keep options open. Several Catalan players have tried this approach, hoping to avoid certain variations and hoping to later transpose into more favorable versions of the Catalan.  However, we can immediately put an end to this possibility with }
3... b5
{ which is a very interesting response, taking advantage of the fact that White did not play c4. We completely rule out c4 for the time being and prepare to quickly fianchetto our light-squared bishop, fully neutralizing White's Catalan bishop.   3...d5  4.c4  transposes to the Catalan.   4.Bg2  Be7  5.c4  allows another transposition to the mainline Catalan.   Bb7  Queen's Indian Defense players can instead choose  3...b6  4.Bg2  Bb7  5.c4=  with direct transposition to the mainline Bb7 QID.   5.O-O  Be7  6.c4=  is another transposition to the Bb7 QID. }
4. Bg2
{ is almost invariably played. I'd also like to say a few words about some rare alternatives.   4.e4?!  is dubious as after  4...Nxe4  5.Bxb5  White exchanged a central pawn for a flank pawn, which is clearly in Black's favor.  5...Be7⩱  is already slightly better for Black.   4.Nc3  walks straight into  4...b4=   4.c3  is completely harmless. After  4...Bb7  5.Bg2  Be7  6.O-O  c5=  Black has comfortably equalized.   4.e3  also makes little sense. White voluntarily blocks his dark-squared bishop and makes his structure rigid. After  4...a6  5.Bg2  Bb7  6.O-O  Be7  7.b3  O-O  8.Bb2  d5=  Black has a great game with ...Nbd7 and ...c5 coming next. }
4... Bb7 5. O-O { 5.Bg5  Be7  6.O-O=  transposes to 5. O-O Be7 6. Bg5. } 5...
c5
{ White has tried a bunch of moves in this position: 6. c3, 6. a4, 6. Na3 and 6. Bg5 in order of decreasing popularity, none of which pose Black any real problems. }
6. c3 { Reinforcing the d4 pawn is White's most popular continuation. } 6...
Be7 7. Bg5
{ Alternatives are given as clickables since they lead to similar play as the previous variations.   7.a4  can once again be bypassed with  7...b4  8.dxc5  Bxc5  9.cxb4  Bxb4  10.Qb3  Na6=  Black had no issues in ½-½ @@StartBracket@@41@@EndBracket@@ Hacche,D @@StartBracket@@2131@@EndBracket@@ -Smerdon,D @@StartBracket@@2502@@EndBracket@@ Canberra 2010. He can comfortablu. complete development with ...O-O and ...Qe7.  If   7.Qd3  Black can simply defend the pawn with  7...a6  8.Nbd2  cxd4  9.cxd4  Nc6  10.a3  O-O  11.Nb3  Na5=  Black was in great shape in the blitz game ½-½ @@StartBracket@@91@@EndBracket@@ Jakovenko,D @@StartBracket@@2713@@EndBracket@@-Pridorozhni,A  @@StartBracket@@2512@@EndBracket@@ Khanty-Mansiysk 2013. Next on the agenda are ...Qb6 and ...Rac8. }
7... cxd4 { The alternative recapture } 8. cxd4
{ fails to pose any challenges after } 8... a6
{ Prophylactically defending the b5-pawn. } 9. Qd3 d6
{ We have entered a hedgehog structure, common to the Nimzo and QID.   9...O-O  is also possible but allows  10.Bxf6  Bxf6  11.Ng5  which leads to a position with opposite-colored bishops after  11...Bxg5  12.Bxb7  Ra7  13.Bg2  d5=  While Black is completely fine, it is hard to play for a win from this position. As such, I prefer 9...d6 keeping more life in the position. }
10. a4 { Trying to break down Black's extended pawns on the queenside. } 10...
bxa4
{ opens up the b-file, which will allow us to attack White's isolated b-pawn in the future. Granted it also leaves us with an isolated pawn on a6, but this is firmly defended by our light-squared bishop. }
11. Nc3
{ Immediately recapturing the pawn with  11.Rxa4  can be met with  11...Nbd7  12.Nc3  O-O=  with a comfortable game. Next up are ...Nb6 and ...Rc8. }
11... Nbd7
{ followed by ...O-O and ...h6 is fully equal and with ample room to fight for the full point.   A sample continuation is  12.e4  O-O  13.Rxa4  h6  14.Bf4  d5  15.e5  Ne4  16.Rfa1  Nxc3  17.bxc3  Qc7=  with a level game. Next up are ...Rfc8 and ...a5. }
