1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Nbd2 { prepares the e4 break. } 3... d5
{ puts an end to any ideas of e2-e4. } 4. c4 { is strongly met by } 4... c5
{ with an excellent version of the Tarrasch. White's knight would much rather be on c3. }
5. e3
{ Alternatively  5.cxd5  can be met with  5...cxd4!?  6.Nxd4  Qxd5  7.e3  Be7=  followed by ...O-O was completely fine in ½-½ @@StartBracket@@30@@EndBracket@@ Madebrink, L @@StartBracket@@2192@@EndBracket@@-Jepson,C @@StartBracket@@2415@@EndBracket@@ Tylosand 2018. }
5... cxd4 6. Nxd4 Be7 7. Be2
{ If  7.cxd5  then  7...Qxd5  8.Bb5+  Bd7  9.Bxd7+  Nbxd7  10.O-O  O-O⩱  is slightly better for Black.   7.b3  runs into  7...e5!!  8.N4f3  d4  9.exd4   9.Nxe5  dxe3  10.fxe3  O-O∓  is obviously better for Black.  9...e4  10.Ng1  Qxd4−+  gives Black a decisive advantage. }
7... e5 { gains space in the center and knocks White's knight back. } 8. N4f3
Nc6 9. O-O O-O
{ Black is clearly for choice. He has more space, full control over the center and White's bishop on c1 is completely restricted. }
