1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Nc3 { Just like 3. Nbd2, White wants to play e4 next. }
3... d5 { Our usual reaction when White places a knight on c3. } 4. Bg5
{ continuing in Veresov fashion is also nothing special. } 4... Nbd7
{ Now White has two options: 5. e3 or 5. e4. } 5. e4 { is easily dealt with }
5... h6 { which forces White to part with the dark-squared bishop. } 6. Bxf6
{ Retreating with  6.Bh4?  drops a pawn after  6...g5  7.Bg3  Nxe4∓ } 6... Nxf6
7. e5 Nd7 8. Bd3 c5
{ is a dream French. White has no way of creating play on the kingside, while Black can easily expand on the queenside with ... a6 and ...b5. }
