1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. Nc3 { Just like 3. Nbd2, White wants to play e4 next. }
3... d5 { Our usual reaction when White places a knight on c3. } 4. Bg5
{ continuing in Veresov fashion is also nothing special. } 4... Nbd7
{ Now White has two options: 5. e3 or 5. e4. } 5. e4 { is easily dealt with }
5... h6 { which forces White to part with the dark-squared bishop. } 6. Bxf6
{ Retreating with   6.Bh4?  drops a pawn after  6...g5  7.Bg3  Nxe4∓ } 6...
Nxf6 7. Bd3 Bb4
{ Black is in great shape and can easily solve the problem of his light-squared bishop as the following sample line shows }
8. Qe2
{ 8.e5?  runs into  8...Ne4  when  9.Bxe4  dxe4  10.Ng1  Qg5∓  is obviously great for Black. }
8... dxe4 9. Bxe4 Nxe4 10. Qxe4 Qd5 11. Qxd5 Bxc3+
{ This zwischenzug makes it all work. } 12. bxc3 exd5
{ If anyone's better here, it's Black. Our bishop is slightly stronger than White's knight and White's pawn structure is compromised. It is true that in exchange for the latter White has access to the b-file. }
