1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. e3
{ The Colle system, also known as the Colle-Koltanowski system, is named after the Belgian masters Edgard Colle and George Koltanowski.    Characterized by the moves 2. Nf3 and 3. e3, White usually develops his light-squared bishop to d3, the queenside knight to d2, and tries to engineer the pawn break e3-e4. White typically reinforces the d4 pawn with c2-c3 in response to …c5, setting up a triangle or pyramidal pawn structure with pawns on f2, e3, d4, c3, and b2.    Nowadays, this variation is considered innocuous as it does not put any pressure on the center and restricts White’s dark-squared bishop. It is a popular system at the club level mainly because it can be learned very quickly and is of very low maintenance.   It is particularly ineffective against the fianchetto with 2...g6 as White lacks control over the key e5 square and the second player can quickly undermine White's center with the ...c5 break. }
3... Bg7 4. Be2 c5
{ I like meeting the Colle setup with a quick ...c5, which avoids any unfavorable transpositions. }
5. O-O O-O 6. c4 cxd4 7. Nxd4 { The knight recapture is harmless. } 7... Nc6 8.
Nc3 d5
{ fighting for the center. There's only one continuation you should remember }
9. cxd5 Nxd5 10. Nxd5 Qxd5 11. Bf3
{ It may seem like we're in trouble on c6, but that's not actually the case. }
11... Qc5 12. Nxc6 bxc6 13. Qa4 Bf5
{ is Black's best move, which was only played once. It's quite a bit stronger than 13...Rb8 which featured in more than 75 OTB games. }
14. Bxc6 Bc2
{ is the point behind 13...Bf5. We force the queens off the board and following... }
15. Qb5 Qxb5 16. Bxb5 a6 17. Be2 Rfd8
{ ... White has serious issues bringing out his pieces. Despite being a pawn down, the engines prefer Black's position with ...a5 and ...Rac8/b8 coming next. }
