1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Bg5
{ The Torre attack, characterized by the early development of the bishop to g5.   White typically places his light-squared bishop on e2 or d3, the queenside knight on d2, and reinforces the d4 pawn with c2-c3. The first player then hopes to push forward with e2-e4 and start a kingside attack, taking advantage of the fact that the bishop on g5 can chop off knight on f6 – the main defender of Black’s king – at an opportune moment.  Out of all the Torre's in this course, this is arguably the best one. Notwithstanding, Black is doing very well in all the variations.   Also covered is  3.c3  Bg7  4.Nbd2  aiming for a quick e4.   4.Bf4  transposes to theLondon system.   4.Bg5  transposes to the3. Bg5 variation.  4...d5  puts an end to ...e4. White is relegated to a Colle setup, which is analyzed in4 trainable lines. }
3... Bg7 4. Nbd2
{ White has different move orders, most of which will transpose to the mainline.   4.e3  d5  5.Be2   5.c3  will also transpose to the mainline as White can't do without Nbd2.   5.Nbd2  is a direct transposition to the mainline after 4. Nbd2 d5 5. e3.  5...O-O  6.Nbd2  transposes to3. Bg5 Bg7 4. Nbd2 O-O 5. e3 d5 6. Be2   Starting with  4.c3  also has no independent value.  4...O-O  5.Nbd2  transpoes to4. Nbd2 O-O 5. c3.   5.e3  d5  6.Nbd2  transposes to 4. Nbd2 O-O 5. c3 d5 6. e3.   4.Nc3  d5  transposes to the Barry attack, which is covered via the 2. Nf3 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Bg5 d5 move order inchapter 19. }
4... O-O { Here we'll consider White's three most common moves, namely } 5. c3
{ with 2600+ OTB games.   5.e4  played in 2300+ OTB games.   5.e3  which featured in 1300+ OTB games. }
