1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Bg5
{ The Torre attack, characterized by the early development of the bishop to g5.   White typically places his light-squared bishop on d3, the queenside knight on d2, and reinforces the d4 pawn with c2-c3. The first player then hopes to push forward with e2-e4 and start a kingside attack, taking advantage of the fact that the bishop on g5 can chop off knight on f6 – the main defender of Black’s king – at an opportune moment.  Out of all the Torre's in this course, this is arguably the best one. Notwithstanding, Black is doing very well in all the variations.   Also covered is  3.c3  Bg7  4.Nbd2  aiming for a quick e4.   4.Bf4  transposes to theLondon system.   4.Bg5  transposes to the3. Bg5 variation.  4...d5  puts an end to ...e4. White is relegated to a Colle setup, which is analyzed in4 trainable lines. }
3... Bg7 4. Nbd2 O-O
{ There is no need to prevent e4 with .. .d5 since it's not a good option for White. }
5. c3 d5
{ is my preferred approach. The alternative setup with 5...d6 is also fully playable, but why not take up more space in the center? }
6. e3 Nbd7
{ It's time to discuss our plan. We have two pawn breaks available here, namely ...c5 and ...e5. Given that White's bishop is on g5 instead of f4, the ...e5 break is easy to achieve and more challenging for White to meet. We can prepare it with ...Re8.   Here  6...Be6  is not as strong as in the previous line. This because in this line White has already played c3, giving him the extra option of  7.Qb3  hitting the b7 pawn. After  7...Qc8  8.Be2  c5  9.h3  c4  10.Qa3  Nc6  11.b3  White has good play against our pawns. Black is still ok but the text is more ambitious. }
7. Bd3
{ intending to go O-O and then break with e3-e4. However, we'll get our ...e5 break in first. }
7... Re8 8. O-O e5 { gives Black a good game. A sample continuation is } 9.
dxe5 Nxe5 10. Nxe5 Rxe5 { gains a tempo on White's dark-squared bishop. } 11.
Bf4 { 11.Nf3  Re8  12.h3  c6  13.Qc2  Qb6=  gives Black a pleasant game. }
11... Re8 12. h3 c5 { There's no reason not to grab more space in the center. }
13. Nf3 b6 14. Qc2 Bb7
{ followed by ...Qe7 and ...Rad8. Black was very comfortable in ½-½ @@StartBracket@@101@@EndBracket@@ Radjabov,T @@StartBracket@@2713@@EndBracket@@-Giri,A @@StartBracket@@2734@@EndBracket@@ Beijing 2013. }
