6. e3 Nbd7
{ It's time to discuss our plan. We have two pawn breaks available here, namely ...c5 and . .. e5. Given that White's bishop is on g5 instead of f4, the ...e5 break is easy to achieve and more challenging for White to meet. We can prepare it with ... Re8. }
7. Be2 { The most common bishop development. } 7... Re8 8. O-O e5
{ Once we get this break in, we have comfortably equalized. It's possible to stop here but I think it's worth continuing for a few more moves to understand Black's typical middlegame plans. }
9. Nb3
{ was played a couple of times by Tony Miles. White vacates the d2 square so as to be able to drop the f3 knight to d2 in case of ...e4. }
9... a5
{ A rare but very logical move, intending to knock back White's knight with ...a4. }
10. a4 exd4
{ is a novel and timely capture. Black resolves the tension in the center intending to plant a knight on e4, which White surrendered control of with Nb3. }
11. exd4 h6 12. Bh4 g5 { breaks the pin. Next up is ...Ne4. } 13. Bg3 Ne4
{ with an excellent position. White's knight on b3 isn't doing anything while Black is ready to expand on the kingside with ...f5-f4. }
