1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Bg5
{ The Torre attack, characterized by the early development of the bishop to g5.   White typically places his light-squared bishop on d3, the queenside knight on d2, and reinforces the d4 pawn with c2-c3. The first player then hopes to push forward with e2-e4 and start a kingside attack, taking advantage of the fact that the bishop on g5 can chop off knight on f6 – the main defender of Black’s king – at an opportune moment.  Out of all the Torre's in this course, this is arguably the best one. Notwithstanding, Black is doing very well in all the variations.   Also covered is  3.c3  Bg7  4.Nbd2  aiming for a quick e4.   4.Bf4  transposes to theLondon system.   4.Bg5  transposes to the3. Bg5 variation.  4...d5  puts an end to ...e4. White is relegated to a Colle setup, which is analyzed in4 trainable lines. }
3... Bg7 4. Nbd2 O-O
{ There is no need to prevent e4 with ...d5 since it's not a good option for White. }
5. c3 d5
{ is my preferred approach. The alternative setup with 5...d6 is also fully playable, but why not take up more space in the center? }
6. e3 Nbd7
{ It's time to discuss our plan. We have two pawn breaks available here, namely ...c5 and . .. e5. Given that White's bishop is on g5 instead of f4, the ...e5 break is easy to achieve and more challenging for White to meet. We can prepare it with ... Re8. }
7. Be2 { The most common bishop development. } 7... Re8 8. O-O e5
{ Once we get this break in, we have comfortably equalized. It's possible to stop here but I think it's worth continuing for a few more moves to understand Black's typical middlegame plans. }
9. Bh4
{ is an interesting Kramnik move, intending to drop the bishop back to g3 and ask Black to clarify the tension in the center. }
9... c6
{ is always a useful move. It does not commit the structure prematurely, retaining maximum flexibility.   9...e4  is possible but gives White a clear plan with  10.Ne1  Nf8  11.c4  c6  12.Nc2=  followed by b4-b5. Although Black is still fine, I'd rather not give White such a straightforward plan. }
10. Bg3
{ Asks Black to clarify the tension in the center, which we gladly do with }
10... e4 { gaining space. } 11. Ne5
{ 11.Ne1  is very passive.  11...Nb6  12.a4  Be6  ensures White won't get c4 in good conditions.  13.a5  does not help White as  13...Nc8=  Black can reroute the knight ...Ne7-f5. }
11... Nxe5 12. Bxe5
{ This position occurred in the high-profile game ½-½ @@StartBracket@@73@@EndBracket@@ Kramnik,V  @@StartBracket@@2811@@EndBracket@@-Radjabov,T @@StartBracket@@2710@@EndBracket@@ Shamkir 2017, where Radjabov played ...Bf8 with the idea ...Bd6 to exchange the dark-squared bishops. The NNUE engines prefer the novel and more direct }
12... Nd7
{ kicking White's bishop from e5 and proposing an exchange of dark-squared bishops, which is in Black's favor since Black's bishop on g7 is less active. This move was not considered by GM Nikola Sedlak in the book 'The Modernized London System Vol. 2', where he advocated the Torre vs 1...Nf6 2...g6. }
13. Bg3
{ 13.Bxg7  is inferior.  13...Kxg7  14.a4  Qg5→  followed by ... Nf6 when White has to be careful not to get mated on the kingside. }
13... Nf8 14. c4 Ne6
{ Black is very comfortable and has ideas of expanding on the kingside with ...f5-f4 . White, on the other hand, will have a very hard time creating anything on the queenside. }
