1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Bg5
{ The Torre attack, characterized by the early development of the bishop to g5.   White typically places his light-squared bishop on d3, the queenside knight on d2, and reinforces the d4 pawn with c2-c3. The first player then hopes to push forward with e2-e4 and start a kingside attack, taking advantage of the fact that the bishop on g5 can chop off knight on f6 – the main defender of Black’s king – at an opportune moment.  Out of all the Torre's in this course, this is arguably the best one. Notwithstanding, Black is doing very well in all the variations.   Also covered is  3.c3  Bg7  4.Nbd2  aiming for a quick e4.   4.Bf4  transposes to theLondon system.   4.Bg5  transposes to the3. Bg5 variation.  4...d5  puts an end to ...e4. White is relegated to a Colle setup, which is analyzed in4 trainable lines. }
3... Bg7 4. Nbd2 O-O
{ There is no need to prevent e4 with .. .d5 since it's not a good option for White. }
5. c3 d5
{ is my preferred approach. The alternative setup with 5...d6 is also fully playable, but why not take up more space in the center? }
6. e3 Nbd7
{ It's time to discuss our plan. We have two pawn breaks available here, namely ...c5 and ...e5. Given that White's bishop is on g5 instead of f4, the ...e5 break is easy to achieve and more challenging for White to meet. We can prepare it with ...Re8. }
7. Be2 { The most common bishop development. } 7... Re8 8. O-O e5
{ Once we get this break in, we have comfortably equalized. It's possible to stop here but I think it's worth continuing for a few more moves to understand Black's typical middlegame plans. }
9. b4
{ A very interesting plan which has been played by several 2600+ GMs. The center is stable so White wants to expand on the queenside. Here I quite like }
9... c6
{ discouraging b5. The idea is that if White later goes b5, we can close the center with ...e4 and then bypass the b-pawn with .... c6-c5 @@StartBracket@@this way not allowing en passant@@EndBracket@@, gaining a lot of space. We can also undermine White's b4 pawn with ...a5 next. }
10. Nb3 h6 11. Bxf6 { gives away the bishop pair. After } 11... Qxf6 12. b5 Qd6
13. bxc6 bxc6
{ Black had no issues and even went on to win in 0-1 @@StartBracket@@33@@EndBracket@@ Grachev,B @@StartBracket@@2684@@EndBracket@@ -Navara,D @@StartBracket@@2692@@EndBracket@@ Sibenik 2009. Black can expand on the queenside with ...a5-a4 or in the center with ...e4 next. }
*

