[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18. Torre (1...Nf6 2...g6)"]
[Black "3. c3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. c3 Bg7 4. Nbd2
{ aiming for a quick e4.   4.Bf4  transposes to the London system.   4.Bg5  transposes to the 3. Bg5 variations. }
4... d5
{ puts an end to ...e4. White is relegated to a Colle setup, which is completely harmless. }
5. e3
{ The Colle/Triangle system, which is ever popular at the club level. White builds a solid triangle pawn formation and avoids any confrontations in the center. Such an approach is hardly ambitious. }
5... O-O
{ White can now develop his light-squared bishop to e2 or d3, which makes little difference to us. All you really need to know is to break in the center with ...c5, place the knight on d7 and fianchetto the light-squared bishop. }
6. Bd3 c5 7. O-O Qc7
{ Black can also play the immediate ...Nbd7, but starting with ...Qc7 is more nuanced. The point is that if White goes for a Stonewall setup with Ne5 and f4, our knight is better placed on c6. }
8. Qe2 Nbd7 { White is able to break with } 9. e4
{ but it doesn't bring him anything of value. } 9... dxe4 10. Nxe4 cxd4 11.
Nxd4
{ The alternative recapture  11.cxd4  leaves White with an isolated pawn on d4. After  11...Nxe4  12.Qxe4  Nf6  13.Qh4  Bg4⩱  Black is slightly better. }
11... a6 { followed by ...b5 and ...Bb7 gives Black a great game. } *

