1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Nc3 d5
{ is our default reaction when White develops his knight to c3, taking control over the e4 square and thus preventing e2-e4. }
4. Bg5
{ Writing this from the other side of the pond, I'm pretty clueless when it comes to British slang but detailed analysis shows that White is under serious pressure after }
4... Ne4
{ which is 5 times less popular than 4...Bg7 but much stronger. While 4...Bg7 comfortably equalizes, 4...Ne4 gives Black a significant advantage @@StartBracket@@or even an outright winning position@@EndBracket@@ in every single line.   We will consider White's 5 most popular continuations, namely  5.Bf4  ,  5.Nxe4  ,  5.Bh4  ,  5.e3  , and  5.h4 }
5. h4
{ is the 5th most popular continuation and not a particularly good one. White keeps his bishop on g5 but it's not doing anything there. }
5... Bg7 6. e3 c5
{ is a typical pawn break, gaining space in the center and pressuring the d4 pawn. }
7. Bb5+
{ can simply be blocked with   7.Nxe4?!  has never been played OTB and for good reason. After  7...dxe4  White's pieces are first forced back  8.Nd2  h6  9.Bf4  and now  9...cxd4  10.exd4  Qxd4∓  nets Black a pawn. }
7... Nc6 8. Ne5
{ was seen in all three games that reached this position. White can however hardly exploit the pin on the knight on c6 as }
8... Nxc3
{ is a strong counterblow, hitting White's queen and crippling his pawns. } 9.
bxc3
{ White has no time for  9.Nxc6?  as after  9...Qb6  10.bxc3   10.Nxe7+  runs into  10...Nxb5  11.Nxd5  Qa5+−+  gives Black an extra piece and with it a decisive advantage.  Qxb5  11.Nxe7  Be6−+  White's knight on e7 is trapped and will drop in short order. }
9... Qa5
{ with a double-attack on the bishop on b5 and the c3 pawn. White quickly collapsed in 0-1 @@StartBracket@@28@@EndBracket@@ Clausen,S @@StartBracket@@2250@@EndBracket@@-Hellers,F @@StartBracket@@2550@@EndBracket@@ Copenhagen 1991. }
