[Black "5. e3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Nc3 d5
{ is our default reaction when White develops his knight to c3, taking control over the e4 square and thus preventing e2-e4. }
4. Bg5
{ Writing this from the other side of the pond, I'm pretty clueless when it comes to British slang but detailed analysis shows that White is under serious pressure after }
4... Ne4
{ which is 5 times less popular than 4...Bg7 but much stronger. While 4...Bg7 comfortably equalizes, 4...Ne4 gives Black a significant advantage @@StartBracket@@or even an outright winning position@@EndBracket@@ in every single line.   We will consider White's 5 most popular continuations, namely  5.Bf4  ,  5.Nxe4  ,  5.Bh4  ,  5.e3  , and  5.h4 }
5. e3 { gives Black the two bishops advantage after } 5... Nxg5 6. Nxg5 h6
{ is a strong OTB novelty, pushing back White's knight. Black is behind in development so he should limit White's activity as much as possible.   6...Bg7?!  is premature. After  7.Qf3  the f7 pawn is already under fire.  7...f6  may at first sight look strong  8.Nh3  c6  9.O-O-O  and Black would be doing very well with  9...e5?!  if not for  10.e4  exd4  the stunning  11.exd5!!  which gives the upper hand after  11...dxc3  12.Bc4  Kf8  13.dxc6  Qc7  14.Rd6⩲ }
7. Nf3 Bg7 8. Bd3 O-O
{ is safest. Black is slightly behind in development so he does best in first securing his king. }
9. O-O c5
{ is both novel and strong, pressuring the d4 pawn. Black intends to play ...cxd4 and then undermine the d4 pawn with ...Nc6 and possibly ...Bg4. It is clear that White's knight on c3 is completely misplaced, preventing White from being able to reinforce the d4 pawn with c2-c3. }
10. dxc5
{ 10.Qd2  can be met with  10...cxd4  and after  11.exd4  Nc6  12.Bb5  Bf5∓  Black has the two bishops and good pressure against the d4 pawn. Next up is ...Rc8. }
10... Nd7 { will recoup the pawn with the upper hand. } 11. Nxd5
{ Trying to hold on to the pawn with  11.Na4  fails to  11...Qa5  12.c4  Nxc5  13.Nxc5  Qxc5  14.cxd5  Qxd5∓  when Black's two bishops are a big asset in such an open position.   11.Bb5  allows  11...Bxc3  12.bxc3  Nxc5∓  when White has nothing to show for the crippled queenside pawns. }
11... Bxb2
{ White picks up the d5 pawn but drops the one on b2. This clearly favors the second player as White has been left with split pawns on the queenside. }
12. Rb1 Bg7 13. c6
{ returns the pawn to weaken Black's pawn structure. However, White is not out of the woods just yet. After }
13... bxc6 14. Nb4 Qc7 15. Na6 Bxa6 16. Bxa6 Nc5
{ Black is clearly for choice. Both players have split queenside pawns but Black is in a much better position to attack them with ...Qa5. The bishop on g7 is also far superior to White's light-squared bishop. }
