4... Ne4
{ which is 5 times less popular than 4...Bg7 but much stronger. While 4...Bg7 comfortably equalizes, 4...Ne4 gives Black a significant advantage @@StartBracket@@or even an outright winning position@@EndBracket@@ in every single line.   We will consider White's 5 most popular continuations, namely  5.Bf4  ,  5.Nxe4  ,  5.Bh4  ,  5.e3  , and  5.h4 }
5. e3 { gives Black the two bishops advantage after } 5... Nxg5 6. Nxg5 h6
{ is a strong OTB novelty, forcing White's knight. Black is behind in development so he should limit White's activity as much as possible.   6...Bg7?!  is premature. After  7.Qf3  the f7 pawn is already under fire.  7...f6  may at first sight look strong  8.Nh3  c6  9.O-O-O  and Black would be doing very well with  9...e5?!  if not for  10.e4  exd4  the stunning  11.exd5!!  which gives the upper hand after  11...dxc3  12.Bc4  Kf8  13.dxc6  Qc7  14.Rd6⩲ }
7. Nf3 Bg7 8. Bd3 O-O
{ is safest. Black is slightly behind in development so he does best in first securing his king. }
9. h4
{ intending to create a kingside attack with h5. This is however nothing but a pipe dream as Black can immediately strike in the center with }
9... c5 { Our thematic pawn break works wonders here. } 10. Qd2
{ 10.h5  can be met with  10...g5  stopping White's attack before it even got started.  11.Qd2  c4  send White's bishop packing.  12.Be2  Nc6  13.O-O-O?!  b5−+  starts a vicious attack on White's king. This attack is so dangerous that the engines are already giving Black a decisive advantage. }
10... cxd4 11. exd4 h5
{ closes the door on White's attack. All White achieved with h2-h4 was weakening the g4 square. }
12. O-O-O Nc6
{ White is in big trouble. The d4 pawn is a big target, which can be furthered pressure with ...Bg4. Not only that, Black can quickly launch an assault on White's king with ...Qa5, ...Rb8, and ...b5-b4. Conversely, White has no way of reaching our king. }
