{ forces White's knight back, which has no good place to retreat to. } 6. Ng1
{ at least does not lose the d4 pawn. Nevertheless, if White is forced to undevelop his pieces, then the opening has obviously been a disaster. }
6... Bg7 7. c3 { 7.e3  c5  8.c3  O-O  transposes to the text. } 7... O-O 8. e3
{ is most logical, preparing to complete development with Bc4 and Ne2. Notice how our pawn on e4 stops White from developing the knight to f3, which is its best square.  Alternatively   8.g3  intending to fianchetto the light-squared bishop is strongly met by  8...Qd5!  hitting White's bishop and threatening ...e4-e3, thus forcing  9.Be3  and after  9...Nd7  10.Bg2  Nf6∓  Black is clearly better. The pawn on e4 gives the second player a big space advantage and severely restricts White's pieces. }
8... c5 { increases the pressure on the d4 pawn. Next up is ...Nc6. } 9. dxc5
{ can be met with the novel } 9... Qa5
{ clearing the way for ...Rd8 and improving over the game 0-1 @@StartBracket@@18@@EndBracket@@ Trujillo,O @@StartBracket@@2173@@EndBracket@@-Santofimio Vega,A @@StartBracket@@1758@@EndBracket@@ La Dorada 2016. White has no time for }
10. Bxe7
{ Better is  10.Ne2  but after  10...Rd8  11.Qc2  Qxc5∓  Black has restored material equality with a big space advantage. }
10... Re8 11. Bd6 Bxc3+
{ wins at least a rook.   For example  12.bxc3  Qxc3  13.Qd2   13.Ke2  Bg4−+  is lights out  13...Qxa1−+  is winning }
