[White "19. Barry Attack (1...Nf6 2...g6)"]
[Black "5. Bf4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Nc3 d5
{ is our default reaction when White develops his knight to c3, taking control over the e4 square and thus preventing e2-e4. }
4. Bg5
{ Writing this from the other side of the pond, I'm pretty clueless when it comes to British slang but detailed analysis shows that White is under serious pressure after }
4... Ne4
{ which is 5 times less popular than 4...Bg7 but much stronger. While 4...Bg7 comfortably equalizes, 4...Ne4 gives Black a significant advantage @@StartBracket@@or even an outright winning position@@EndBracket@@ in every single line.   We will consider White's 5 most popular continuations, namely  5.Bf4  ,  5.Nxe4  ,  5.Bh4  ,  5.e3  , and  5.h4 }
5. Bf4
{ is the most popular move at the master level and basically an admission that 4. Bg5 was not a good move. If White wanted to place his bishop on f4, he should have done so on move 4! }
5... Nxc3
{ permanently damages White's pawn structure just like in the 5. Bh4 variation. The doubled c-pawns will remain a weakness for the rest of the game.   5...Bg7  is playable but the text is far stronger. }
6. bxc3 c5
{ immediately undermines White's center. Black will be able to pressure it with ...Bg7 and ...Qa5 in the near future. }
7. e3
{ is the most popular continuation.   7.Qd2  with the idea ...Bh6 has also been tried. However, after  7...Bg7  8.Bh6  Bxh6  9.Qxh6  Apart from wasting valuable time, White did not achieve anything with this Bh5 excursion. In fact  9...Qa5∓  forces White's queen back with a clear advantage. White has nothing to show for his crippled pawn structure.   7.dxc5?!  is obviously terrible, leaving White with tripled pawns on an open file.  7...Bg7  8.Be5  f6  9.Bg3  Qa5∓  with a clear advantage for Black. }
7... Bg7 8. Be5 { only loses valuable time. } 8... Bxe5 9. Nxe5 Qa5
{ hits the c3 pawn, forcing } 10. Qd2 { when } 10... c4
{ gives Black a big space advantage. White's knight on e5 will be promptly kicked back with ...f6 while we can develop our b8 knight via d7 and target the c3 pawn with ...Nd7-b6-a4 later on. }
