[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "19. Barry Attack (1...Nf6 2...g6)"]
[Black "[4...Bg7 Alternative] 5. Bxf6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Nc3 d5
{ Our default reaction when White develops his knight to c3. } 4. Bg5
{ The Barry Attack, which is British slang for rubbish attack according to the New in Chess Yearbook. }
4... Bg7
{ is an alternative to  4...Ne4  , which is mymain recommendation.  White has three options now: 5. e3, 5. Bxf6 and 5. Qd2?! in order of decreasing popularity. }
5. Bxf6
{ has been tried but is hard to take seriously since White can't even get e4 in under good conditions. }
5... exf6
{ is the best recapture, opening the e-file for our rooks and enabling us to play ...f5. This will put an end to White's only logical plan of breaking with e4, meaning his knight on c3 will be misplaced. }
6. e4 { only opens the position for our bishops. } 6... dxe4 7. Nxe4 O-O 8. Be2
f5 { starts chasing White's knight around. } 9. Nc5
{ Worse is  9.Ng3  f4  10.Ne4  Re8  11.Nc3  Nc6∓  will pick up the d-pawn. }
9... b6 10. Nb3 c5 { White is very poorly developed to deal with such a move. }
11. O-O
{ This position occured in the game 0-1  (26)  Ciftci,M  (1803)  -Atakisi,U  (2312)  Manavgat 2015. Black started with 11...Bb7 and only then played 12...Qc7. It is more accurate to start with }
11... Qc7 { which avoids counterplay associated with dxc5. } 12. c3 Bb7
{ is clearly better for Black with ...Rd8 coming next. The two bishops are very strong here. }
