{ Having examined the main alternatives in 5. Bxf6 and 5. Qd2, it's now time to turn our attention to White's most common move. }
5... O-O 6. Bd3 c5 { Principled and strong. } 7. O-O
{ This position was reached in several tens of games. Black has never played }
7... h6
{ which is the top choice of the neural network engines. White now has to make a decision on where to place his bishop. }
8. Bxf6 { hands over the bishop pair for little gain. } 8... Bxf6 9. Qd2 cxd4
10. exd4 Kg7
{ followed by ...Nc6 is very comfortable. Black has the bishop pair and good pressure against the d4 pawn. }
