[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. London (1...Nf6 2...g6) - Part 1 (lines w/ Nc3)"]
[Black "Chapter overview"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ The London system. Underestimate it at your own peril as this is an opening where White can play ambitiously and fight for an advantage.  Attempts to refute or crush the London usually backfire. One course with such a title on Chessable fails to even equalize with Black. Now I'm all for trying to 'crush' incorrect openings, but the London certainly does not fall into this category.     Moreover, I don't believe in goofy systems such as @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.Bf4  c5  3.e3  Nd5?!   or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Bf4  c6  3.e3  Qb6  , which have been proposed by a few authors on this platform. White has excellent chances for an advantage when Black plays like this.  Instead, I'll be recommending a reliable system with 2...g6, suitable for both Grunfeld and King's Indian players. After careful analysis with powerful cloud engines running Stockfish and LeelaZero, I've found numerous improvements over current theory that'll allow you to fight for the full point. }
2... g6 3. Nc3
{ In this chapter, we'll cover all the setups with White's knight on c3. Setups without a knight on c3 are discussed in thenext chapter. }
3... d5
{ Now we will examine each of White's three main options: 4. e3, 4. Qd2 and 4. Nf3.   3...Bg7  allows a transposition to the Pirc defense after  4.e4  which is only suitable if you play the Pirc with Black. }
4. e3
{ White's most popular choice with 1400+ OTB games.   4.Qd2  second most common with 500+ OTB games.   4.Nf3  third most played with 150+ OTB games. }
*

