1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 { The London system. } 2... g6 3. Nc3
{ In this chapter, we'll cover all the setups with White's knight on c3. } 3...
d5
{ Now we will examine each of White's three main options: 4. e3, 4. Qd2 and 4. Nf3. }
4. Nf3 { is White's third most popular continuation. } 4... Bg7 5. e3 O-O 6.
Be2
{ 6.Nb5  Na6  7.h3  c6  8.Nc3  Nc7  transposes to5. Nb5 Na6 6. e3 c6 7. Nc3 Nc7 8. h3 O-O.   6.h3  to stop ...Bg4 is harmless.  6...c5  7.Be2  is the most popular move. There are other options, none of which pose any problems. Black is doing very well after the strong move  7...Ne4! }
6... c5 { The knight jump } 7. Ne5
{ is most common. I like immediately challenging it with } 7... Nc6 8. O-O Ne8
{ A strong retreating move, uncovering the bishop and planning to reroute the knight to f5. It also clears the way for ...f6 should we desire to knock back White's knight. }
9. Na4
{ was tried in a couple of correspondence games. Black gets an excellent game with the simple }
9... cxd4 10. exd4 Nd6
{ with the idea ...Nf5 and ...f6 gave Black good prospects in ½-½ @@StartBracket@@42@@EndBracket@@ Lara Ruiz,J @@StartBracket@@2291@@EndBracket@@ -Mihailovs,A @@StartBracket@@2333@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2017. }
