1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 { The London system. } 2... g6 3. Nc3
{ In this chapter, we'll cover all the setups with White's knight on c3. } 3...
d5
{ Now we will examine each of White's three main options: 4. e3, 4. Qd2 and 4. Nf3. }
4. Qd2
{ is White's second most popular move. He intends to quickly castle queenside and then start an attack against our king with Bh6 and h4-h5. }
4... Bg7 5. O-O-O
{ is very natural, albeit considerably less common than 5. Bh6. } 5... O-O 6.
h4
{ 6.Bh6  c5  7.Bxg7  Kxg7  transposes to 5. Bh6 O-O 6. Bxg7 Kxg7 7. O-O-O c5 }
6... c5 { A flank attack is best met by counterplay in the center! } 7. e3
{ 7.dxc5  Qa5  8.Kb1  Nc6  9.Nxd5  Qxc5=∞  gave Black full compensation and the initiative in the correspondence game 0-1 @@StartBracket@@51@@EndBracket@@ Keijzer,R @@StartBracket@@1852@@EndBracket@@-Pasko,P ICCF email 2006 }
