d5 4. e3
{ White's most popular choice, which is 3x as common as the alternatives 4. Qd2 and 4. Nf3 that we already tackled. }
4... Bg7 5. Be2 O-O 6. Nf3
{ is a relatively popular position that has been reached in 1400+ games.   It can be reached via different move orders, for example @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.Nf3  g6  3.Nc3  d5  4.Bf4  Bg7  5.e3  O-O  6.Be2  which explains the high number of games. }
6... c5 7. Ne5
{ is the most popular move 7th move at both the club and master level.   7.O-O  cxd4  8.exd4  Nc6  9.Ne5  transposes }
7... Nc6 8. O-O
{ 8.h4  only weakens White's position. After  8...cxd4  9.exd4  h5⩱  stops White's h-pawn. Next up is ...Bf5 with a slight advantage.   8.Qd2  can be met with  8...Bf5  when  9.g4  is most common but harmless. After  9...Nxe5  10.gxf5  Nc4  11.Bxc4  dxc4  12.dxc5  Qxd2+  13.Kxd2  Rac8⩱  Black has the upper hand. }
8... cxd4
{ Black has other good options, but this is simple and effective, leaving White with a weak pawn on d4. It's clear White's knight on c3 is misplaced as White cannot play c2-c3 to reinforce the pawn. }
9. exd4 Bf5
{ This natural move was not considered by GM Aaron Summerscale and Sverre Johnsen in the book 'A Killer Chess Opening Repertoire'. }
10. Nxc6
{ is logical, slightly spoiling Black's structure. White hopes to make use of the slightly weakened c5 square with Na4-c5. }
10... bxc6 11. Na4
{ is the logical follow up to Nxc6, intending to plant the knight on c5.   11.Be5  can be met with  11...Nd7  12.Bxg7  Kxg7  13.Qd2  And now  13...e5=  improves over the game ½-½ @@StartBracket@@18@@EndBracket@@ Pein,M @@StartBracket@@2425@@EndBracket@@ -Gullaksen,E @@StartBracket@@2367@@EndBracket@@ Hampstead 1999, giving Black superior central control. }
11... Re8
{ intending to later expand in the center with ...e5. Black need not worry about White's knight coming to c5 as he can exchange it off with ...Ne4 or ...Nd7. }
12. Nc5
{ Immediately jumping into c5 is a novelty. This is not that surprising given that }
12... Ne4 { gets rid of White's knight right away. After } 13. Nxe4 dxe4 14. c3
e5
{ Black has good pressure against the d4 and b2 pawns with ...Rb8 coming next. }
