1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 { The London system. } 2... g6 3. Nc3
{ In this chapter, we'll cover all the setups with White's knight on c3. } 3...
d5 4. e3
{ White's most popular choice, which is 3x as common as the alternatives 4. Qd2 and 4. Nf3 that we already tackled. }
4... Bg7 5. Be2 O-O 6. Nf3
{ is a relatively popular position that has been reached in 1400+ games.   It can be reached via different move orders, for example @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.Nf3  g6  3.Nc3  d5  4.Bf4  Bg7  5.e3  O-O  6.Be2  which explains the high number of games. }
6... c5 7. dxc5
{ is the second most common 7th move and the engines' top choice. White hopes to make Black waste time recouping the pawn. }
7... Qa5 8. O-O Qxc5
{ A direct attempt to exploit White's lead in development is } 9. Nb5
{ threatening to win material with Nc7. Black is however well equipped to deal with such an incursion.   Harmless is  9.Nd4  After  9...e6  10.Nb3  Qe7=  Black is very comfortable with ...Rd8 and ...Nc6 coming next. }
9... Nh5
{ with a double-attack on White's bishop and the b2 pawn.   Alternatively  9...a6  10.Nc7  Ra7  11.Nb5  Ra8=  leads to a repetition. }
10. Be5
{ 10.Nc7??  is a blunder. After  10...Nxf4  11.Nxa8  Nxe2+  12.Qxe2  b6−+  White's knight is trapped. With ...Ba6 coming next, it'll only be a matter of time before White picks it up. }
10... Bxe5 11. Nxe5 Nc6
{ Now that the dark-squared bishops are off the board, White's knight on b5 makes little sense. }
12. Nxc6 bxc6
{ Reinforces the d5 pawn and opens up the b-file for Black's rook. } 13. Nd4
Nf6
{ Black is in fantastic shape. He can expand in the center with ...e5 and use the b-file to attack White's queenside. }
