{ Pushing Harry is ever popular.  White can also push Harry one move later with   5.Be2  O-O  6.h4  As usual, the thematic break  6...c5  gives us excellent counterplay.  7.h5  Nc6  8.hxg6  hxg6  9.Nf3  Ne4!  Exclam! White can't play Qd2, meaning his king is stranded in the center. Black was already better and went on to win in 0-1 @@StartBracket@@36@@EndBracket@@ Ponomariov,R @@StartBracket@@2631@@EndBracket@@ -Kuzubov,Y @@StartBracket@@2643@@EndBracket@@ chess.com INT 2020.   5.Nb5  5...Na6  6.h3  c6  7.Nc3  7...Nc7  8.Nf3  transposes to 4.Nf3 line }
5... O-O 6. h5 c5
{ Thematic. This central reaction to White's flank attack works wonders here.  And not   6...Nxh5?  as after  7.Rxh5!  gxh5  8.Qxh5→  White has a very dangerous attack. }
7. hxg6 hxg6 8. Qd2
{ is White's most logical move, clearing the way for O-O-O. } 8... Nc6 9. Nge2
{ is half as popular as 9. O-O-O.   9.dxc5  is once again met with  9...Qa5= }
9... Qa5
{ this time does not pin White's knight but supports the ...b5-b4 pawn advance.   This move was not considered in the Chessable course 'The Jobava London system' by GM Simon Williams, who only looked at the dubious 9...Re8.   The immediate  9...b5!?  is also very interesting. Note that  10.Nxb5?  runs into  10...Ne4!  11.Qd1  Qa5+−+  winning material. }
10. Bh6
{ Perhaps better is  10.f3  although after  10...b5↑  I certainly wouldn't want to be in White's shoes. }
10... Bxh6 11. Rxh6 Kg7
{ improves over the game 1-0 @@StartBracket@@26@@EndBracket@@ Gumularz,S @@StartBracket@@2376@@EndBracket@@-Kus,A @@StartBracket@@2154@@EndBracket@@ Krakow 2017. }
12. Rh1 Bd7
{ followed by ...Rh8 puts an end to any dreams White had of kingside play. } *

