[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "21. London (1...Nf6 2...g6) - Part 2 (lines wo/ Nc3)"]
[Black "Chapter overview"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 g6 3. Nf3
{ In this chapter, we will consider all the major setups where White does not develop his b1 knight to c3. }
3... Bg7
{ White has a zoo of different move orders, whether to start with h3, include c3 or not, play Nbd2 first, develop the light-squared bishop to e2, d3 or c4, etc. This can easily catch a Black player off guard and trick him into a variation he did not want to enter. Worry not, we're going to avoid all of this.   To make this repertoire practical, I chose to recommend a setup with ...d6, ...c5 followed by ...Qb6, which we'll play in almost all the lines where White plays e3. Not only is this easy to learn and remember, but it's also one of the top choices of the neural network engines. In the rare cases where White opts for e4, we'll mostly aim for a quick ...e7-e5 instead of breaking with ...c5. }
4. e3
{ is 9x as popular as the alternatives with 18000+ OTB games.   4.h3  is White's second most popular continuation with 2100+ OTB games.   4.c4  Not the most London-esque move, but with 300+ games it certainly deserves some attention.   4.Nbd2  is third most common with 1800+ OTB games.   4.c3  has some independent value when White opts for e4 setups. It has been played in 1100+ OTB games.  Setups with a knight on c3   4.Nc3  were covered in chapter20. }
*

