[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "22. 3.g3 system (1...Nf6 2...g6)"]
[Black "Overview for Grunfeld players"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3
{ 2.g3  is not theoretically dangerous but can be used to trick you into a variation you did not want to play. For example  2...g6  3.Bg2  White is now 'threatening' to play 3. e4 and while  3...d5  stops e4, White can now transpose to a mainline variation of the Fianchetto Grunfeld with  4.Nf3  Bg7  5.c4  thus move ordering King's Indian players out of their repertoire.   The easiest is to meet  2.g3  with  2...d5  when  3.Nf3  c5!  transposes to chapter8. White has zero chances for an advantage here and you only need to learn 10 trainable variations. }
2... g6 3. g3
{ We will now examine the g3 system. This approach was, amongst others, recommended by IM Cristof Sielecki in the book and Chessable course Keep it Simple: 1.d4.  White delays  (and often entirely foregoes)  c2-c4, preferring to first develop his kingside and keep options open. The problem with such an approach is that it fails to fight for the center effectively, meaning Black has little trouble emerging out of the opening with a good position. }
3... Bg7 4. Bg2 O-O 5. O-O
{ is a flexible move. White can play c2-c4 next and transpose into the mainlines or instead choose from a number of alternative setups.   5.b3  has been played in 200+ OTB games. }
5... d5 { We will examine the following possibilities on move 6: } 6. Nbd2
{ is White's most common alternative to the mainline approach with 6. c4 with over 2300 OTB games.   6.c3  has been played in 1400+ OTB games.   6.Bf4  has been essayed in 600+ OTB games.   6.Ne5  has featured in 400+ OTB games.   6.c4  Transposes to a mainline in the Grunfeld, which is outside the scope of this course @@StartBracket@@as we're only dealing with d4 systems@@EndBracket@@. }
*

