[Black "[Both] 5. b3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. g3
{ We will now examine the g3 system. This approach was, amongst others, recommended by IM Cristof Sielecki in the book and Chessable course Keep it Simple: 1.d4.  White delays  (and often entirely foregoes)  c2-c4, preferring to first develop his kingside and keep options open. The problem with such an approach is that it fails to fight for the center effectively, meaning Black has little trouble emerging out of the opening with a good position. }
3... Bg7 4. Bg2 O-O 5. b3
{ This early fianchetto is much less popular than  5.O-O  or  5.c4  the reason being that Black can immediately strike with }
5... c5 { undermining White's center. } 6. O-O { surrenders the center. After }
6... cxd4 7. Nxd4 d5 8. Bb2 e5
{ Black has full control of the center and is already better. } 9. Nf3
{ Going forward with  9.Nb5?!  is worse. After  9...a6  10.N5c3  Be6  11.Qd2  Nc6∓  Black had full control of the center and was clearly better in Almasi,I @@StartBracket@@2437@@EndBracket@@ -Rajlich,V @@StartBracket@@2377@@EndBracket@@/Budapest 2002/EXT 2003. }
9... e4 { Gains more space with yet another tempo on the knight. } 10. Nd4 Re8
{ is a strong move, hinting at ...e3.   Also interesting is  10...e3!?  11.fxe3  Ng4  12.Qd2  Re8  13.Rf3  Qg5=  when the e3 pawn should drop at some point. }
11. Na3
{ with the idea c4 is White's only logical plan. The first player needs to chip away at Black's center or he'll end up clearly worse once Black finishes development.   Worse is  11.e3?!  as it severely weakens the f3 square. Black can readily exploit this with  11...Nbd7  12.Qe2  Ne5  13.h3  g5  with the idea ...g4 improves over the game 0-1 @@StartBracket@@40@@EndBracket@@ Halldorsson,J @@StartBracket@@2195@@EndBracket@@-Steingrimsson,H @@StartBracket@@2554@@EndBracket@@ Egilsstadir 2011. After  14.f4  Nf3+−+  Black is already winning. }
11... h5
{ This Alpha Zero-esque h-pawn advance improves over the game 0-1 @@StartBracket@@32@@EndBracket@@ Hafiz,A  @@StartBracket@@2396@@EndBracket@@-Gagunashvili,M @@StartBracket@@2573@@EndBracket@@ Tashkent 2017. Black wants to drive the pawn down to ...h3 to further restrict White's light-squared bishop.   11...e3!?  was recommended by GM Boris Avrukh in the book GM Repertoire: Beating 1. d4 sidelines. However, the game can quickly fizzle out after  12.f3  Nc6  13.c4  Qe7  14.Nxc6  bxc6  15.cxd5  Nxd5  16.Bxg7  Kxg7=  Black can get more with 11...h5, which is both Stockfish and Leela's top choice. }
12. c4 h4 13. cxd5 Nxd5 14. Nc4 h3
{ The pawn has reached its final destination. White's light-squared bishop is forced back. }
15. Bh1 Nc6
{ Black is at least slightly better here. The pawn on e4 gives him more space, excellent central control and completely restricts White's light-squared bishop. }
