[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. g3
{ We will now examine the g3 system. This approach was, amongst others, recommended by IM Cristof Sielecki in the book and Chessable course Keep it Simple: 1.d4.  White delays  (and often entirely foregoes)  c2-c4, preferring to first develop his kingside and keep options open. The problem with such an approach is that it fails to fight for the center effectively, meaning Black has little trouble emerging out of the opening with a good position. }
3... Bg7 4. Bg2 O-O 5. O-O
{ is a flexible move. White can play c2-c4 next and transpose into the mainlines or instead choose from a number of alternative setups. }
5... d5 { is the move Grunfeld players should make. } 6. c3
{ is aimed against ...c5, which White wants to meet with dxc5 followed by b2-b4 to keep the c5 pawn alive. Such a slow approach is obviously harmless.   6.c4  Transposes to one of the Grunfeld mainlines, which is beyond the scope of this course. }
6... Nbd7
{ White may have discouraged the immediate ...c5, but Black can prepare it with ...Nbd7. }
7. Nbd2
{ 7.Bf4  can be met with  7...b6  8.Ne5  Bb7  9.Nxd7  Qxd7  10.Be5  c5=  Black was very comfortable in ½-½ @@StartBracket@@27@@EndBracket@@ Cyborowski,L @@StartBracket@@2526@@EndBracket@@-Ragger,M  @@StartBracket@@2690@@EndBracket@@ Czech Republic 2019. }
7... c5 8. Re1
{ Breaking with e4 is White's only logical plan. Black need not worry about this and can continue development with }
8... b6 { intending to fianchetto the light-squared bishop. } 9. e4 dxe4 10.
Nxe4 Nxe4 11. Rxe4 Bb7
{ Pushes White's rook back. 11 moves in and Black is ahead in development and already better. After }
12. Re1 cxd4 13. Nxd4 Bxg2 14. Kxg2 e5
{ Black is slightly better. He has more space in the center and can aim to plant a knight on d3 with ...Nd7-c5, a square which was weakened all the way back when White played 6. c3.   A sample continuation is  14...e5  15.Nf3  Nc5  16.Qxd8  Rfxd8  17.Be3   17.Nxe5  is a mistake as after  17...Bxe5  18.Rxe5  Rd1  19.Re2  Nd3∓  White is completely pinned down.  17...Nd3⩱  Next up is ...f5 with the upper hand. }
