[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "22. 3.g3 system (1...Nf6 2...g6)"]
[Black "[Grunfeld] 5. O-O 6. Ne5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. g3
{ We will now examine the g3 system. This approach was, amongst others, recommended by IM Cristof Sielecki in the book and Chessable course Keep it Simple: 1.d4.  White delays  (and often entirely foregoes)  c2-c4, preferring to first develop his kingside and keep options open. The problem with such an approach is that it fails to fight for the center effectively, meaning Black has little trouble emerging out of the opening with a good position. }
3... Bg7 4. Bg2 O-O 5. O-O
{ is a flexible move. White can play c2-c4 next and transpose into the mainlines or instead choose from a number of alternative setups. }
5... d5 { is the move Grunfeld players should make. } 6. Ne5
{ is a typical move in these fianchetto structures. White's knight is well placed on e5 and supports the c4 break.   6.c4  Transposes to one of the Grunfeld mainlines, which is beyond the scope of this course. }
6... Bf5 7. c4
{ is the only critical continuation.   7.c3  is obviously harmless. Black can follow suit with  7...c6  8.Nd2  and then neutralize White's knight on e5 with  8...Nbd7  9.Ndf3  Nxe5  10.Nxe5  Nd7= }
7... c5
{ is rare with only a handful of games in the database but very dynamic. It sets White problem as early as move 7. We will consider three possibilities: 8. e3, 8. dxc5 and 8. cxd5, which is already a novelty. }
8. e3 { Reinforcing the e3 pawn is rather slow. After } 8... cxd4 9. exd4 Nc6
{ expels White's knight from e5 due to the pressure on the d4 pawn. } 10. Nxc6
bxc6 11. Nc3 dxc4
{ This materialistic approach is very strong. Yes, the c6 pawn is dropping and we opened up White's light-squared bishop. However, once White captures on c6 the bishop won't be doing much as there are no longer any targets on the long diagonal. Ok, what did we achieve with ...dxc4 apart from temporarily winning a pawn? The main point is that the d4 pawn is now a big target and we're already threatening to win it with ...Bd3 followed by ...Qxd4. The engines are already giving Black a clear advantage. }
12. Qa4
{ 12.Bxc6?!  is dubious. After  12...Rb8  13.Re1  e6  improves over the game 0-1 @@StartBracket@@29@@EndBracket@@ Brito Garcia,A  @@StartBracket@@2350@@EndBracket@@-Hernandez Guerrero,G @@StartBracket@@2555@@EndBracket@@ Zaragoza 1996. Next up is ...Bd3 when the d4 pawn will drop. Black already has a decisive advantage. }
12... Bd3 { Covers the c4 pawn with a tempo on White's rook. } 13. Re1
{ Moves the rook to safety and stops Black from playing ...Qxd4 as the e7 pawn would then hang. This only delays the inevitable as the d4 pawn will drop sooner rather than later. }
13... Rb8
{ improves over the game 0-1 @@StartBracket@@42@@EndBracket@@ Petakov,U @@StartBracket@@2366@@EndBracket@@ -Tadic,B @@StartBracket@@2495@@EndBracket@@ Palic 2014, where Black went for the hasty ...Qxd4. The d4 isn't running anywhere and Black does best in targeting the b2 pawn first. }
14. Qxa7 e6 15. Bxc6 Ng4
{ The pawn on d4 is about to drop with ...Bxd4. This will not only restore material equality but give Black a decisive advantage as the pawn on f2 will be very hard to cover. }
