5... d6
{ is the move King's Indian players should make. Grunfeld players should play 5...d5, which is covered here. }
6. Re1
{ is another way to prepare the e2-e4 advance. Black should immediately strike in the center with   6.c4  transposes to a mainline in the King's Indian, which is outside the scope of this course. }
6... c5 7. dxc5
{ has been tried a couple of times but is essentially harmless. The ensuing endgame is very comfortable for Black. }
7... dxc5 8. Qxd8 Rxd8 9. c3 Be6
{ The bishop is well placed here, giving us the option of playing ...Bd5 later on to neutralize White's bishop on g2. Next on the agenda is ...Nc6 completing development. }
10. Ng5
{ Worse is  10.Na3?!  After the following logical set of moves  10...Nc6  11.Ng5  Bd7  12.Be3  b6  13.Red1  Rac8  14.Nc4  This position was reached in the game 1-0 @@StartBracket@@56@@EndBracket@@ Artemiev,V @@StartBracket@@2731@@EndBracket@@ -Guseinov,G @@StartBracket@@2666@@EndBracket@@ Moscow 2019. Black could now have gained the upper hand with  14...Ng4⩱  going after White's bishop. The knight on g5 can then be kicked with ...h6. }
