1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. g3
{ We will now examine the g3 system. This approach was, amongst others, recommended by IM Cristof Sielecki in the book and Chessable course Keep it Simple: 1.d4.  White delays  (and often entirely foregoes)  c2-c4, preferring to first develop his kingside and keep options open. The problem with such an approach is that it fails to fight for the center effectively, meaning Black has little trouble emerging out of the opening with a good position. }
3... Bg7 4. Bg2 O-O 5. O-O
{ is a flexible move. White can play c2-c4 next and transpose into the mainlines or instead choose from a number of alternative setups. }
5... d6
{ is the move King's Indian players should make. Grunfeld players should play 5...d5, which is covered here. }
6. a4
{ I was surprised to find this move has been played in 1800+ games. White's idea is to grab as much space as possible with a5 without committing his minor pieces to specific squares, thus retaining a great degree of flexibility.   6.c4  transposes to a mainline in the King's Indian, which is outside the scope of this course. }
6... Na6
{ is a very interesting move. Black not only prepares the ...c5 break but can also jump into b4 in certain variations, a squared which White weakened with 6. a4. }
7. Nc3
{ prepares the e4 advance. As usual, when White places his knight on c3, Black should consider putting his pawn on d5 }
7... d5
{ taking control over the e4 square. If White cannot expand with e4 then his knight on c3 makes little sense and is in the way of c2-c4. }
8. Bf4 c6 9. Qd2 Bf5
{ Black comfortably equalized in ½-½ @@StartBracket@@39@@EndBracket@@ Stefanova,A @@StartBracket@@2518@@EndBracket@@ -Muzychuk,A @@StartBracket@@2598@@EndBracket@@ Batumi 2012. He can follow up with ...Rc8 and then consider breaking in the center with ...c5. }
