3... Bg7 4. Bg2 O-O 5. O-O
{ is a flexible move. White can play c2-c4 next and transpose into the mainlines or instead choose from a number of alternative setups. }
5... d6 { is the move King's Indian players should make. } 6. b3
{ is White's most popular alternative to 6. c4. It has been played 3000+ times OTB and was recommended by IM Cristof Sielecki in the Chessable course 'Keep it Simple: 1.d4'. White wants to play Bb2 next to dissuade us from breaking in the center with ...e7-e5.   6.c4  transposes to a mainline in the King's Indian, which is outside the scope of this course. }
6... e5
{ This typical King's Indian break is my preferred approach.   The alternative break  6...c5  was recommended by GM Boris Avrukh in the book GM Repertoire: Beating 1.d4 sidelines but after  7.c4  e5  8.dxe5  dxe5  9.Bb2⩲  White has decent chances for a slight advantage. Avrukh goes on for several moves, reaching an endgame where Black is a pawn down but should hold with correct play. I see no need to give White such a possibility. }
7. dxe5 dxe5 8. Ba3 { is more incisive than 8. Bb2. } 8... Qxd1 9. Rxd1 Re8
{ Removes the rook from danger and covers the e5 pawn, which can be pushed to e4 at an opportune moment. White has two different approaches now: 10. Nc3 and 10. c4. }
