12... a5
{ is a strong move, taking control of the b4 square and preparing to develop the knight to a6. }
13. Nc3 Na6
{ From ...a6, the knight controls the b4 and c5 squares and preemptively defends the c7 pawn against Nb5. }
14. Rac1 Bd7
{ This is Black's strongest move, which was not considered by IM Cristof Sielecki in the Chessable course 'Keep it Simple: 1.d4'. The bishop is well placed on d7, controlling the b5 square and supporting the ...a5-a4 break at an opportune moment.   14...c6!?  allows  15.Bd6  with the idea Na4-b6 next. 'White has the easier game here' was Christof Sielecki's assessment. While Black is still okay, there is no need to weaken the b6 and d6 squares with 14...c6. }
15. Ndb5 h5 16. f4 Rab8
{ Steps out of the long diagonal. Black is very comfortable and can consider ...Bg4 next to attack White's weak pawn on e2. }
