1. d4 Nf6 2. g4
{ The so-called Bronstein Gambit, which is completely unsound and therefore mainly seen in bullet chess. }
2... Nxg4 { Thanks for the free pawn! } 3. e4
{ Worse is  3.f3  as after  3...Nf6  4.e4  d5  5.e5  Nfd7  6.f4  c5  7.Nf3  Nc6  8.c3  cxd4  9.cxd4  Nb6∓  White has virtually no compensation for the pawn deficit. }
3... d5 { Immediately taking a stake in the center is Black's best move. } 4.
Be2
{ 4.e5  runs into  4...c5  5.h3  Nh6  6.Bxh6  gxh6  7.Nf3  Qb6  8.Nc3  e6∓  followed by ...Nc6 when Black is still a pawn up and has the bishop pair. }
4... Nf6 5. e5 Ng8
{ Undeveloping the knight is preferable to ...Nfd7 as it does not block the light-squared bishop, which we want to develop outside our pawn chain with ...Bf5. The g8 knight can then be developed with ...e6 and ...Ne7. }
6. Nc3
{ Alternatives like  6.c4  aren't much better. After  6...e6  7.Nc3  Ne7  8.Nf3  Nbc6  9.Be3  dxc4  10.Bxc4  Nd5∓  White has no compensation for the material deficit.   or  6.Nf3  also fails to impress. Following  6...Bf5  7.c4  dxc4  8.Bxc4  e6  9.Bg5  Qd7  10.Nc3  h6  11.Be3  Ne7∓  Black is a clean pawn up. }
6... Bf5 7. Nf3 e6 8. Bg5 { is most common but can be easily sidestepped with }
8... Qd7 9. Qd2 Nc6 10. O-O-O f6
{ undermines White's e5 pawn and makes ...O-O-O possible. } 11. Bf4 O-O-O
{ gives Black a clear advantage as White has close to zero compensation for the missing pawn. The immediate threat is ...g5.   A sample continuation is  12.exf6  gxf6  13.Nh4  Bg6  14.Rhg1   Worse is  14.Nb5?  a6  15.Nxc7  e5-+  wins material  a6  15.Nxg6  hxg6  16.Rxg6  Qf7  17.Rg2  e5∓  Material is level but Black's central e5 pawn is far stronger than White's isolated h2 pawn. }
