d5 3. Nf3 e6 { immediately targets the weak b4 pawn. } 4. a3 a5
{ is the most incisive move at Black's disposal, forcing White's pawn to move forward or open the a-file in Black's favor.  Alternatively   4...b6  preparing to break with ...c5 is another good option.  5.e3  c5  6.bxc5  bxc5  7.c4  cxd4  8.exd4   8.Nxd4  N  is both a novelty and White's best move.  8...Nbd7  9.cxd5  Nxd5  10.Bb2  Bb7  11.Nd2  Be7  12.Rc1  O-O =  is an almost symmetrical position where Black is obviously completely fine.  dxc4  leaves White with an isolated d-pawn, giving the second player a slight advantage after  9.Bxc4  Be7  10.O-O  O-O  11.Nc3  Ba6⩱ }
5. b5
{ 5.bxa5?!  only helps activate Black's pieces. After  5...c5  6.e3  c4  7.g3  Rxa5⩱  Black has a big space advantage and the a3 pawn is very weak. }
5... c5 6. bxc6
{ 6.e3  can simply be met with  6...Nbd7  7.c4  cxd4  8.exd4  b6⩱  followed by ...Bb7, ...Be7 and O-O with the upper hand. White will end up with an isolated pawn on d4 and a lot of queenside weaknesses. }
6... bxc6
{ is the correct recapture, clearing the way for ... Ba6. The c6 pawn will later be pushed to undermine White's center. }
7. Bf4
{ is natural but inaccurate.   7.c4  is White's only way of keeping the balance. After  7...Nbd7  8.e3  Be7  9.Be2  O-O  10.O-O  c5  11.Nbd2  cxd4  12.Nxd4  Bb7=  Black is doing very well. }
7... Ba6 { White will now find it very hard to develop his kingside. } 8. Nbd2
Nbd7 9. e3 Bxf1 10. Nxf1 c5
{ with the idea ...c4 gives Black the upper hand. White has only weakened his position and wasted valuable tempi with b4-b5. }
