1. d4 Nf6 2. e3 g6 3. Bd3 { 3.Nf3  Bg7  transposes to theColle. } 3... Bg7 4.
f4
{ The Stonewall setup is completely ineffective versus the kingside fianchetto as White's light-squared bishop is biting on granite.   4.Nf3  transposes to theColle. }
4... d5 5. Nf3 c5 6. c3 Bf5
{ ensures White's light-squares will be critically weak after the bishop trade. }
7. Bxf5
{ 7.O-O  can simply be met with  7...Nbd7  8.Ne5  e6  N  improves over the game 1-0 @@StartBracket@@51@@EndBracket@@ Flores Guerrero,J @@StartBracket@@2345@@EndBracket@@-Petrov,M @@StartBracket@@2458@@EndBracket@@ Baku 2016 and gives Black the upper hand after  9.Bxf5  gxf5  10.Nd2  Rc8⩱ }
7... gxf5
{ Black's doubled f-pawns are an asset here. The f5 pawn takes control over the key e4 square and the f7 one can later be pushed to boot White's e5 knight. }
8. O-O Nbd7 9. Nbd2 e6 10. Ne5 h5
{ with the ideas ...h4 as well as ...Nxe5 followed by ...Ne4 give Black a sizeable advantage. White's position is full of light-squared weaknesses and the bishop on c1 is completely out of the game. }
