[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model games"]
[Black "0-1 (47) Norowitz,Y (2420)-Boyer,M (2302) Titled Tuesday 2020"]
[Result "*"]

{ The following is a model game in the Stonewall between IM Yaacov Norowitz and FM Mahel Boyer. Incidentally, Yaacov recommended the Stonewall in a Chessable course but got completely demolished by Boyer, who took full advantage of the downsides of this opening. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. e3 c5 3. c3 d5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. f4
{ The Stonewall system. White takes firm control over the e5 square with f2-f4. He wants to plant a knight on e5 and then start a kingside attack with Qe1-h4. However, I'm sure the bishop on c1 isn't too happy with the way White arranged his pawns. }
5... Bg4
{ is the most active position for the bishop, developing it outside the pawn chain. }
6. Nf3 e6 7. Nbd2 Bd6 8. O-O O-O 9. Qe1 cxd4
{ is a timely recapture as White's White's desirable recapture with exd4 is not available since the f4 pawn would then drop. }
10. cxd4
{ opens the c-file in Black's favor, which he's ready to exploit with ...Nb4 and ...Rc8 next. }
10... Nb4 11. Bb1 Rc8
{ This was all covered in the theoretical section of the course, specifically in the 5. f4 #2 variation in chapter 1. We are 11 moves into the game and Black is already clearly better, a great example of how poor the Stonewall is. }
12. Qd1 Qc7 { renewing the threat of Nc2. } 13. h3 Bxf3
{ Even stronger was  13...Bh5!  intending to meet  14.g4  with  14...Bg6  After the light-squared bishops are off the board, White will be riddled with light-square weaknesses. }
14. Nxf3 Nc2 15. Bxc2 Qxc2
{ Black exchanged off White's light-squared bishop, which was his only good piece. Next up is ...Ne4, exploiting the hole White created when he played 5. f4.  Similar positional ideas can be seen if Black plays the plan with ...b6 + ...Ba6, also trading off the light-squared bishops }
16. Bd2 Ne4 17. Bc3 Qxd1 18. Rfxd1 Nxc3 19. bxc3 Rxc3
{ Black is a pawn up, has the better pawn structure, the better minor piece and a 2 vs 1 on the queenside. You get the picture, Black is already winning. }
20. Kf2 Rfc8 21. Ke2 Rc2+ 22. Rd2 Bb4 23. Rxc2 Rxc2+ 24. Kf1
{ White's king is now cut off. } 24... Bc3 25. Rb1 b6 26. a4 Ra2
{ 26...f6!  followed by bringing the king to the center was even stronger. }
27. Rc1 Ra3 28. Ne5 f6 29. Nc6 Bd2
{ White's position now collapses. Once the e3 pawn drops, the entire pawn chain will be vulnerable. }
30. Rd1 Bxe3 31. g3 Rxa4 32. Ke2 Rc4 33. Nd8 Rxd4 34. Ra1 Re4 35. Kf3 a5
{ Black is four pawns up, two of which are connected passed pawns. He had no trouble bringing the point home. }
36. Nb7 Bc5 37. Nxc5 bxc5 38. Rxa5 c4 39. f5 exf5 40. Rxd5 g6 41. Rd7 h5 42.
Rc7 Rd4 43. h4 Rd3+ 44. Kf4 c3 45. Ra7 Rd4+ 46. Ke3 Rc4 47. Kd3 c2
{ was a nice way to end the game. White resigned. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model games"]
[Black "0-1 (51) Bromann,T (2384)-Gretarsson,H (2567) Reykjavik 2017"]
[Result "*"]

{ The following is a model game in the Pseudo Trompowsky between the danish IM Thorbjorn Bromann and the Icelandic GM Hjorvar Gretarsson. }
1. d4 d5 2. Bg5 f6 3. Bh4 Nh6 4. e3 Nf5 5. Bg3 h5 6. Be2 h4 7. Bh5+ Kd7 8. Bf4
g5 9. e4 dxe4 10. d5 gxf4
{ Stronger was  10...e6!  which was my recommendation in the3. Bh4 #5  variation in chapter 3. }
11. Bg4 Ke8 12. Bh5+ Kd7 13. Bg4 c6 { creating a square for the king on c7. }
14. Bxf5+ Kc7 15. Bxc8 Qxc8 16. Nc3 Qf5
{ is natural, bringing the queen out but Black had an even better option at his disposal.   Stronger was  16...e6!  17.dxc6   17.dxe6?!  Qxe6  18.Nge2  Bh6  19.O-O  Rd8  20.Qc1  Qe5−+  Nxc6  18.Qd2  e5∓ }
17. Qd4 { White clears the way for queenside castling but } 17... Bh6
{ puts an end to that plan. } 18. Rd1
{ 18.O-O-O??  runs into  18...f3+  19.Kb1  fxg2−+  when White's rook on h1 is trapped. }
18... Rd8 19. Nb5+
{ is a blunder.   19.Qc4  would have maintained the balance. } 19... cxb5 20.
Qc5+ { White gets a few checks in but after... } 20... Kd7 21. Qxb5+ Kc8 22.
Qc4+ { ...Black can now block the checks with } 22... Nc6
{ a move which I suspect White missed. } 23. dxc6
{ opens the d-file in Black's favor } 23... Rxd1+ 24. Kxd1 Kc7
{ And it turns out that White's king is the one in danger with ...Rd8 coming next. }
25. cxb7+ Kxb7 26. Qb4+ Ka6 27. Qa4+ Kb6 28. Qd4+
{ If  28.Qb4+  then  28...Qb5  29.Qd4+  Qc5  puts an end to the checks. } 28...
Qc5 29. Qxe4 Rd8+ { The rook and queen now coordinate against White's king }
30. Ke1 Qa5+ 31. c3 Qxa2
{ Equal material but not an equal position. White's king is in grave danger. }
32. Qb4+ Ka6
{ 32...Kc7  is the ruthless computer move. The point is that after  33.Qxe7+  Rd7  34.Qc5+  Kd8  White has run out of checks and his king is too exposed. Black is in fact threatening checkmate in three with  35.--  Qb1+  36.Ke2  Qd1 }
33. Qa3+ Qxa3 34. bxa3 Rb8
{ White managed to exchange the queens but is completely undeveloped. } 35. Ke2
Rb1
{ put White under a devastating pin. White cannot bring his knight and rook into the game while Black can simply collect White's queenside pawns and then promote the a-pawn. Black had no trouble converting. }
36. Kf3 Kb5 37. Kg4 a5 38. Kxh4 a4 39. Kh5 f3 40. gxf3 Bd2 41. Kg4 Bxc3 42. h4
Kc4 43. Kf5 Kb3 44. f4 Re1 45. h5 Kxa3 46. h6 Kb2 47. f3 Kb3 48. Kg6 f5 49. h7
Bh8 50. Kxf5 a3 51. Rh6
{ White resigned as after  51.Rh6  e6+  52.Kg4  drops the knight with check.   52.Rxe6  Rxe6  53.Kxe6  a2−+  when Black promotes  52...Rxg1+  53.Kh5  a2  and White will soon be mated. }
