[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model games"]
[Black "0-1 (40) Rapport,R (2731)-Giri,A (2783) Wijk aan Zee 2019"]
[Result "*"]

{ The following is a model game in the Jobava Attack between super-GMs Richard Rapport and Anish Giri from the 2019 Tata Steel tournament. }
1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bf4 e6 4. Nb5 Na6 5. e3 Be7 6. Nf3 O-O 7. Bd3 c6 8. Nc3
{ This was all covered in the theoretical section of the course, specifically in the4. Nb5 #1 in chapter 6. There I recommended 8...c5, improving over Anish's choice of }
8... Nb4 { immediately going after White's light-squared bishop. } 9. h3 Nxd3+
10. cxd3 b6
{ preparing to fianchetto the light-squared bishop. Black can then follow up with ...Rc8 to prepare the ...c5 break. }
11. O-O Bb7 12. Qb3 Nd7
{ The knight was not doing much on f6 so Anish places it on d7, where it controls the e5 square and supports the ...c5 break. Additionally, it covers the b6 pawn should Black decide to push ahead with ...a5 instead. }
13. Rfe1 Rc8 14. Rac1 h6 15. Bg3 a5
{ with the idea ...Ba6 to attack White's weak pawn on d3. } 16. Na4 Ba6 17. Ne5
Nxe5 18. Bxe5 Bb5 { activating the bishop and covering the b6 pawn. } 19. Re2
Re8 20. Rec2 Bf8
{ is another small improvement. The bishop is better placed on f8 than on e7 where it doesn't obstruct the rook on e8. }
21. Nxb6 { is a mistake that ended up costing White the game. } 21... Qxb6 22.
a4 Ra8 23. g4 Qd8
{ unpinning. Black is now ready to drop back the bishop to a6 so } 24. axb5
{ is forced } 24... a4 25. Qc3 cxb5
{ Black is now a effectively pawn up @@StartBracket@@White's doubled d-pawns are useless@@EndBracket@@. Not only that, he can easily create a passed pawn on the queenside. }
26. Qc6 b4 27. Bc7 Qg5 28. f4
{ further weakens White's kingside, but his position was already difficult. }
28... Qg6 29. e4 h5
{ is a logical move, undermining the g4 pawn.   Even stronger was  29...Qf6  The double-attack on the d4 and f4 pawns forces  30.Be5  when  Qd8−+  followed by ...b3 and ...a3 is decisive. }
30. g5 h4 31. Kf2 a3 { creates a passed pawn on the a-file. } 32. b3 Rec8 33.
Qb7 dxe4 34. dxe4 f6
{ Not only does Black have a protected passed pawn on a3, but White's king is also very exposed. }
35. Be5 Rxc2+ 36. Rxc2 Re8 37. gxf6 gxf6 38. Kf1
{ threatening Rg2, which Anish readily neutralized with } 38... Re7 39. Qc6 Rg7
40. Qxe6+ Kh7
{ White resigned as there is no way to both stop ...Qg1+ and save the bishop on e5. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
