[White "Model games"]
[Black "0-1 (33) Abasov,N (2632)-Dominguez Perez,L (2763) Khanty-Mansiysk 2019"]
[Result "*"]

{ The following is a model game in the London system between GM Nijat Abasov and super-GM Leinier Dominguez from the 2019 FIDE World Cup. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 d5 3. e3 e6 4. Nf3 Bd6
{ immediately fighting for the e5 square and clearing the way for ...O-O. } 5.
Bg3 O-O 6. Nbd2 c5 7. c3 Qc7
{ Next up is ...Nd7 to take full control over the e5 square. } 8. Bd3 Nbd7
{ Lenier went for our ideal setup and is now ready to break in the center with ...e5. }
9. Qe2 e5
{ Once Black achieves this break he has comfortably equalized. Not only that, Black can start thinking about playing for an advantage since he has a space advantage. }
10. dxe5 Nxe5 11. Nxe5 Bxe5
{ This was all covered in the theoretical section of the course, specifically in the5. Bg3 #19 variation in chapter 7. }
12. Bh4 Bg4 { develops the bishop with tempo. } 13. Nf3 Ne4
{ 13...d4!?  was very interesting, trying to blast open the center before White has castled. For example  14.exd4  cxd4  15.cxd4  Bxd4  16.O-O  Rfe8=  is very comfortable. }
14. h3 Be6 15. Nxe5 Qxe5 16. f4 Qc7 17. g4
{ is uncalled for. Black has no weaknesses on the kingside and is ahead in development so White's attack is unsound. }
17... f6 18. Rg1 Bf7 { clears the e-file for Black's rooks. } 19. Bxe4
{ 19.g5  can simply be bypassed with  19...f5  when White has no way of continuing the attack. }
19... dxe4 20. g5 f5 21. g6
{ desperately trying to open the kingside was met with the cool } 21... hxg6
22. Rd1 a5 { prepares to lift the rook along the 6th rank. } 23. Kf2 Ra6 24.
Rd2 Bxa2
{ picks up another pawn. White is now two pawns down and has no attack whatsoever. }
25. Rgd1 Be6 { takes control over the key d7 square. } 26. Kg3 Qf7
{ with the idea ...Bc4. } 27. Rd8 Ra8 28. Rxf8+ Rxf8 29. Rd6 Bc4 30. Qd1 Bd3
{ cuts the communication between the queen an rook. } 31. Qa4
{ blunders the game away.   Better was  31.Bd8  going after Black's queenside pawns. }
31... g5
{ is a fantastic breakthrough, which White surely missed. Next up is ...Qh5 when White's king is in big trouble. }
32. fxg5 { 32.Bxg5  Qh5  followed by ...Qf3 is lights out. } 32... f4+ 33. Kh2
{ 33.exf4  leads to a forced mate in four with  33...Qxf4+  34.Kg2  Qd2+  35.Bf2  Rxf2+  36.Kg3   36.Kg1  Qe1  Qf4 }
33... Qh5
{ threatens both ...Qxh4 and ...Qe2+. White is completely busted and so resigned. }
*

[Event "?"]
