[White "Model games"]
[Black "0-1 (32) Kvakovszky,G (2025)-Mishra,A (2387) Saint Louis 2019"]
[Result "*"]

{ The following is a model game in the Blackmar-Diemer Gambit from the 2019 Spice Cup Open. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3
{ Threatens to expand in the center with e2-e4, which we immediately stop with }
2... d5 3. e4 dxe4 4. f3 exf3 5. Qxf3 Qxd4 6. Be3 Qg4 7. Qf2 Qf5 8. Qd2 e6 9.
O-O-O Be7 10. Nb5 Na6 11. Bd3
{ This was all covered in the theoretical section of the course, specifically in the3. Nc3 4. f3 5. Qxf3 #2 variation in chapter 9. }
11... Qd5
{ In the aforementioned line, I recommended the novel  11...Qg4  which gives Black the extra possibility of proposing a queen exchange with ...Qb4. }
12. c4 Qd8 13. Qe2 c6 { knocks White's knight back. } 14. Nc3 Bd7
{ Even stronger was  14...Qc7  with ideas of ...e5 and even ...b5. For example  15.g4  b5  16.cxb5  Nb4  17.bxc6  Nxd3+  18.Qxd3  Qxc6  19.Nge2  Ba6−+  followed by ...O-O gives Black a decisive advantage. Not only is Black a pawn up but the two bishops are also incredibly strong. }
15. Bb1 Qa5 { Clearing the way for queenside castling. } 16. Nf3 O-O-O 17. Bf4
Bb4 18. Be5 Ng4 19. Bd4 c5
{ is a good move but Black had an even better option at his disposal.   19...e5!  would have won on the spot as  20.Bg1   20.Bxa7  Bxc3  21.bxc3  b6  traps White's bishop.  20...Bxc3  21.bxc3  Be6−+  is lights out. The pawn on c3 is hanging and ...Qa3 and ...Rxd1 followed by ...Rd8 are big threats. }
20. Bxg7 Rhg8 21. Be5 f6
{ White's dark-squared bishop cannot maintain protection of the knight on c3 so White decided to sacrifice it with }
22. Nb5
{ going after the a7 pawn.   22.Bg3  Bxc3  23.bxc3  Qxc3+  is disastrous for White. For example  24.Qc2  Qxc2+  25.Bxc2  Ne3  will pick up yet another pawn when Black will be three pawns up. }
22... Nxe5 23. Nxa7+ Kb8 24. Nxe5 fxe5 25. Nb5 Bxb5 26. cxb5 Nc7
{ Black is a piece up and the b5 pawn is about to drop. } 27. Bd3
{ covers b5 but loses the a2 pawn. } 27... Qxa2 28. Bb1 Qa5 29. Rhf1 Nxb5 30.
Bxh7 Qa1+ 31. Bb1 Nc3 { is a nice way to end the game! } 32. bxc3 Ba3+
{ White resigned as  32...Ba3+  33.Kc2  Qb2  is checkmate! } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model games"]
[Black "0-1 (68) Jones,G (2665)-Meier,G (2646) Tromsoe 2014"]
[Result "*"]

{ The following is a model game between GM Gawain Jones and Georg Meier from the 2014 Tromso Olympiad. It started out as Trompowsky but then transposed into a variation of the Torre. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 d5 3. e3 e6 4. Nd2 c5 5. c3 Bd6 6. Ngf3 h6 7. Bh4 Nbd7 8. Bd3
O-O 9. O-O b6 10. e4 cxd4 11. Bxf6 Qxf6 12. cxd4 dxe4 13. Bxe4
{ Worse is  13.Nxe4  Qe7  14.Nxd6  Qxd6⩱  when White has no compensation for the isolated d-pawn. }
13... Rb8 14. Nc4 Qe7 15. Nxd6 Qxd6 16. Rc1 Bb7
{ This was all covered in the theoretical section of the course, specifically in the3. c3 #9 in chapter 14.  There I wrote that Black had comfortably equalized and White had little to show for the isolated pawn on d4. Meier exploits this weakness in textbook style. }
17. Bxb7 Rxb7 18. Qc2
{ 18.Rc4  followed by Qc2 was a better way of doubling on the c-file.  18...Nf6  19.Qc2  when the queen is better placed behind the rook than in front of it. }
18... Nf6 19. Qc6 Qe7
{ There was of course nothing wrong with  19...Qxc6  20.Rxc6  but there's no need to improve the position of White's rook. }
20. Qb5 Rc7
{ Activating the rook. Black is ready to take over the c-file with ...Rfc8. }
21. Qa6 Qd7 22. Rxc7 Qxc7 23. a3 Rc8
{ Black has full control of the open c-file and can target the isolated d4 pawn. While White should be able to hold this position, Meier was able to convert this small advantage with excellent technique and a lot of patience. }
24. h3 Qb8 25. Qe2 Qf4 26. Re1 Nd5 27. Qb5 Qc7 28. Qa6 Qb8 29. Qe2 Rc7 30. Ne5
Qb7 31. Qe4 Qc8 32. Qf3 Qd8 33. g3 Nf6 34. Rd1
{ Black didn't make much progress over the last few moves so he decides to exchange off the queens with }
34... Qd5 35. Qxd5 Nxd5 36. Rd2 f6 37. Ng4 Kf7 38. Ne3 Nxe3 39. fxe3 Rc1+ 40.
Kf2
{ We've reached a rook endgame that is a bit unpleasant for White. However, he should be able to hold with accurate play. }
40... h5 41. h4 Ke7 42. e4 Kd6
{ Notice how Black first centralized the king before moving any of his kingside pawns. }
43. Kf3 g6 44. Kf4 Rf1+ 45. Ke3 f5 46. e5+
{ is a big mistake as it leaves White with a big target on d4.   Instead, White should have exchanged pawns with  46.exf5  gxf5  47.Rc2  when Black will have a very hard time making progress. For example, trying to activate the king with  47...Re1+  48.Kf3  Kd5  allows  49.Rc7  which gives White enough counterplay. }
46... Kd5 47. Rc2 Re1+ 48. Kf4 Re4+ 49. Kg5 Rg4+
{ is winning but Black had an even quicker way to convert.   49...Kxd4  was even stronger.  50.Kxg6  Kxe5  51.Kxh5  Rg4−+  White's king is cut off and there's no stopping the e5 pawn. }
50. Kf6 f4 51. gxf4 Rxf4+ 52. Kxg6 Rxh4 53. Rc7 Rxd4 54. Rxa7 h4 55. Kf6 Rf4+
56. Kg5 Kxe5
{ Black had two passed pawns and had little trouble bringing the point home. }
57. Rh7 Ke4 58. Rh6 e5 59. Re6 Kf3 60. Rxe5 h3 61. Rb5 Kg3 62. Rb3+ Rf3 63.
Rxb6 h2 64. Rh6 Kg2 65. Kg4 Rb3 66. Kf4 h1=Q 67. Rxh1 Kxh1 68. Ke5 Rxb2
{ White resigned as he is not in time to defend let alone promote the a-pawn. For example  9.Kd4  Ra2  70.Kc3  Rxa3+  picks it up. }
