[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model games"]
[Black "0-1 (26) Slavin,A (2417)-Adams,M (2706) Canterbury 2010"]
[Result "*"]

{ The following is a model game in the 1...Nf6 2...e6 Colle between IM Alexey Slavin and GM Michael Adams. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. e3
{ The Colle system, characterized by the moves 2. Nf3 and 3. e3, doesn't put any pressure on the center and restricts White's dark-squared bishop.  It's a popular system at the club level mainly because it can be learned very quickly and is of very low maintenance.   White can set up a solid triangle formation with pawns d4, c3 and e3 and play the same developing moves almost irrespective of what Black does. White's setup is definitely solid but also very unambitious. }
3... b6 4. Bd3 Bb7 5. O-O d5 6. Ne5 Bd6 7. f4 O-O 8. Nd2 c5 9. b3 b5 10. c3 b4
11. cxb4 cxd4 12. exd4 Bxb4 13. Bb2 Nc6 14. Qe2
{ This was all covered in the theoretical section of the course, specifically in the6. Ne5 #3 variation in chapter 13. }
14... Qb6
{ is logical pressuring the d4 pawn.   Even better is  14...Bd6  which was my recommendation in the aforementioned trainable line, making way for ...Nb4. }
15. Ndf3 Bd6 { makes way for ...Nb4. } 16. a3
{ White prevents ...Nb4 but weakens the b3 pawn, which is now a big target. }
16... a5
{ A very strong move, stopping ...b4 and thus ensuring the b3 pawn will always be weak.   16...Qxb3  runs into  17.Rab1  when Black is exposed along the b-file. For example  17...Qb6  18.Rfc1  18...Rac8  19.Bc3  Qc7  20.Be1=∞  gives White decent compensation for the pawn. White has strong pressure along the b and c-files. }
17. Rac1 Bxe5 18. fxe5 Ne4 19. Bxe4 dxe4 20. Ng5
{ blunders the d4 pawn.  The point behind Adam's ...Ne4 was that   20.Qxe4  can be met with  20...Ne7  heading to f5 to pressure the d4 pawn. For example  21.Qe3  Nf5  22.Qd2  Qxb3∓  is equal material but not an equal position. Black's light-squared bishop is very active while White's dark-squared bishop is relegated to the defense of the d4 pawn. }
20... Nxd4 21. Bxd4 Qxd4+ 22. Kh1
{ White would like to get Qh5 in but Adams immediately puts a stop to that with }
22... h6 23. Nxf7 { is desperation. } 23... Rxf7 24. Rxf7 Kxf7 25. Rc7+ Kg8 26.
Rxb7 Qa1+ { White resigned as  26...Qa1+  27.Qd1  Qxd1  is checkmate } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model games"]
[Black "0-1 (30) Krasenkow,M (2651)-Wojtaszek,R (2640) Lublin 2009"]
[Result "*"]

{ The following is a model game in the 1...Nf6 2...e6 Torre between two strong Polish GMs, Michal Krasenkow with White and Radoslaw Wojtaszek with the Black pieces. }
1. d4 e6 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3
{ The Colle system, characterized by the moves 2. Nf3 and 3. e3, doesn't put any pressure on the center and restricts White's dark-squared bishop.  It's a popular system at the club level mainly because it can be learned very quickly and is of very low maintenance.   White can set up a solid triangle formation with pawns d4, c3 and e3 and play the same developing moves almost irrespective of what Black does. White's setup is definitely solid but also very unambitious. }
3... b6 4. Bd3 Bb7 5. O-O d5 6. b3 Bd6 7. Bb2 O-O 8. c4 Nbd7 9. Nc3 a6 10. Rc1
Qe7 11. cxd5 exd5 12. Ne2 Ne4 13. Ng3 f5 14. Re1
{ This was all covered in the theoretical section of the course, specifically in the6. b3 #8 variation in chapter 13. }
14... g6
{ I prefer  14...c6  which keeps the 6th rank clear, allowing us to lift a rook with ...Rf6-h6 later on. }
15. Re2 c5
{ Black is playing on both sides of the board but there was no need to open the c-file.   Better was  15...c6  to shut down play along the c-file.  16.Rec2  followed by  16...a5⩱  which stops any play on the queenside. Black can now concentrate on the kingside while White has no active plan. }
16. Rec2 Ndf6 { allows White to jump into e5 with } 17. Ne5 cxd4 18. exd4
{ We can now see why 15...c5 was inaccurate. White's rooks are very active on the c-file and Black in fact decided to neutralize this pressure with }
18... Rac8
{ However, it'll be hard for Black to create any real threats on the kingside if he has to exchange all the rooks }
19. Nf1 Rxc2 20. Rxc2 Rc8 21. Rxc8+ Bxc8 22. f3
{ is a big mistake.   Better was  22.Qc1  activating the queen.  22...Qc7   22...Bb7  runs into  23.f3  Nc5  24.dxc5  Bxe5  25.cxb6⩲  when White has the upper hand/  23.Qxc7  Bxc7  24.Ne3=  should result in a draw. }
22... Bxe5
{ is an in-between move White surely misassessed. A forced sequence now follows }
23. fxe4 fxe4 24. Bxa6 Bxh2+ 25. Nxh2 Bxa6
{ Black is a pawn up and has a passed e-pawn. However, the presence of opposite colored bishops gives White decent drawing chances. }
26. Ng4
{ is a mistake.   Better was  26.Qc1  with the idea Qc6 to create counterplay. }
26... Nh5 { heading to f4. } 27. Nh6+ Kh8 28. Bc3
{ blunders the game away.   It still wasn't too late for  28.Qc1  Ng3  29.Kf2  Ne2  and now  30.Qg5!  forces the queens of the board.  30...Qxg5  31.Nf7+  Kg7  32.Nxg5  Nf4  Black is still clearly for choice in this endgame but White can play on. }
28... Nf4 { Now there's no stopping ...Ne2+. White's king is in grave danger. }
29. Be1 Ne2+ 30. Kh1 Qf6
{ White had no good way of stopping ...Qf1+ and so he resigned.   30...Qf6  31.Bd2  covers the f1 square but loses control over h4 when  31...Qh4  is checkmate. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model games"]
[Black "0-1 (40) Suarez Garcia,C (2472)-Gonzalez de la Torre,S (2448) Elgoibar 2017"]
[Result "*"]

{ The following is a model game in the Trompowsky between two Spanish IMs, Carlos Suarez Garcia with the White pieces and Santiago Gonzalez de la Torre with Black. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 d5 3. Bxf6 exf6 4. e3 Bd6 5. g3 c6 6. Nd2 Nd7 7. Bg2 f5 8. Ne2
Nf6 9. O-O h5 { started a big attack. } 10. c4 dxc4 11. Nxc4 Bc7
{ Preserving the dark-squared bishop, a move which Kamil Plitcha did not consider in his Chessable course on the Trompowsky! }
12. Nc3 Be6 { stops White from breaking with d5. } 13. Qd3 h4
{ This was all covered in the theoretical section of the course, specifically in the5. g3 #4 variation in chapter 11. }
14. Rad1 hxg3 15. hxg3 Qe7
{ clearing the way for ...Rd8. Notice how Black improves all of his pieces before carrying on with his attack. }
16. Qe2 Rd8 17. Ne5 O-O
{ Even stronger was  17...g5!  followed by ...Kf8-g7, which would have maintained the rook on the open h-file.  18.Rfe1  Kf8 }
18. Nd3 Bc8 19. Rfe1 Rfe8 { Black is now fully centralized. } 20. Nc5 Ng4
{ making way for ...Qg5-h5. } 21. Qf3 Qg5 22. d5
{ White is desperately trying to create some counterplay in the center but Black is perfectly placed to meet this. }
22... cxd5
{ is a good move but Black had an even better option available.   22...b6!  was much stronger. After  23.Nd3  Qh5−+  ...Qh2 and ...Ba6 are coming next with a decisive attack. }
23. Nxd5 Bd6 24. Nd3 Qh6 25. e4 Qh2+ 26. Kf1 Qh5 { threatening ...Nh2+. } 27.
Kg1 fxe4 28. Rxe4 Bf5
{ preparing to eliminate the knight on d3, which is the main defender of the f2 pawn. }
29. Rxe8+ Rxe8 30. Nc3 Bxd3 31. Qxd3 Bc5 { White has big problems on f2. } 32.
Qd7
{ 32.Ne4  runs into  32...Bxf2+!  33.Nxf2  Qh2+  34.Kf1  Ne3+  when White's position collapses. }
32... Re6
{ Simple and effective.   Even stronger was  32...Bxf2+  33.Kf1  f5  34.Bd5+  Kh7−+  ...Ne3+ is coming next. White is busted. }
33. Qd8+ Kh7 34. Ne4 Bxf2+ { finishes White off. } 35. Kf1
{ 35.Nxf2  runs into  35...Qh2+  36.Kf1  Ne3+  37.Ke2  Nxd1+  38.Kd2  Qxg2−+  is curtains. }
35... Bb6 36. Ng5+ { picks up an exchange but ...Ne3+ is also coming. } 36...
Kg6 37. Nxe6 Ne3+ 38. Kg1 Qxd1+ 39. Qxd1 Nxd1+ { is check. } 40. Nd4
{ White resigned as  40.Nd4  Bxd4+  leaves Black with an extra piece. } *

