[Result "*"]

{ The following is a model game in the Fianchetto variation of the London system between GM Alex Bachmann and GM Rameshbabu Praggnanandhaa from the 2016 Isle of Man tournament. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Qd2 Bg7 5. Bh6 O-O 6. Bxg7 Kxg7 7. O-O-O c5 8.
e3 Nc6 9. f3 c4 10. e4 { Black now started a vicious attack with } 10... b5 11.
exd5 { trying to create counterplay in the center } 11... Nb4
{ is a strong reply. The idea is to target the c2 pawn with ...Bf5. } 12. Nxb5
{ It not only opens the b-file but allows } 12... Nxa2+ 13. Kb1 Qxd5
{ A strong counterblow, ignoring the attack on the knight on a2 and instead going after White's knight on b5. }
14. Na3 { 14.Kxa2??  loses the queen to the discovery  14...c3+−+ } 14... c3
{ blasts open the b-file } 15. bxc3 Rb8+ 16. Ka1 Qa5 17. Kxa2 Nd5
{ Threatens ...Nxc3+ followed by ...Qxa3. } 18. Ne2 Be6
{ White resigned as Black has a forced mate in 6.   18...Be6  19.c4  Nb4+  20.Qxb4  Qxb4  21.Rb1  Bxc4+  22.Rb3  Bxb3+  23.Kb2  Ba4+  24.Kc1  Qe1  It's not every day you see a 2600+ GM go down in 16 moves! }
